<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, May 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White House E-mail Furor Rages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House is raising the possibility it may invoke
executive privilege to keep Congress from seeing some documents in the furor
over missing e-mails under subpoena in investigations ranging from Whitewater to
impeachment, documents disclosed Monday. The White House sent the House
Government Reform Committee a one-page list of documents it is not turning over
under subpoena because of executive privilege and attorney-client
confidentiality. Among documents on the list, which was obtained by The
Associated Press, are notes by White House lawyers involving discussions they
had with computer experts about the e-mails.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Reports on World Terrorism
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three countries courted by the United States for a better
relationship -- Iran, Syria and North Korea -- were again branded as sponsors of
terrorism by the State Department today along with Cuba, Iraq, Libya and Sudan.
A yearly report showed a shift in concern from the Middle East to South Asia,
where Afghanistan is a favorite haven for terrorists and Pakistan has backed
groups that engage in violence in Kashmir.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
ABC-TV Is Off Some Cable Systems
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In an escalating corporate dispute, ABC-TV was blacked out
in the homes of 3.5 million Time Warner cable customers around the country
Monday -- just as the ratings ''sweeps'' period was beginning. The Walt Disney
Co., ABC's corporate parent, is fighting over how much money Time Warner must
compensate Disney for the right to carry some of its cable channels. The
affected customers were in seven markets served by ABC-owned television
stations. About 1.5 million were in the New York City area, 665,000 in Houston
and 440,000 in Raleigh-Durham, N.C.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Castro Leads May Day Parade
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Fidel Castro joined the annual May Day parade today for the
first time in years and ended a speech with a cell phone call to Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, urging him to continue his fight to bring his refugee son, Elian, home
to Cuba. Castro led hundreds of thousands of Cubans from Havana's Plaza of the
Revolution to the U.S. Interests Section. ''Fidel! Fidel!'' chanted the crowd in
the annual march that traditionally involves workers. In a speech, Castro
praised Cubans for their tenacity.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Decried on Social Security
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- GOP presidential campaigner George W. Bush's plan for
Social Security was dismissed today by the White House as set ''in a world where
budgets don't exist.'' Bush is considering proposing -- as Republicans in
Congress have -- a plan through which workers could invest a portion of their
Social Security payroll taxes in the stock market. White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart said Bush needed to provide more details on his proposal and ''stop
talking about campaign promises in a vacuum.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Expects Palestinian State
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EILAT, Israel (AP) -- Trying to improve the climate in peace talks, Israeli
officials said Monday they've resigned themselves to Palestinian statehood, and
the Palestinians acknowledged Israel's pain on Holocaust Remembrance Day. But
negotiators reported little progress and awaited the arrival of a U.S. mediator
Tuesday to help draft an outline of a final peace treaty. Israeli officials said
they would not oppose a Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, but
said the Palestinians should accept that some Jewish settlements there will
become part of Israel.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Higher at Midday
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average on Tuesday rose 77.81 points to
18,480.89 points at the end of the morning session. Financial markets in Tokyo
will be closed Wednesday through Friday because of national holidays. The
markets will reopen Monday, May 8. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average rose 77.87 points to close at 10,811.78 on Monday. The technology-heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 97.42 to close at 3,958.08.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Devils Defeat Maple Leafs 5-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Martin Brodeur withstood Toronto's best period
of the series and went on to stop 22 shots in leading the Devils to a 5-1
victory over the Toronto Maple Leafs on Monday night. Jason Arnott, Scott Gomez,
Patrik Elias, Petr Sykora and Alexander Mogilny scored as the Devils took a 2-1
lead in the best-of-seven Eastern Conference semifinal series. Elias also had
two assists as New Jersey dominated for the third straight game. New Jersey
could easily have a 3-0 lead if Curtis Joseph hadn't stolen the opening game
with a 32-save performance in a 2-1 Toronto victory.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON
</SUBHEAD>
