<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- Two Camden County men were arrested Monday
night, charged in the murder-for-hire of the wife of a prominent
Cherry Hill rabbi, the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Jenoff, 54, of Collingswood, and Paul M. Daniels, 26, of
Pennsauken, were charged with murder and conspiracy to commit
murder in connection with the killing of Carol Neulander,
Prosecutor Lee Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, 52, was bludgeoned to death on Nov. 1, 1994, in her
Cherry Hill home. Investigators say she was killed by a hit man
posing as a deliveryman.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Rabbi Fred J. Neulander, found her body when he
returned from Congregation M'Kor Shalom synagogue. Her purse was
missing, but no other valuables were touched.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Neulander had been considered the sole suspect in his
wife's killing. He was indicted in January 1999 on charges of
accomplice murder and conspiracy to commit murder. He is free on
bail awaiting his trial, which is scheduled to begin in June.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor's spokesman Greg Reinert said Jenoff is a friend of
the rabbi. A private investigator, he was hired by Neulander to
work on the case. Daniels was ''known to Jenoff,'' Reinert said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if officials believe Neulander hired the hit men,
Reinert said he could not comment on Neulander's case because it is
pending.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Wixted and Jeffrey Zucker, Neulander's attorneys, said
the rabbi was shocked when he learned of the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   They said Jenoff had repeatedly said under oath that Neulander
was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he's changed his tune, we'll have to wait and see why,''
Wixted told FOX-TV in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''From the very beginning of this, he's always been on the
rabbi's side and always said he had nothing to do with it,'' Zucker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker said a hearing on the case is scheduled for May 9 with
Superior Court Judge Linda G. Rosenzweig.
</P>
<P>
   ''My belief is we should (meet) with the judge to get an idea of
where we stand with respect to the trial,'' Zucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff's attorney, Francis J. Hartman, told the Courier-Post of
Cherry Hill for Tuesday's editions that his client contacted
Solomon and arranged to meet him and an investigator Friday. At
that meeting, Jenoff ''told them he was the intermediary between
the rabbi and someone who would kill his wife,'' Hartman said.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman said Jenoff recruited Daniels for the job. He said he
did not know if Jenoff was at the Neulander home the night of the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman said Jenoff called the prosecutor because he felt
remorse about Carol Neulander's death. The attorney said his client
had hoped for a plea agreement or even immunity in exchange for his
cooperation, but Solomon was ''not hearing anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff and Daniels were scheduled to be arraigned Tuesday in
state Superior Court in Camden.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have said Neulander had his wife of 29 years killed
so that he could continue his extramarital affair with Philadelphia
radio personality Elaine Soncini.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Neulander thought divorce would jeopardize his
position as senior rabbi at the synagogue, which he founded with
his wife in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Soncini admitted having a two-year affair with Neulander that
ended shortly after his wife's killing. She has not been charged
with any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Soncini has told authorities that Neulander told her that their
problem would be solved by December 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander stepped down from his synagogue post in February 1995
after reports of his affairs with two congregants. He was later
suspended by a rabbinical panel.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff and Daniels were being in the held Camden County Jail on
Monday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
