<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney general says bottle bill should be expanded  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- New York's ''bottle law'' should also impose
a 5-cent deposit on cans and bottles containing three
ever-more-popular beverages: spring water, sports drinks and juice,
according to state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said the popularity of the three drinks was not
envisioned in 1982, when the redeemable container law was enacted
to encourage the recycling of cans and bottles containing beer and
carbonated drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer also said Monday the state's requirement that
municipalities recycle must be shored up and he threatened to sue
the city of Amsterdam, in Montgomery County, in a month if it does
not reinstitute the recycling program it suspended as of Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Procopio, co-founder of the state Bottle and Can
Redemption Association and owner of a Syracuse redemption center,
said excluding non-carbonated drinks from the bottle law showed a
lack of foresight by legislators about future beverage-consumption
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   He said it is estimated that every person in New York now
consumes about 125 bottles and cans containing non-carbonated
beverages a year.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates say it is more efficient to get those containers
recycled by requiring deposits on them rather than having residents
and waste haulers weed the containers out of the waste stream.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer also proposed a bill to close what he said is a loophole
in the state's mandatory recycling law, which dates to 1988. That
law said every community must have a local recycling program in
place by 1992, but it created a dodge of sorts by saying those
localities only had to recycle if it is economically feasible to
local governments.
</P>
<P>
   With prices falling for may kinds of recyclable materials,
Spitzer said his office is now investigating numerous instances
where glass, plastic, newsprint and other recyclables are being
dumped in landfills.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's proposal would clarify that recyclables cannot be
dumped in landfills or incinerators.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general said he has given city of Amsterdam
officials until June 1 to make a ''reasonable and forthright''
effort to reinstitute a recycling program in that city about 30
miles west of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Amsterdam officials temporarily suspended the city's recycling
program starting Jan. 1. In March, its common council rejected all
bids received from companies interested in winning a new contract,
saying they were too expensive. The lowest bid was $188,000 for one
year, which is about double what the city was paying its old
recycler.
</P>
<P>
   Amsterdam terminated its contract with County Waste and
Recycling Services Inc. last year after receiving complaints that
glass, cans and other recyclables were being commingled with
non-recyclables and dumped in a landfill.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said he knew of no other instance where a municipality
has been sued for failing to recycle. Amsterdam was the only
locality in the state refusing to do so, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no doubt that we will win,'' Spitzer said. ''I am not
saying this as a threat to the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Amsterdam Deputy Mayor Ray Halgas said the city has worked hard
to gather bids on a new recycling program and to explore other
options. A new round of bids is due back on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have covered all the bases. We haven't let anything go,''
Halgas said. ''I know I am doing what I was elected to do by the
people in the city of Amsterdam. We could have just said, 'Hey,
it's 200 grand, let's just do it and let the people of Amsterdam
pay for it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Halgas said a $188,000 recycling bill on the city was akin to
the state imposing an ''unfunded mandate'' on the locality.
Amsterdam officials have called for months for the state to provide
funds to help pay for its recycling program.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said there is money available to help communities pay
for recycling through the state's 1996 environmental bond act and
other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Many municipalities and waste haulers have complained that
sinking prices have made recycling unprofitable. Spitzer said
recycling can still make money if done right, and he predicted that
the impending closure of New York City's Fresh Kills landfill in
December 2001 will change the economics of the whole recycling
industry in New York state to make the selling of recyclable
materials more lucrative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
