<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate approves bill undoing pollution credit advantages  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- New York utilities would lose any incentive
to sell pollution credits in the states chiefly blamed for creating
acid rain under a bill headed to Gov. George Pataki's desk.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate Monday gave final passage to the measure
designed to keep the pollution credits earned in New York from
being converted into emissions and dumped back on the state through
utilities and companies in 14 Southern and Midwestern states.
</P>
<P>
   ''We aren't talking about whether a few more lakes will die,''
said Timothy Burke, head of the Adirondack Council. ''We are
talking about saving the Adirondacks from ecological destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The sponsor of the bill in the Senate, Nassau County Republican
Carl Marcellino, said the measure will send a message to the
federal government that the system of selling pollution credits is
harming Northeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   More than 700,000 credits -- each representing the right to emit
one ton of sulfur dioxide -- have been accumulated by New York
utilities. The credits generally sell for between $100 and $140 on
the open market.
</P>
<P>
   New York utilities qualify for about 300,000 new credits each
year, Marcellino said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would create a mechanism for the state Public
Service Commission to step forward when New York utilities sell a
credit in one of the proscribed states. The amount of the profit
would be diverted from the utility and put into a special state
account to fund alternative energy projects.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would apply to the sale of pollution credits by New
York utilities in New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Maryland, Delaware,
Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, West Virginia, Ohio, Michigan,
Illinois, Kentucky, Indiana and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Marcellino said he expected Pataki to sign the bill, which was
approved 59-0 Monday, into law. It passed in the state Assembly in
March.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Richard Dollinger, D-Rochester, said the state should
prevent its utilities from selling the credits anywhere by buying
all outstanding and future credits itself.
</P>
<P>
   ''The better thing to do is to put our money where our mouth is
... so that no one in this state, on this planet, can run into the
problems that we have had,'' Dollinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Marcellino said the state could not afford to spend that kind of
money.
</P>
<P>
   The state Energy Association, which represents New York's
private utilities, predicted the measure would harm the economy by
raising the cost of generating electricity in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The trade organization also said utilities will find lower
prices for their credits when they try to sell them among a limited
number of states. There is also no conclusive evidence, the Energy
Association said, that not selling the credits in the 14 states
will reduce acid emissions being absorbed by the Adirondacks or
other parts of New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Acid rain is blamed on utilities which burn high-sulfur fuel.
The pollution is carried eastward and northward by the jet stream
and falls clinging to drops of rain or flakes of snow in the
Northeast. It is blamed for biologically ''killing'' hundreds of
lakes in New York by destroying their acidic balance.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative passage of the bill ended a running battle between
the state Assembly and Senate which became particularly sharp last
summer. At that time, the two chambers could not agree whether the
bill should apply to new pollution credits or to the more than
700,000 credits already accumulated by New York utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Richard Brodsky, D-Westchester, said the bill is
''infinitely improved'' over the prospective bill the Senate
favored because it applied to the old credits as well as new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would not fold on the issue of the over 700,000 credits
which might have come back,'' Brodsky said Monday. ''And this is
not chopped liver.''
</P>
<P>
   Several environmental groups, including the Adirondack Council,
angered Brodsky by siding with the Senate in the dispute last
summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
