<HEADLINE> State's sex-offender registry being challenged this week  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The sex-offender registry established by New
York state's version of Megan's Law will be under judicial scrutiny
this week by members of the state's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals will hear oral arguments in two cases
involving offenders who are challenging their required inclusion on
the sex-crime registry.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Megan's Law took effect in 1996, thanks in part to
personal lobbying in the state Legislature by Maureen Kanka. She is
the Hamilton Township, N.J., woman whose daughter Megan was killed
by a sex offender living near the Kanka home in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Information can be accessed through a 900 telephone number by
people seeking to know whether a person is on the registry due to a
sex-related conviction.
</P>
<P>
   One of the cases being heard by the Court of Appeals this
Thursday involves a man identified in court papers only as ''David
W.'' He was sentenced to one year in jail for refusing to sign a
registration form which classified him as a risk level three sex
offender or a ''sexually violent predator'' in the state's sex
registry.
</P>
<P>
   Level three is the highest-risk category of offenders and the
only classification of sex-related criminals listed in the
registry.
</P>
<P>
   David W., of Southampton in Suffolk County, was convicted in
1995 of sodomizing and sexually abusing two boys. His lawyer
Charles Newell will argue before the Court of Appeals that since
David W.'s crimes were committed before the state's sex registry
was set up, he is being denied his constitutional due process
rights by the way he was classified as a level three offender.
</P>
<P>
   Those convicted after 1996 are assigned risk classifications by
judges and have a right to be heard on those decisions. But sex
offenders prior to 1996 get classified by parole or probation
officers without a hearing, and David W. will contend that is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Level three violators must report to local police every 90 days
and be subject to public release of their photographs and criminal
histories. Those offenders are considered to be most likely to
commit sex crimes again.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, Ian Kearns' lawyer Elizabeth Miller will
argue before the Court of Appeals that sex offenders should be able
to appeal the classifications within the sex registry which are
determined by judges.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Kearns' case will argue that appeals should not
be allowed on risk-level assessments and, at any rate, that Kearns
waved his right to appeal by pleading guilty to a sexual abuse
charge involving a 16-year-old girl in the Bronx which underlies
his inclusion in the sex registry.
</P>
<P>
   Other cases before the judges during their May session include:
</P>
<P>
   BELL LABS
</P>
<P>
   The state Public Service Commission is seeking reinstatement of
its order requiring New York Telephone to repay customers $19.5
million. That is the company's share of its profit from the sale of
the former Bell Telephone Laboratories and the Western Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between the PSC and New York Telephone dates back to
the 1984 government-ordered breakup of the old AT&AMP;T monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   The PSC estimates that each customer of New York Telephone would
be in line for a credit of about $2.44 if the repayment order is
reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGES' PAY
</P>
<P>
   A salary dispute dating to 1978, when the state unified New
York's court system, will be before the Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   A lower court ruled that Monroe County Court judges should get
$131,400 a year, the same amount as Albany County Court judges. The
Monroe County Court judges currently make $125,600 a year, but they
are arguing that their court loads are similar to their colleagues
in Albany and they should be paid accordingly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
