<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York dairy group vows to continue fighting dairy compact  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN KEKIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Despite losing its final court battle, a
New York dairy group said it would continue fighting a compact that
sets minimum prices for milk sold in six northeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, the U.S. Supreme Court on Monday rejected the
argument by New York State Dairy Foods, Inc. that the Northeast
Dairy Compact Commission's pricing plan discriminates against
processors located outside New England.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Boston had previously upheld the pricing
rules, as did the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last November.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to oppose the unfair compact system through
legislative means here in New York state,'' Bruce Krupke, executive
vice president of New York State Dairy Foods, Inc., said in a
statement. ''We will also continue to try to enlighten our state's
legislators and dairy farmers on the negative impact the compact
would have if allowed to include New York state.''
</P>
<P>
   The compact was born in 1996, when Congress allowed
Massachusetts, Connecticut, Rhode Island, New Hampshire, Vermont
and Maine to group together to regulate milk prices in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The group sets minimum prices, which can be higher than the
price set by the federal government. Milk processors make payments
into a pool, and money from that pool is sent back to the
processors for distribution to the dairy farmers from whom they
bought milk.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Northeast plan, processors located in New England
receive rebates based on the total amount of milk they sell,
whether in the six-state region or elsewhere. Processors located
outside the region get rebates based on how much milk they sell in
New England in liquid form -- not milk for making into cheese, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge by New York State Dairy Foods began in 1997. The
trade group, which represents New York-based milk processors
Cumberland Farms, Crowley Foods, and Elmhurst Dairy, said dairy
farmers get a higher payback from New England processors and
therefore farmers prefer to do business with them.
</P>
<P>
   Although Krupke cited higher consumer prices as one of the
negatives of the compact, Carl Peterson saw only positives in the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been in business 49 years and my son wants to stay in
business,'' said Peterson, one of approximately 1,000 farmers in
eastern New York who sell milk to the compact. ''It's like a safety
net when prices drop low. It would make it very, very difficult
because we're just surviving right now. I'm gratified.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, was Mae Schmidle, vice chair of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're extremely pleased with the outcome of this,'' she said.
''It certainly indicates the Northeast Dairy Compact is progressing
in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   New York is the third-largest dairy producing state in the
nation behind California and Wisconsin. It was denied admittance to
the compact last year after a bitter political battle broke out
over whether it should be abolished. The fight pitted the Northeast
against the Midwest, where there is widespread opposition to the
regional compacts.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, who took over the family farm just west of Albany from
his father in 1961, said he wasn't sure what would happen if the
compact was abolished because milk prices are down so much, at
their lowest in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a lot tighter this year, even with the compact,'' he
said. ''We're down $1.50 (per hundred pounds) from last year. And
we expect on the year to be down an average of $1.75. Without it,
the average would have been $2.75. That would have made it very
difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-02-00 0018 </TRAILER>
