<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Socially responsible investing showing growth  </HEADLINE>
o0143nyc--
r f PM-NY--ConscienceInvesti     05-02 0739
PM-NY--Conscience Investing,Bjt,745   
Socially responsible investing showing growth
AP Membership Enterprise, 
By JEREMY BOYER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) -- For years, the idea of investing money
strictly in companies that share your social values was considered
by financial analysts to be a good for the conscience and bad for
the wallet.
</P>
<P>
   But the days of beating up on socially responsible investing
seem to be long gone, thanks in large part to strong performances
of many SRI funds.
</P>
<P>
   ''The debate is opening up,'' said Susan Lhota, a marketing
associate with the Cobleskill-based Fenimore Asset Management, a
mutual fund and private money management company.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a whole new genre of SRI funds coming out and many
more people are interested in investing in companies who have
passed socially responsible screens.''
</P>
<P>
   SRI funds work by screening potential companies for
characteristics in addition to financial performance. Typical
companies that are avoided by socially responsible investors
include tobacco, alcohol, firearms and gambling firms.
</P>
<P>
   Another screen for many investors is environmental performance
and labor practices. Producing potentially harmful products or
engaging in environmentally destructive behavior are considered
negative screens, but many funds also weigh positive screens, such
as diverse boards of directors or community involvement.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the types of companies that most often fit this
screen are technology-oriented. With the performance of technology
stocks in recent years, the recent troubles in that sector
notwithstanding, SRI funds are seeing unprecedented growth.
</P>
<P>
   Five-star rating Morningstar Inc., a leading national
independent securities analysis firm, now places 21 percent of the
SRI funds it tracks in its lofty five-star rating, which is twice
the rate of overall funds. Just two years ago, no SRI funds were in
that top category.
</P>
<P>
   With the strong performance of SRI funds, the number of people
investing in them has skyrocketed. From 1997 to 1999, the total
assets managed in screened portfolios for socially conscious
investors rose from $529 billion to $1.49 trillion, according to
the Social Investment Forum, a national nonprofit organization that
promotes the concept.
</P>
<P>
   Social Investment Forum also reports that the number of screened
mutual funds grew from 55 in 1995 to 175 in 1999. Another sign that
SRI is becoming mainstream is the creation of socially conscious
funds by reputable firms, such as Vanguard, which plans to start an
SRI index fund on May 8.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point, most of the major brokerage firms have some
kind of an offering,'' said Lowell Miller, president of
Miller/Howard Investments in Woodstock, which offers an SRI fund of
its own.
</P>
<P>
   For people who have not plunged into the world of socially
responsible investing, a wealth of information is available on the
internet. Web sites that Miller recommended include
www.greenmoney.com, which lists socially responsible funds. Another
site belongs to the Social Investment Forum, www.socialinvest.org.
A simple query using the words ''socially responsible investing''
on most internet search engines will yield dozens of sites.
</P>
<P>
   Financial planners warn, however, that the world of SRI funds
can sometimes be a little murky. Each fund is managed with
different sets of criteria, so it's important to know exactly what
screens are being employed.
</P>
<P>
   The people at Fenimore Asset Management are learning that lesson
firsthand. Although FAM has always avoided certain companies such
as tobacco or alcohol firms, it has not yet offered a full-blown
socially conscious fund.
</P>
<P>
   George Chelius III, director of marketing at FAM, said the
company is exploring the idea of launching an SRI fund, and it is
encountering some dilemmas. As an example, he cited a company that
makes ball bearings for both magnetic resonance imaging machines in
hospitals and for defense weapons. FAM has frequently invested in
that company, but it may not fit into an SRI fund.
</P>
<P>
   ''You always get into these gray areas,'' Chelius said. Miller
said there are also SRI funds that focus exclusively on one type of
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are funds that invest according to Islamic beliefs and
funds that invest only with an eye on the treatment of animals,''
he said. ''There are all kinds of social screens, so it's important
for an investor to check them out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-02-00 0018 </TRAILER>
