<HEADLINE> Boy finds body of dead infant brother in woods  </HEADLINE>
By HADLEY PAWLAK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, N.Y. (AP) -- A 29-year-old woman is being charged
with the second-degree murder of her infant son.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Ramsey gave police a detailed statement and was charged
with second-degree murder, according to Saratoga County Sheriff
James Bowen.
</P>
<P>
   ''She admitted to giving birth to the young boy, and he was
alive and crying,'' Bowen said. ''She wrapped it in a towel, and
took it across the street from the residence and placed it in the
woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey was being held without bail in Saratoga County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   The infant's body was found by his 9-year-old brother who had
been riding his bike through the woods with a 13-year-old neighbor
around 8 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the 13-year-old's mother, Pat St. Louis, her son
was upset when he came in for dinner because the boys thought they
had found the St. Louises' dead pet Siamese cat.
</P>
<P>
   After supper, St. Louis and her husband, Mark, accompanied their
son across the street and found a partially decomposed, naked,
blond baby boy wrapped in a pink or faded towel, Pat St. Louis
said.
</P>
<P>
   They called the sheriff's department.
</P>
<P>
   The baby, who was named Alexander Scott by his mother, was alive
at the time of abandonment, said Saratoga County Coroner John
DeMartino.
</P>
<P>
   According to the coroner's office, Alexander was left in the
woods in January, about 75 feet from a rural road.
</P>
<P>
   Albany County forensic pathologist Dr. Barbara Wolf conducted
the autopsy and authorities expected a preliminary cause of death
to be determined today, with toxicology results to follow.
</P>
<P>
   If found guilty, Rose Ramsey faces a sentence of 25 years to
life.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys live in one of four mobile homes clustered together
on a 1.5 mile road nestled in this sparsely populated area in the
Adirondack foothills.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor who also saw the infant's body said the incident had
shocked her.
</P>
<P>
   ''Looking at the baby you could see what that it was freshly
born and had just been sat out there,'' Linda Skeens said. ''It
makes you wonder if she ever walked over there to see the baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowen said that Ramsey gave birth at home but kept the pregnancy
a secret from her entire family. Ramsey told police that her
husband had threatened to leave her if she had another child.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that she left the baby with no provisions for its
care,'' Saratoga County District Attorney James A. Murphy III said
at a news conference Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to fast track this,'' Murphy said. ''It's an
absolute tragedy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-02-00 0022 </TRAILER>
