<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fed OKs Schwab Purchase  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve has approved big online
broker Charles Schwab Corp.'s purchase of old-line bank U.S. Trust
Corp., the financial industry's first major melding of old and new
in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Monday was 5-0 by the central bank's board of
governors, who determined that the acquisition of U.S. Trust by the
nation's largest discount and online brokerage would not threaten
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition was made possible by landmark legislation
enacted in November removing Depression-era barriers and allowing
banks, securities firms and insurance companies to get into each
other's businesses. It is the first major transaction since the new
law took effect.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on all the facts of record, the board concludes that
consummation of the proposal would not result in any significantly
adverse effects on competition or on the concentration of banking
resources in any relevant banking market,'' the Fed said in its
order.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators in several states still must approve the transaction,
but those clearances are expected.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're gratified by the Fed's decision,'' said Schwab spokesman
Glen Mathison.
</P>
<P>
   But Matthew Lee, executive director of Inner City
Press/Community on the Move, which had criticized U.S. Trust's
record of lending to low- and moderate-income people, assailed the
central bank's approval of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Fed governors' action showed how the new financial
services law, combined with ''the Fed's lax approach to enforcing
the Community Reinvestment Act, can allow a major financial
conglomerate to nearly-entirely evade the letter and spirit of the
(reinvestment act), which is to serve the credit needs of low- and
moderate-income areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal announced by the two companies in January, San
Francisco-based Schwab will buy U.S. Trust for $2.9 billion in
stock. The transaction is expected to be completed by July.
</P>
<P>
   While 25-year-old Schwab already has captured a big chunk of the
booming retail-investor market, it will be able to tap wealthy
investors through its purchase of New York-based U.S. Trust,
purveyor of investment advice and private banking services to some
of America's richest families since 1853.
</P>
<P>
   The move was designed to fill existing gaps in both Schwab's and
U.S. Trust's current gamut of services, company officials have
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its market power, Schwab was unable to meet the needs of
its wealthiest clients, according to company founder and co-chief
executive Charles R. Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   Wealthy investors, meanwhile, have shown an increased desire to
participate in the online investing revolution sweeping Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   The companies estimate there are more than 6 million U.S.
households with a net worth exceeding $1 million, and that the
number of Americans with large investment portfolios is expected to
grow at a double-digit pace in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Millionaires currently comprise just 5 percent of Schwab's 6.4
million customers, while U.S. Trust's core customers have more than
$5 million each to invest.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to private banking services such as checking
accounts, credit lines and mortgage loans, U.S. Trust, which has
about $5 billion in assets, also helps clients create trust funds
to pass on their considerable wealth to the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab, with some $29 billion in assets, now will be able to
offer those services through its U.S. Trust unit.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies will retain their separate brand identities.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Federal Reserve's order: 
www.federalreserve.gov/BoardDocs/Press/BHC/2000/20000501/default.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 0031 </TRAILER>
