<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Homers in San Francisco Bay  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Barry Bonds became the first player to
homer into the water at San Francisco's new bayside ballpark Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds drove the first pitch from New York's Rich Rodriguez over
the right-field wall and into McCovey Cove where it was quickly
fished out of the water with a net by Joseph Figone, a member of
the grounds crew at the Giants' old ballpark on Candlestick Point.
</P>
<P>
   Figone was cruising McCovey Cove in a raft and was in the right
place at the right time. The crowd erupted when the ball sailed
into the bay and brought Bonds out for a bow after the three-run
shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants celebrated the milestone by shooting off water
cannons over the right-field wall and putting up the number one on
a scoreboard designating splashdowns in the bay.
</P>
<P>
   In an exhibition game against the Yankees, Bonds hit a ball that
bounced off the pier-side walkway and into the bay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
