<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Charged In Murder of Rabbi's Wife  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- Two men were arrested Monday night and
charged in the murder-for-hire of the wife of a prominent rabbi,
who was earlier charged in the killing. One of the men has admitted
to his role as a go-between, his attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Jenoff, 54, and Paul M. Daniels, 26, were charged with
murder and conspiracy to commit murder in connection with the
killing of Carol Neulander, Prosecutor Lee Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, 52, was bludgeoned to death on Nov. 1, 1994, in her
Cherry Hill home. Investigators say she was killed by a hitman
posing as a deliveryman.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff's attorney told the Courier-Post of Cherry Hill for
Tuesday's editions that his client has admitted that ''he was the
intermediary between the rabbi and someone who would kill his
wife,'' attorney Francis J. Hartman said.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman said his client recruited Daniels for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman said Jenoff called the prosecutor and met with him
Friday because he felt remorse about Carol Neulander's death.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Rabbi Fred J. Neulander, said he found her body
when he returned from Congregation M'Kor Shalom synagogue. Her
purse was missing, but no other valuables were touched.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander was indicted in January 1999 on charges of accomplice
murder and conspiracy to commit murder. He is free on bail awaiting
his trial, which is scheduled to begin in June.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff and Daniels were being held in the Camden County Jail
Monday night. It was unclear whether Daniels had an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have said Neulander had his wife of 29 years killed
so that he could continue his extramarital affair with Philadelphia
radio personality Elaine Soncini.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander allegedly thought divorce would jeopardize his
position as senior rabbi at the synagogue, which he founded with
his wife in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Soncini admitted having a two-year affair with Neulander that
ended shortly after his wife's killing. She has not been charged
with any wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 0052 </TRAILER>
