<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, May 2, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore To Offer Wider Felon Drug Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore plans to propose expanded drug treatment programs
for convicted felons and continued federal funding of a program to put police
officers on the nation's streets. In an address being prepared for his visit
Tuesday to Atlanta, the vice president was proposing that police be allowed to
carry concealed weapons off duty. Gore also was promising another 50,000 police
on the street under a program begun by President Clinton in his bid to convince
swing voters that Democrats can be trusted with crime and safety issues. Some
Republicans have balked at the federally funded program.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Castro Leads May Day Parade
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Fidel Castro joined the annual May Day parade today for the
first time in years and ended a speech with a cell phone call to Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, urging him to continue his fight to bring his refugee son, Elian, home
to Cuba. Castro led hundreds of thousands of Cubans from Havana's Plaza of the
Revolution to the U.S. Interests Section. ''Fidel! Fidel!'' chanted the crowd in
the annual march that traditionally involves workers. In a speech, Castro
praised Cubans for their tenacity.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Severe Drought Grips India
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BHUBANESHWAR, India (AP) -- A severe drought has parched South Asia,
affecting 50 million people in India, drying up water wells in southern
Afghanistan and killing animals in southern Pakistan. In India, the drought has
cut a smoldering swath from west to east across the states of Andhra Pradesh,
Madhya Pradesh, and Orissa on the east coast, where a cyclone and floods killed
at least 10,000 last fall. Eleven of India's 31 states are facing a water
crisis. Last week, temperatures reached 118 degrees in Orissa state, drying up
streams, ponds and wells.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Time Warner Yanks Plug on ABC
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission planned to hold
negotiations tonight with the Walt Disney Co. and Time Warner after the cable
giant pulled the plug on ABC programming. Disney, ABC's corporate parent, is
fighting over how much money Time Warner must compensate Disney for the right to
carry some of its cable channels. Disney had offered a series of deadline
extensions after the original national transmission deal expired Dec. 31. The
most recent deadline expired at 12:01 a.m. on Monday, when ABC was blacked out
in the homes of 3.5 million Time Warner cable customers in the New York City
area, Houston and Raleigh-Durham, N.C., and elsewhere.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Anger Linked to Heart Attacks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- People who are highly anger-prone are nearly three times more
likely to have a heart attack, a study has found. The connection between anger
and heart attacks held true even after researchers took into account other major
risk factors such as high blood pressure, high cholesterol, smoking and obesity.
''The implications of our study are that anger could potentially lead to heart
attacks, especially among middle-aged men and women with normal blood
pressure,'' said Janice Williams, an epidemiologist in Atlanta who led the study
while at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Expects Palestinian State
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EILAT, Israel (AP) -- Trying to improve the climate in peace talks, Israeli
officials said Monday they've resigned themselves to Palestinian statehood, and
the Palestinians acknowledged Israel's pain on Holocaust Remembrance Day. But
negotiators reported little progress and awaited the arrival of a U.S. mediator
Tuesday to help draft an outline of a final peace treaty. Israeli officials said
they would not oppose a Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, but
said the Palestinians should accept that some Jewish settlements there will
become part of Israel.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Higher at Midday
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average on Tuesday rose 77.81 points to
18,480.89 points at the end of the morning session. Financial markets in Tokyo
will be closed Wednesday through Friday because of national holidays. The
markets will reopen Monday, May 8. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average rose 77.87 points to close at 10,811.78 on Monday. The technology-heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 97.42 to close at 3,958.08.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bucks Beat Pacers 100-87
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Ray Allen scored 20 points before taking a blow to the
head, and reserve Scott Williams added 20 as the hot-shooting Bucks routed the
Indiana Pacers 100-87 Monday night in Game 4 of their best-of-five series. Game
5 is Thursday night at Conseco Fieldhouse, where the Bucks already have won
twice this season. Milwaukee is hoping to become the third No. 8 seed to upset a
top-seeded team. When Denver upset Seattle in 1994 and the Knicks beat the Heat
last year, both eighth-seeded teams won on the road in a fifth game.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON
