<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MP3.com CEO: Settlement likely in copyright infringement case  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- MP3.com was trying to hit the right notes in
negotiations with major record companies even before a judge ruled
that the Internet-based music service violates their copyrights,
MP3.com's chief executive says.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been in heavy negotiations for weeks,'' said Michael
Robertson, MP3.com's chief executive officer, in a telephone
interview Monday from the headquarters of the San Diego-based
company.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was cautiously optimistic that the talks, which began
a month ago, would ultimately resolve the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say that we have two very motivated parties,'' he
said. ''We're relatively close in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments came after U.S. District Judge Jed Rakoff ruled
Friday that MP3.com is liable for offering music online without
permission.
</P>
<P>
   The company lets users listen to music on the MP3.com Web site
from compact discs they already own. The record companies
challenged the practice, saying MP3.com violated copyrights by
loading CDs onto computer servers and letting customers download
them.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the judge issued a three-page order setting a
schedule for how the case will proceed, with an Aug. 28 date for a
trial of any remaining issues in the case, including damages.
</P>
<P>
   But he froze the exchange of evidence in the case through May 25
to give the parties an opportunity for any settlement discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Forrest, a lawyer for plaintiff Warner Brothers
Records Inc., referred calls to the Recording Industry Association
of America, a trade association for the major music labels
representing 90 percent of signed artists.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Maloni, a spokesman for the organization, declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   A source familiar with the talks, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said there was nothing to indicate the record companies
were close to a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, though, said the talks were in ''fifth gear'' even
when the judge issued his one-page ruling Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He said a settlement was in the interests of both sides,
including record companies interested in licensing their content in
new ways.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he said, MP3.com and the companies were trying to
accomplish something that was unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one in the world has ever gotten a worldwide licensing
agreement for the entire record catalogue,'' he said. ''It would be
a monumental licensing deal if we are able to bring it to
fruition.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Sandler, a spokesman for The National Academy of Recording
Arts &AMP; Sciences, said the trade organization for songwriters and
producers would be pleased with a deal that forces MP3.com to pay
for its music.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't close the door to the barn so you might as well make
it feasible for these people to pay for the use,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said MP3.com ''had demonstrated it's a good marketing
vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The question is whether they are going to pay money that will
eventually flow to the songwriters and artists and publishers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   If settlement talks break down, Robertson said, the company
would not be doomed. He said it still seemed on track, as analysts
predict that it will become profitable in the first quarter of
2001.
</P>
<P>
   ''None of our revenues are tied to the technology in legal
question. No revenues of note are being generated through that
service,'' he said, noting that the service accounts for only 4
percent of the company's business.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson likened his company's current court battle to that
faced by companies during the introduction of other technologies
such as cable television, cassette recorders and the video cassette
recorder.
</P>
<P>
   He said settlement negotiations were focusing on payments to
record companies that would still allow his company to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think both parties are really motivated to make it a
realistic number,'' he said. ''The content we're talking about is
only the CDs that you've already bought. It doesn't make sense to
tax the hell out of consumers, especially the ones who are buying
CDs, and say, 'You have to pay again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the upbeat talk by Robertson, he acknowledged there were
critics predicting the demise of his company because of the judge's
ruling, including a friend who offered to send over canned food so
they could eat.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're hanging in there,'' he said with a chuckle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
