<HEADLINE> Vieques Protesters Vow To Fight US  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS HAWLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- The scene is familiar: a crowd of
determined demonstrators talking worriedly in Spanish, fears of a
nighttime raid by federal authorities, threats of a political
backlash and a nationwide wave of civil disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   As U.S. authorities show signs of marshaling their forces to
arrest protesters on the U.S. Navy bombing range on Vieques Island,
comparisons to unrest surrounding the Elian Gonzalez case in Miami
buzzed through protest camps.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the case of that young boy in Miami, the issue ended with
the arrests. Here the problem will start with the arrests,'' said
Ruben Berrios, the Puerto Rican Independence Party leader who has
spent nearly a year camped on the Navy's bombing range.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, protesters outside the gate of the range said they
feared pepper spray would be used, as it was in the raid to seize
Elian from his Miami relatives' home. They kept a box of rags at
hand, ready to soak them in water and vinegar to minimize the
effects of the spray.
</P>
<P>
   Local politicians who arrived to reinforce the camp promised a
backlash against the Clinton administration by the sizable Puerto
Rican populations in New York, Florida and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is going to be worse than Miami for the Clinton
administration,'' said Jose Aponte, a prominent Puerto Rican
Democrat and the mayor of Carolina, a San Juan suburb. ''Arrests
are not going to end the fight. They are going to extend it to the
rest of Puerto Rico and big cities in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Activist Robert Rabin said: ''These arrests will only begin a
new chapter here. Any attempt at intervention will touch off civil
disobedience around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months there have been marches and demonstrations in
Washington and New York. On Monday, the New York-based Vieques
Support Campaign announced a protest in Times Square the day after
any arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will show them that Vieques is not alone,'' a statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   Berrios was optimistic that President Clinton might call off the
expected raid. ''Calmer minds have prevailed for one year,''
Berrios said. ''It would surprise me if the warmonger minds prevail
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
