<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Talks Recess  </HEADLINE>
By DANA BUDEIRI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EILAT, Israel (AP) -- Israeli and Palestinian negotiators took a
daylong break today from peace talks that have made little
progress, choosing to await the arrival of a U.S. envoy to help
bridge the gaps.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's session was marked by attempts at good will, with
Israeli officials acknowledging Palestinian statehood as inevitable
and the Palestinians expressing sympathy for Israel's pain on
Holocaust Remembrance Day, the reason for today's recess.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. envoy Dennis Ross was to arrive later at this Red Sea port
to help push along the negotiations that have so far revealed
''large differences,'' according to Palestinian negotiator Saeb
Erekat.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations are trying to produce a framework agreement for
a final peace treaty, ostensibly by the end of the month, though
both sides have expressed doubt that the deadline will be met. The
treaty itself is due by September.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators are to reach a deal on the scope of a third and
final interim Israeli troop pullout from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat said Israel had offered too little land. The two sides
disagree over the size of the Jewish settlements and military and
border areas that Israel may retain in the pullback.
</P>
<P>
   The thorniest issues -- Palestinian refugees, settlements, final
borders and the fate of Jerusalem, claimed by both sides as their
capital -- remain unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   Amid Palestinian anger over plans to expand the Jewish West Bank
settlement of Maaleh Adumim, a close aide to Prime Minister Ehud
Barak said Israel would not oppose a Palestinian state in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Cabinet Minister Haim Ramon said Monday that a Palestinian state
already existed, de facto, and that negotiators would discuss its
parameters. He said, however, that the Palestinians should accept
that some Jewish settlements, including Maaleh Adumim, would be
annexed to Israel as part of the final treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat denounced the settlement
expansion in an area where the Palestinians hope to establish their
state and said the construction was negatively affecting peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Yasser Abed Rabbo, meanwhile, offered
Israelis words of support for Holocaust Memorial Day, which began
Monday evening and ends today after sundown.
</P>
<P>
   ''We share with the Israeli people the feeling of pain and
sorrow on this day, a day of tragedy in Jewish history,'' Yasser
Abed Rabbo told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is sensitive. Many Palestinians feel Israel demands
sympathy because of the tragedy of the Holocaust, but ignores the
suffering of Palestinians displaced from their homes and homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ''We also want our days of tragedy to become a distant memory
and to put an end to the suffering of the Palestinian people that
has lasted until today,'' Abed Rabbo went on to say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 0121 </TRAILER>
