<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, Gore Try To Stay Within Budget  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tax and spending plans by Al Gore and George
W. Bush leave plenty of unanswered questions about how -- and
whether -- they can live within their own budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, their efforts have drawn plaudits from some budget
experts because it is the first time presidential contenders have
at least said they would use Social Security funds only to reduce
the debt or to buttress the huge pension program. Many economists
think using those funds for debt reduction is wise because it would
help push interest rates down and keep the economy strong.
</P>
<P>
   ''From a historical perspective, you'd give both candidates high
marks for fiscal prudence,'' said Robert Reischauer, president of
the Urban Institute and former chief of the Congressional Budget
Office.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore both rely on projections of big federal surpluses
in coming years -- which could prove wrong if a major economic
downturn occurs.
</P>
<P>
   But if anything, both men should benefit when official forecasts
are updated this summer because most analysts expect the economic
boom to push projected surpluses higher still, leaving more money
for their proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates' budgets are more political platforms
than fiscal blueprints. Even so, both proposals omit key details
about where they would find budget savings and how much they would
need, raising questions about whether their plans are politically
feasible.
</P>
<P>
   By the Bush campaign's own numbers, the Republican's five-year
plan -- headlined by his $483 billion tax cut -- would clip Social
Security surpluses slightly and drain the entire surplus he
projects from the rest of the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor projects a five-year, $586 billion surplus
from non-Social Security programs -- a number expected to rise when
the campaign releases a new estimate based on April federal tax
collections. But, using figures provided by aides, his tax cut plus
proposals to boost spending for health, schools, defense and other
programs would total $588.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That means Bush would use $2.6 billion of the nearly $1 trillion
in Social Security surpluses expected from 2002-2006, or about 0.26
percent. That figure has little budgetary significance, but
underlines the difficulty of leaving politically sacrosanct Social
Security money alone.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's balance,'' Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said of the
figures.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Bush's proposals could cost billions more
because his plan excludes the costs of lost interest savings, a new
Medicare prescription drug benefit, or other proposals. And to
arrive at his surplus forecast, Bush assumes the government will
spend tens of billions of dollars less annually than many lawmakers
of both parties believe is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Aides say Bush will soon detail federal waste that could provide
additional savings.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would also use an unspecified amount of the Social Security
surplus to subsidize new, voluntary personal retirement accounts,
investments that would supplement traditional Social Security
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   He has provided no details on that. But one frequently discussed
plan on Capitol Hill cited by aides would use 2 percent of the
current 12.4 percent payroll tax that finances Social Security, or
about $85 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean less money for debt reduction. But Bush aides
say the higher return likely on such investments would mean better
overall retirement plans for Americans and less pressure on Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in an interview in today's editions of the Washington
Post, said the combination of Bush's Social Security privatization
plan and his tax cut would eliminate the projected surplus along
with any hope of paying down the national debt, as the vice
president favors.
</P>
<P>
   ''He would continue these multitrillion-dollar debts
indefinitely and with his tax scheme, would significantly add to
them,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan covers 10 years and is not directly comparable to
Bush's.	   Largely because he assumes higher spending and a slightly weaker
economy than Bush, the vice president says the non-Social Security
surplus will total $746 billion over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Gore would use that money -- plus an additional $130
billion in savings largely from raising taxes on tobacco and some
corporate transactions -- for a $250 billion tax cut, an expansion
of health-insurance coverage, a new Medicare prescription drug
benefit, debt reduction and $34 billion worth of still unannounced
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has repeatedly rejected President Clinton's calls for
tobacco and corporate taxes, raising questions about where Gore
would actually get that money.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Gore wants $115 billion more for education. And he
has talked about $9 billion more for cancer research, $5 billion a
year more to help states expand preschool, and unspecified
increases for Internet technology and foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   To pay for those increases, aides say Gore will keep other
programs from growing as fast as the overall inflation rate. But
Gore has not said which programs, or precisely how much of these
savings he will need.
</P>
<P>
   ''The risk with Al Gore's plan is he'll reinvent big
government,'' said Bush spokesman Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also would use $100 billion of the $2.2 trillion in
projected Social Security surpluses over the next decade to improve
benefits for widows and working women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 0136 </TRAILER>
