<DOCNO> APW20000502.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Calls for Drug Testing Inmates  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore says prisoners should be tested for
drug use and offered top-notch treatment programs in an effort to
''stop that revolving door once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of an anti-crime package being unveiled in Atlanta
today, the vice president planned to propose federal funds to hire
50,000 new police across the country and say off-duty officers
should be allowed to carry concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Giving the speech a partisan edge, Gore planned to criticize
Texas Gov. George W. Bush's record of rehabilitating Texas inmates,
advisers said Monday. Bush is the GOP nominee-in-waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to stop that revolving door once and for all,'' Gore
said in a draft of his Atlanta speech. ''First of all we have to
test prisoners for drugs while they are in jail and break up the
drug rings in our prisons. We have to expand drug treatment within
our prisons,''
</P>
<P>
   He promised to make prisoners ''a simple deal: Before you get
out of jail you have to get clean. If you want to stay out, then
you better stay clean.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was not expected to estimate the cost of the
initiatives, many of which were first unveiled in his July 1999
anti-crime address in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   They included:
</P>
<P>
   -- Ensuring continued funding of a cops-on-the-street program
started by President Clinton in his bid to convince swing voters
that Democrats can be trusted with crime and safety issues. Gore
promised to fund an additional 50,000 police positions nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   --Establishing gang-free zones that would ban the wearing of
gang-related clothing. Civil liberties groups have questioned the
constitutionality of such laws.
</P>
<P>
   --Making it a federal crime to stalk a child on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   --Targeting telemarketers who prey on senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   --Giving more prison time to inmates who don't break their drug
habits.
</P>
<P>
   The crime speech was coming as a new national poll showed Bush
and Gore in a statistically dead heat. Crime is traditionally an
issue that favor Republican candidates, but Gore hopes to cut into
Bush's advantage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 0142 </TRAILER>
