<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Braves 2, Dodgers 1  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN NADEL, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Atlanta Braves won again, and visiting
fans went after John Rocker again.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood scattered five hits over seven innings, and
light-hitting Quilvio Veras homered Monday night as the Braves beat
the Los Angeles Dodgers 2-1 for their franchise-record 14th
straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, making his second road appearance since his
season-opening, two-week suspension, was mooned by a fan who ran on
the field with two outs in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was booed loudly by the Dodger Stadium crowd of 28,790
upon entering the game with a 2-0 lead. Several objects were thrown
on the field, prompting a warning from the stadium announcer.
</P>
<P>
   With Kevin Elster batting and two outs, a fan bolted out of the
right-field stands, ran toward the mound, turned around and dropped
his shorts. The fan quickly was escorted off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Elster singled to drive in Todd Hundley, the first run this year
off Rocker, who had pitched eight scoreless innings. Rocker then
struck out pinch-hitter Geronimo Berroa and was surrounded by
security as he came off the field. Rocker flipped the ball to a fan
in a Braves cap behind Atlanta's dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who haven't lost since April 15, broke the previous
team standard of 13 consecutive wins, set in 1982 and equaled 10
years later. Three of the wins came against the Dodgers in Atlanta
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood (3-0) walked three and struck out four before Rudy
Seanez pitched a perfect eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood, who retired 13 of the last 15 batters he faced,
allowed five hits and one unearned run in seven innings of a 5-1
victory over the Dodgers last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Veras, who has two homers this year and just 26 in his 635-game
career, hit a 3-1 pitch from rookie Eric Gagne (0-2) into the
right-center field seats with one out in the third to put the
Braves on top.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne was the hard-luck loser, allowing just four hits in seven
innings while walking two and striking out six. He went six innings
in Atlanta last Wednesday and gave up three runs -- all on solo
homers.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves got an unearned run off Matt Herges in the eighth
when Veras scored from second on an infield hit by Andres Galarraga
and third baseman Adrian Beltre's throwing error.
</P>
<P>
   Veras opened the inning with a single and took second on Andruw
Jones' grounder to second. Veras avoided the tag attempt of second
baseman Mark Grudzielanek, who elected to go to first instead of
throwing to second for the force.
</P>
<P>
   Herges had appeared in 10 games previously this season, pitching
15 scoreless innings.
Notes: Dodgers slugger Gary Sheffield received a scare before the
game when he stepped on a baseball that was underneath a tarpaulin
near the batting cage and rolled his right ankle -- the same ankle
he sprained April 8 in New York that has continued to bother him.
After 40 minutes of treatment, he took about 10 swings off a
batting tee and declared himself ready to play. He went hitless in
four at-bats. ... The Braves, who brought a big league-leading 3.08
ERA into the game, outscored the Dodgers 12-4 in sweeping a
three-game series in Atlanta last week. The Dodgers then scored 25
runs in a weekend sweep of the Florida Marlins. ... Rocker,
suspended for the season's first two weeks for offensive remarks
that appeared in Sports Illustrated over the winter, politely
declined to be interviewed before the game. .. Veras has hit safely
in a career-high 12 straight games. ... The loss was the third 1-0
setback for the Dodgers in a span of eight games. ... Current New
York Yankees manager Joe Torre was the Braves' manager in 1982, and
current manager Bobby Cox was on the job 10 years later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 0158 </TRAILER>
