<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, May 2, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israeli-Palestinian Talks Recess
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EILAT, Israel (AP) -- Israeli and Palestinian negotiators took a daylong
break Tuesday from peace talks that have made little progress, choosing to await
the arrival of a U.S. envoy to help bridge the gaps. Monday's session was marked
by attempts at good will, with Israeli officials acknowledging Palestinian
statehood as inevitable and the Palestinians expressing sympathy for Israel's
pain on Holocaust Remembrance Day, the reason for Tuesday's recess. U.S. envoy
Dennis Ross was to arrive later at this Red Sea port to help push along the
negotiations that have so far revealed ''large differences,'' according to
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Calls for Drug Testing Inmates
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore says prisoners should be tested for drug use and
offered top-notch treatment programs in an effort to ''stop that revolving door
once and for all.'' As part of an anti-crime package being unveiled in Atlanta
Tuesday, the vice president planned to propose federal funds to hire 50,000 new
police across the country and say off-duty officers should be allowed to carry
concealed weapons. Giving the speech a partisan edge, Gore planned to criticize
Texas Gov. George W. Bush's record of rehabilitating Texas inmates, advisers
said Monday. Bush is the GOP nominee-in-waiting.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Arkansas Woman Faces Execution
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The state of Arkansas is preparing to execute its
first female inmate in more than 150 years, a former nurse who says she wants to
die for suffocating her two children. Christina Marie Riggs, 28, would be the
fifth woman executed nationwide since the U.S. Supreme Court lifted a ban on
capital punishment in 1976. She is to die by injection Tuesday night. Riggs
asked the jury to sentence her to death for the Nov. 5, 1997, slayings of
Justin, 5, and Shelby Alexis, 2. Justin was injected with potassium chloride and
morphine and eventually smothered; his sister was smothered.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Castro Leads May Day Parade
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Fidel Castro joined the annual May Day parade today for the
first time in years and ended a speech with a cell phone call to Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, urging him to continue his fight to bring his refugee son, Elian, home
to Cuba. Castro led hundreds of thousands of Cubans from Havana's Plaza of the
Revolution to the U.S. Interests Section. ''Fidel! Fidel!'' chanted the crowd in
the annual march that traditionally involves workers. In a speech, Castro
praised Cubans for their tenacity.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Severe Drought Grips India
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BHUBANESHWAR, India (AP) -- A severe drought has parched South Asia,
affecting 50 million people in India, drying up water wells in southern
Afghanistan and killing animals in southern Pakistan. In India, the drought has
cut a smoldering swath from west to east across the states of Andhra Pradesh,
Madhya Pradesh, and Orissa on the east coast, where a cyclone and floods killed
at least 10,000 last fall. Eleven of India's 31 states are facing a water
crisis. Last week, temperatures reached 118 degrees in Orissa state, drying up
streams, ponds and wells.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Time Warner Yanks Plug on ABC
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission planned to hold
negotiations tonight with the Walt Disney Co. and Time Warner after the cable
giant pulled the plug on ABC programming. Disney, ABC's corporate parent, is
fighting over how much money Time Warner must compensate Disney for the right to
carry some of its cable channels. Disney had offered a series of deadline
extensions after the original national transmission deal expired Dec. 31. The
most recent deadline expired at 12:01 a.m. on Monday, when ABC was blacked out
in the homes of 3.5 million Time Warner cable customers in the New York City
area, Houston and Raleigh-Durham, N.C., and elsewhere.
</P>
