<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: Communication poor between prostate cancer patients,doctors  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN BACHMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- A survey of prostate cancer patients and their
doctors finds poor communication between the two, with patients
saying they weren't informed of all treatment options and half the
doctors finding that patients weren't prepared to make such
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which surveyed 307 men diagnosed with prostate
cancer and 302 doctors, was released Monday in conjunction with the
American Urological Association's 95th annual meeting, which ends
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There seems to be a disconnect between physicians and
patients,'' said Dr. David McLeod, director of urologic oncology at
Walter Reed Medical Center in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod is the surgeon who successfully treated Sen. Bob Dole and
Army Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod said the communication gap between urologists and
patients threatens effective treatment and underscores the cancer's
nature as a taboo subject of frank discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a treatment battle,'' he said. ''The key to winning the
treatment is communication between doctor and patient.''
</P>
<P>
   In the survey, 94 percent of doctors said they presented
patients with all treatment options. But 32 percent of patients
said such discussions focused on the treatment the doctor
considered best and not on all options.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer of the prostate, a gland involved in semen production, is
the second most common type of cancer found in American men. Early
detection greatly increases the chance of successful treatment.
About 179,300 men were diagnosed with the disease last year, while
about 32,000 die from it annually.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the doctors -- 90 percent -- said they believed
patients used the Internet to learn about the disease. In fact,
only 19 percent said they researched online, opting instead for
newspaper and magazine articles and talking with friends and
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Joe Torre, the New York Yankees manager, did
when he was diagnosed with prostate cancer in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank God for my wife. I don't go in there on the Internet and
get information on stuff,'' Torre said Monday from Cleveland, where
his team had a game. ''She's the researcher. She leaves the
(baseball) managing to me, but the rest of the world is up to
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani announced that he
has prostate cancer, which was detected early, a key to successful
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was fortunate,'' said Torre, who called Giuliani to offer
his support. ''Being a high-profile person, I was made aware of
everything, the treatment, the side effects, A-to-Z. But, again,
there's a certain responsibility on the patients' side of it. We
went in with some questions, and unless you raise the questions,
you're not going to get the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   American Urological Association: http://www.auanet.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-02-00 0203 </TRAILER>
