<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minn. Goes After Holocaust Insurers  </HEADLINE>
By GREGG AAMOT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- When Max Goodman's father died in Europe
60 years ago, he left his family a life insurance policy worth 1
million Romanian lei.
</P>
<P>
   But Goodman and his Jewish family were never able to collect the
money, worth about $5,000 then or $60,000 in today's dollars. They
were imprisoned in a Nazi concentration camp in what is now the
Ukraine until 1945, when he, his mother and sister were freed by
Russian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman tried to cash in the policy after he was liberated, but
dropped the matter when he realized the money would ''maybe buy 10
loaves of bread'' because of postwar inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman eventually settled in St. Paul, where he lives today
with his wife. More than a half-century later, the retired
accountant hopes he will finally get his money, with the help of an
international commission and a new Minnesota law.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never thought of it that I would be able to file a claim,''
Goodman, 76, said recently as his apartment filled with the smells
of a roast and meatballs his wife, Edith, was preparing for a Seder
to mark the beginning of Passover.
</P>
<P>
   The law signed by Gov. Jesse Ventura two weeks ago is designed
to pressure a handful of European insurance companies with
affiliates in Minnesota to cooperate with the International
Commission on Holocaust Era Insurance Claims.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how many of the estimated 200 to 300 Holocaust
survivors in Minnesota will benefit. But the lawmakers who pushed
the bill hope other states will follow suit, creating pressure that
uncooperative insurers will find difficult to resist.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a way to get some kind of leverage with these
companies,'' said Sen. Allan Spear, a Democrat who sponsored the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   California and Washington have enacted similar measures.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota law allows the state Commerce Department to strip
licenses from insurers doing business in Minnesota as long as their
parent companies refuse to cooperate with the commission. The
department also will help Holocaust survivors by sharing
information about claims with the commission and other states, and
by possibly creating a registry of Holocaust-related policies.
</P>
<P>
   The London-based commission, created in 1998 and headed by
former U.S. Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger, is working on
behalf of Holocaust victims who owned, were covered by or were the
beneficiaries of policies for life insurance, education or dowries
issued between 1920 and 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Several European insurance companies are involved. For decades,
thousands of policies went unpaid because documents were destroyed
and because in many cases insurers demanded a death certificate, a
difficult if not impossible request of families whose loved ones
died in concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   Spear said while the legislation may put pressure on the
companies, it is unlikely the state would take the extreme step of
taking away any licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's there as a last resort,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance industry representatives argued against the bill,
saying it could undermine the work of the commission and will be
difficult to administer. But when Republican Rep. Ron Abrams and
Spear brought the legislation to their respective chambers, they
found little opposition. The bill passed the House 133-1 and the
Senate 62-0.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Oertelt, 79, was born to a poor family in Berlin which had
no life insurance. Still, he is proud Minnesota is trying to do
something for its Holocaust survivors and said the law might shed
more light on a dark era.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important that people learn about that time and about
what can happen when hatred and bigotry goes uncontrolled,'' said
Oertelt, who made it through Auschwitz and two other camps before
moving to Minnesota in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the new law, Goodman still believes his chances of
collecting on his father's life insurance policy are slim. Based on
a formula that uses a 1938 exchange rate, the 1 million lei policy
was worth about $5,000 or some $60,000 today. The International
Commission allows for recovery of 10 times the policy's original
value, which would bring the amount to about $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''So, maybe they'll find something,'' he said, adding with a
shrug, ''I don't put a big hope on it.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The International Commission on Holocaust Era Insurance Claims:
http://www.icheic.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 0236 </TRAILER>
