<DOCNO> APW20000502.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 02:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lenora Fulani says Hillary Clinton attacked to score points  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign reiterated its
criticism of Patrick Buchanan and Lenora Fulani despite Fulani's
accusation that Clinton is merely using the attack to ''score
political points.''
</P>
<P>
   ''She and her professional advisers thought she could score some
political points by name-calling,'' Fulani said Monday. ''They feel
completely secure that they have the support of New York's black
leadership and that they can single me out for abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton attended a candidate's forum in Buffalo on Saturday
sponsored by the Independence Party, which is the state wing of the
national Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of soliciting the party's support for her U.S.
Senate candidacy, the first lady condemned the group for allowing
itself to ''become defined by the anti-Semitism, extremism,
prejudice and intolerance of a few shrill voices of both the right
and the left.''
</P>
<P>
   She later said she was referring to Buchanan, a Reform Party
presidential candidate, and Fulani, a left-leaning black activist
who ran for president in 1992 as an independent and who has become
an important force in the Independence Party.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton's spokesman Howard Wolfson reiterated the
campaign's contention that Buchanan and Fulani have a long history
of making anti-Semitic and divisive statements.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's why Hillary made it very clear on Saturday that she
won't compromise her principles by running on a ticket with Pat
Buchanan,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   But Fulani wasn't the only one to see another motive in
Clinton's attack.
</P>
<P>
   George Stephanopoulos, former spokesman for President Clinton
and now an ABC News political analyst, described Clinton's going to
the Independence Party event and then turning around to critique it
as a ''Sister Souljah move.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase refers to an incident in 1992, when Bill Clinton,
running for president for the first time, went to an event
sponsored by Jesse Jackson and attacked the racial remarks of black
rap singer Sister Souljah.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way that Bill Clinton's condemnation of Sister
Souljah's militant rhetoric was designed to appeal to white voters,
Hillary Clinton's condemnation of Fulani and Buchanan as
anti-Semitic could appeal to Jewish voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''If that was her motive, I hope the Jewish community isn't
manipulated by it,'' Fulani said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Republican rival for the Senate, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, also appeared at the Independence Party forum but did not
criticize the party during his presentation. Later, however, he
said neither Fulani nor Buchanan ''represent my philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulani said she is not ready to endorse Giuliani for Senate, but
she praised his appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ''He didn't insult us,'' she said. ''He played the role one
plays if he is looking for the party line.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulani insisted she is not an anti-Semite.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have very strong relationships with lots of progressive Jews
and ordinary Jewish people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about statements attributed to her by the Anti-Defamation
League and others that quote her as painting Jews as ''oppressors''
of minorities or ''storm troopers'' of capitalism, she said the
statements were taken out of context or were quotes from a play by
her mentor, Fred Newman.
</P>
<P>
   She said the ADL has a political agenda and has ''gone after a
host of black leaders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-02-00 0250 </TRAILER>
