<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man accused of bludgeoning priest declared competent to standtrial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) -- The man accused in the beating death
of a Bristol priest last June has been declared mentally competent
to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   In New Britain Superior Court Monday, state psychiatric experts
testified that after ten months of treatment Michael Ouellette can
understand the charges against him and aid in his own defense.
</P>
<P>
   Ouellette, a homeless drifter diagnosed as a
paranoid-schizophrenic, is accused of beating the Rev. Robert Lysz
to death with an altar candlestick inside St. Matthew Church on
June 24, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   According to an arrest affidavit, Ouellette told police he beat
the priest after the Rev. Lysz refused to let him sleep in the
church.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Ouellette, 33, broke into the church parish house,
accosted Lysz, bit his ear off and bludgeoned him to death.
Ouellette then changed into the dead priest's clothes, stole his
wallet and dragged the body into a corner of the church, where he
covered the bloodied corpse with a green cloth, police have said.
</P>
<P>
   The priest's body was found in the church sanctuary Friday
morning when worshippers arrived for an early morning service.
Ouellette was discovered wandering inside the church by lay workers
who called police.
</P>
<P>
   Ouellette was sent to the state psychiatric hospital in
Middletown shortly after his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The former U.S. Marine developed severe mental illness in his
late 20s and wandered in and out of Bristol, the town where he grew
up, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Ouellette's family has said he suffers from manic-depression and
behaves erratically when he is not taking medication. Police said
Ouellette stopped taking the drugs months before the murder.
</P>
<P>
   The killing led to a proposal at the state Capitol that would
allow the state to force psychiatric patients with violent
tendencies to take their medications. The bill died in committee,
but sponsors have said they may try to revive it as an amendment to
another piece of legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Ouellette is due back in court on June 20 for a pretrial
conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-02-00 0301 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000502.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 04:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate passes downtown development deal  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The state Senate voted early this morning
to sink $455 million into the Adriaen's Landing project and settle
a dispute over labor issues that threatened to tank the deal and
unravel the state's $12.3 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill passed 30-6 at 3:37 a.m. after more than two
hours of debate. The measure is expected to be OK'd today by the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a decision we knew was coming,'' said Senate President
Pro Tempore Kevin Sullivan, D-West Hartford. ''We have probably the
most clear sense of direction that has ever been in front of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the Hartford waterfront development project include a
700-room hotel, a convention center, entertainment and retail space
and nearly 400 housing units. Also part of the package is a $90
million stadium in East Hartford for the University of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,400 construction jobs and more than 1,100 permanent jobs
are expected to be created.
</P>
<P>
   The $771 million project will be tax exempt for 15 years, and
critics say spending $455 million of public money on it is a waste.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll be feeding this white elephant for years, but we won't
be feeding it peanuts,'' said Sen. Thomas Gaffey, D-Meriden.
''We'll be feeding it millions and millions of state taxpayer
money.''
</P>
<P>
   The public funding portion of the project has hinged on a
commitment of $210 million in private financing, a threshold Gov.
John G. Rowland says has been met.
</P>
<P>
   The Waterford Group, which has developed the Mohegan Sun casino
in Montville and operates other Connecticut hotels, is one of the
project's major private sponsors. Operators Len and Marc Wolman
have said they'll spend $20 million to build the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wolman's threatened to back out of the deal Friday when
some Senate Democrats wanted to introduce a measure requiring
binding arbitration to settle disputes between unionized hotel
workers and their bosses.
</P>
<P>
   After negotiations Monday, officials from the Hotel &AMP; Restaurant
Employees and Bartenders Union of the AFL-CIO dropped their binding
arbitration demands. Instead, they settled for workers to have the
right to organize without interference from their bosses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, workers would earn a ''standard wage'' -- the
average pay of similar jobs in the state.
</P>
<P>
   That means dishwashers and room attendants at the Adriaen's
Landing hotel would make about $9.50 an hour, said Laura Moye, an
organizer with the Hotel &AMP; Restaurant union. Without that
agreement, those workers would be making about $6.50.
</P>
<P>
   ''We went into this trying to raise wages for Hartford
residents,'' Moye said. ''And we got that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Edith Prague, who voted against the plan, said the bill
doesn't make enough promises for workers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The purpose of spending this money is to revitalize the city
of Hartford,'' said Prague, D-Columbia. ''The only way we'll
revitalize Hartford is to revitalize the lives of people who live
here. The way to do that is to give people good paying jobs with
benefits and a pension.''
</P>
<P>
   The labor tussle jeopardized a bipartisan agreement on the
state's $12.3 billion budget when Rowland said Friday he would not
approve it until the Adriaen's Landing deal was passed in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland spokesman Dean Pagani said the governor would sign a
necessary document to implement the budget as soon as the Adriaen's
Landing package passes both the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly is expected to pass the budget after the
House approves the Adriaen's Landing plan today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
