<DOCNO> APW20000502.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 07:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Coast thefts of heavy equipment tied to ring  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WILMINGTON (AP) -- A multistate crime ring that stole and sold
heavy equipment and tractor-trailers along the East Coast was
broken up after one owner saw his stolen bulldozer at a building
site, authorities say. A Staten Island man has been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three recovered pieces of construction equipment, farm
machinery, commercial vehicles and trailers were worth about $1.5
million, officials said. The thefts occurred all over the East
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Thieves were able to drive away with much of the construction
and farm equipment because many models from the same manufacturer
don't have unique keys, said Ralph Smith, an inspector with North
Carolina Division of Motor Vehicles. In many cases, one key fits
all, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers with the Brunswick County Sheriff's Department and the
DMV enforcement section arrested the man they believe was the
ringleader on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The officers put out word through a middleman who helped sell
the property that a buyer was in the market for a 53-foot trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Kauffman, of Staten Island, arrived at an abandoned lot
in Burgaw, N.C., with a stolen trailer for sale, pulled by a truck
stolen two years ago in New York, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman, 36, was arrested on 23 counts of possession of stolen
property and conspiracy to steal as well as one count of altering a
vehicle identification number.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they expect to arrest as many as 11 more
people, including some who bought the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   A few people bought without knowing the equipment was stolen,
but most knew the equipment was hot or should have known because of
the low prices, officials said. Some of the pieces of equipment
were worth $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   The middleman, whom police would not identify, helped set up
last week's sting.
</P>
<P>
   State and local authorities said their break in the case came
when a man driving past a construction site near Burgaw recognized
his stolen bulldozer at work even though it had been modified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
