<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 09:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DioGuardi enters from the right  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSSINING, N.Y. (AP) -- A Giuliani spokesman said today he would
not rule out a write-in campaign to win the Conservative Party
nomination against former Rep. Joseph DioGuardi.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden candidacy of DioGuardi, a Republican who says Rudolph
Giuliani is too liberal, endangers the mayor's grasp on the
conservative votes he may need to beat Democrat Hillary Rodham
Clinton in the race for a U.S. Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment on a New York Post report this morning that
Giuliani could attempt to win a Conservative primary as a write-in
candidate, Giuliani campaign spokesman Bruce Teitelbaum said:
''We're keeping our options open and certainly one of those options
is to consider a primary.
</P>
<P>
   ''The way you get there is open to discussion and we're willing
to consider all options. We still think the door is open with
respect to discussions with the Conservative Party chairman, but
that doesn't preclude other options,'' Teitelbaum said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he was confident he would win a Conservative Party
primary. But state party Chairman Michael Long, who has refused to
back Giuliani because of the mayor's support for abortion rights,
could probably block a primary if he settles on DioGuardi.
</P>
<P>
   DioGuardi, who announced Monday that he wants to be the
Conservative Party candidate, said he's not worried about catching
up to the fund-raising totals of Giuliani and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''They need a lot more money than me,'' DioGuardi said. ''They
have to disguise who they are. She has to disguise that she comes
from Arkansas, he has to disguise that he believes in partial-birth
abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not that Giuliani isn't conservative enough; he's not
conservative at all,'' said DioGuardi, in announcing he would seek
the Conservative, Right to Life and Independence party lines on the
November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   In close New York races -- the Giuliani-Clinton race is a
statistical tie, according to a Quinnipiac College Poll out Monday
-- small-party endorsements can mean victory. No Republican has won
a statewide race without the Conservative line since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, they're popping the champagne corks at Clinton
campaign headquarters,'' said GOP consultant and television
commentator Jay Severin, who is not involved in the race. ''You
could almost run a dead body on the Conservative line and attract
enough votes to defeat the Republican candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   DioGuardi, 59, of Ossining, said he expects to win the
Conservative and Right to Life nominations but realizes Giuliani is
the likely Republican candidate. He said his announcement had
nothing to do with the mayor's recent prostate cancer diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are many people in New York who are not going to vote if
Giuliani and Clinton are the only choices,'' DioGuardi said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spokeswoman Karen Dunn said the campaign had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Long called DioGuardi ''the right candidate'' Monday but held
off on any formal endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   He said DioGuardi could ''blow this into a three-way race'' by
taking votes ''from conservative-minded Democrats and also real
Republicans'' -- the very voters Giuliani is targeting.
</P>
<P>
   DioGuardi, who was born in the Bronx, was a two-term incumbent
who lost his seat in 1988 and failed again in congressional races
in 1992 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He is president of the Albanian American Civic League -- his
father emigrated from an Albanian village in Italy -- and was a
proponent of U.S. military action in Kosovo. He is a certified
public accountant.
</P>
<P>
   The former congressman said Giuliani is a competent mayor but
''hasn't shown any reason to think he can deal with foreign policy,
national security, military morale, any of the things you have to
do as a senator.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton, ''She's a moving van away from the most
scandal-scarred White House maybe in our history,'' DioGuardi said.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   AP Political Writer Marc Humbert and Associated Press Writer
Beth J. Harpaz contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
