<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 49; Nasdaq Down 25  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were slightly lower at the start of
trading today as AT&AMP;T fell after delivering a cautious profit
outlook.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 49.09 at 10,762.69.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was down 7.69 at 1,460.56, and the Nasdaq composite index
was down 25.40 at 3,932.68.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T fell 5 7/16 to 43 5/16 after lowering its earnings
forecasts for fiscal year 2000, saying the competitive
long-distance market is cutting into consumer phone revenue. For
the first quarter, AT&AMP;T posted operating profit of $1.73 billion,
or 53 cents per share. That matched the estimates of analysts
surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Also, shares of AT&AMP;T's new Wireless Group fell 2 to 32 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   The broader market was fairly quiet, hemmed in by a lack of news
on the inflation fronts. The Federal Reserve holds its next
policy-making meeting on May 16, and many investors are expecting
the Fed to raise interest rates by a quarter-percentage point.
Recent signs of booming economic growth have stimulated some
concerns that the Fed could raise rates by as much as a
half-percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates are generally bad for stocks, so fears of
a sharper-than-expected increase are likely to hang over the market
until the Fed's next meeting, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 124.60 million
shares, slightly ahead of Monday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.66 to 517.27.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.2 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.3 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.3 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
