<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conservative Party boss says Giuliani wants meeting  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSSINING, N.Y. (AP) -- The head of the state Conservative Party
and aides to Rudolph Giuliani said today that the New York City
mayor is pressing ahead with efforts to win the party's backing for
his Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Party Chairman Michael Long confirmed that the New York City
mayor is seeking a meeting with him. Meanwhile, Giuliani's campaign
manager, Bruce Teitelbaum, said the mayor might also attempt to
collect enough petition signatures to justify a Sept. 12
Conservative Party primary.
</P>
<P>
   Long continued to say the mayor must come out in favor of a ban
on what critics call ''partial-birth abortion'' and refuse Liberal
Party support if he is to have a chance at winning Conservative
Party backing. That has been Long's position for months.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, an abortion rights supporter, has refused to back a
ban on the procedure. He also counts among his top political
advisers Liberal Party boss Raymond Harding.
</P>
<P>
   In close New York races -- the Giuliani-Clinton race is a
statistical tie, according to a Quinnipiac College Poll out Monday
-- small-party endorsements can mean victory. No Republican has won
a statewide race without the Conservative line since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Giuliani said he had talked to Long and expressed
interest in the Conservative line.
</P>
<P>
   Long said this morning that one of the mayor's advisers -- he
wouldn't identify which one -- had telephoned on Monday to say
Giuliani wanted to meet with Long. The party chairman said a
Giuliani adviser has promised to call back by the middle of this
week to set up such a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Long was also critical of the way the mayor was dealing with the
possibility of getting Conservative Party backing. ''This all
should have been done a year ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Teitelbaum said the mayor was not ruling out a
petition effort to force a Conservative Party primary against
former Rep. Joseph DioGuardi or any other candidate party leaders
might come up with.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden candidacy of DioGuardi, a Republican who says
Giuliani is too liberal, endangers the mayor's grasp on the
Conservative votes he may need to beat Democrat Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're keeping our options open and certainly one of those
options is to consider a primary,'' Teitelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The way you get there is open to discussion and we're willing
to consider all options. We still think the door is open with
respect to discussions with the Conservative Party chairman, but
that doesn't preclude other options,'' Teitelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he was confident he would win a Conservative Party
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Long said this morning that he had the votes on the party's
executive committee to block any move to put Giuliani's name on the
Conservative Party primary ballot. Giuliani forces believe that if
they collected enough signatures from Conservative Party members,
Long and other party leaders would be under great pressure to allow
a primary with Giuliani as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the intrigue in New York's third-party politics, a
spokesman for the Clinton campaign said today the first lady would
appear at the state Liberal Party's policy committee meeting
Saturday to interview for its nomination. Giuliani also plans to
seek that nomination and even Clinton aides privately concede he
will probably get it.
</P>
<P>
   ''People want to talk to her about why she's running for the
Senate and she's going to do it,'' Clinton spokesman Howard Wolfson
said when asked why she would even bother to attend the Liberal
Party gathering.
</P>
<P>
   DioGuardi, 59, of Ossining, who announced Monday that he wants
to be the Conservative Party candidate, said he's not worried about
catching up to the fund-raising totals of Giuliani and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''They need a lot more money than me,'' DioGuardi said. ''They
have to disguise who they are. She has to disguise that she comes
from Arkansas, he has to disguise that he believes in partial-birth
abortions.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not that Giuliani isn't conservative enough; he's not
conservative at all,'' said DioGuardi, in announcing he would seek
the Conservative, Right to Life and Independence party lines on the
November ballot.
</P>
</TEXT>
