<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 60; Nasdaq down 38  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were lower in quiet trading today as AT&AMP;T
fell after delivering a cautious profit outlook.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 60.50 at 10,751.28.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also fell. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 8.55 at 1,459.70, and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 38.26 at 3,919.82.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T fell 5 11/16 to 43 1/16 after lowering its earnings
forecasts for fiscal year 2000, saying the competitive
long-distance market is cutting into consumer phone revenue. For
the first quarter, AT&AMP;T posted operating profit of $1.73 billion,
or 53 cents per share. That matched the estimates of analysts
surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Also, shares of AT&AMP;T's new Wireless Group fell 1 5/16 to 33
3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were mixed after three days of solid gains.
Microsoft gave up some of its Monday advance and was down 2 5/16 at
71 1/8, and Broadcom rose 9 1/4 to 183 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   The broader market was fairly quiet, hemmed in by a lack of news
on the inflation fronts. The Federal Reserve holds its next
policy-making meeting on May 16, and many investors are expecting
the Fed to raise interest rates by a quarter-percentage point.
Recent signs of booming economic growth have stimulated some
concerns that the Fed could raise rates by as much as a
half-percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates are generally bad for stocks, so fears of
a sharper-than-expected increase are likely to hang over the market
until the Fed's next meeting, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some people have gone to the sidelines to wait for the
employment data due out Friday,'' said Arthur Hogan, chief market
analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ''There's no sense of doom, but
investors are definitely waiting for more data to gauge the
strength of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 305.93 million
shares, slightly ahead of Monday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.99 to 517.94.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
