<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 75-Year-Old Tenor Back for 'Otello'  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Imagine Willie Mays coming back to baseball --
and picking the seventh game of the World Series for his return.
</P>
<P>
   Switch home plate for Carnegie Hall, and that's pretty close to
what 75-year-old tenor Carlo Bergonzi is doing by performing
Giuseppe Verdi's fiendishly difficult opera ''Otello'' for his
first time. Most tenors start fading in their 50s.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's little space left for me -- I'm going towards 80,'' the
tenor said with a smile after a grueling four-hour dress rehearsal
for Wednesday's performance with the Opera Orchestra of New York,
Eve Queler conducting.
</P>
<P>
   So closely watched was this musical moment that within hours,
the Internet was abuzz with comments from aficionados. The verdict:
amazing.
</P>
<P>
   The aging, paunchy Bergonzi has a voice that is a force of
nature. His searing performance as the Venetian Moor of
Shakespeare's drama ''brought me to tears,'' Queler said after the
rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian tenor hit his share of artistic home runs as a top
Verdi tenor for five decades. In 1994, he sang his Carnegie Hall
farewell and retreated to the Italian countryside to run an inn in
Busseto, near Verdi's birthplace, and teach.
</P>
<P>
   After a 50-year career, Bergonzi didn't need Carnegie Hall,
which is a megaphone of a stage that draws fierce critics. But he
couldn't resist this musical curve ball.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jon Vickers retired in the 1980s, Placido Domingo has been
the only truly stellar Otello, and Luciano Pavarotti sang the role
to mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Then last June in New York, Queler heard Bergonzi sing a single
aria from ''Otello'' -- ''Niun mi tema,'' meaning, ''Let no one fear
me'' -- as the Moor surrenders to authorities after strangling his
wife in a jealous fit.
</P>
<P>
   The conductor was impressed, and their agents talked.
</P>
<P>
   At Saturday's rehearsal, weeks shy of his 76th birthday, he sang
full voice, hitting high notes that would be the envy of far
younger men. ''He holds the high notes more than any tenor who sang
Otello ever has,'' Queler said.
</P>
<P>
   And he is one of the few artists who can sing as softly and
tenderly as Verdi wrote parts of the score -- a marking of pppppp,
or six times pianissimo. Domingo, in his 50s, doesn't have that
kind of control.
</P>
<P>
   In a youth-driven time, said conductor Queler, ''Bergonzi is
thrilling. And his age is a benefit, not a liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a few slightly raspy notes work in his favor, lending a
heartbreaking power to the tormented figure of Otello.
</P>
<P>
   The tenor's secret? A vocal technique -- modeled after that of
the nearly forgotten tenor Aureliano Pertile -- that has sustained
Bergonzi while his contemporaries have long since retired.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't do Otello at my age without the technique,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, in the twilight of his career, he will dominate an
orchestra, chorus and solo cast half his age, including a Pavarotti
protege, soprano Kallen Esperian, as Desdemona. His wife of 40-plus
years, his two sons and two grandchildren are all in New York for
the event.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've sung all of Verdi's operas, wearing them like a necklace
of pearls,'' he said. ''And this,'' he said of the deadly love
story, ''is the last -- my black pearl.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1320 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
