<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> VH1 Introduces VH1 Classic  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- So far, VH1 chief executive John Sykes has
avoided the topic with his old buddy John Mellencamp. It's not a
conversation he's looking forward to.
</P>
<P>
   Would YOU like to tell the notoriously cranky rock singer that
he's getting too old for your network?
</P>
<P>
   Sykes was Mellencamp's manager for a time in the 1980s, when the
singer was a mainstay on VH1's younger cousin, MTV. During the last
decade, Mellencamp's music moved across the dial to VH1, which
shoots for an audience around age 30.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 48-year-old Mellencamp's videos are about to be sent to
the newest rung of Viacom's entertainment ladder, VH1 Classic,
which debuts as an all-digital channel later this month. The new
network will concentrate on the favorites of baby boomers, the
generation that grew up on the Beatles, Rolling Stones and Motown.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the cradle-to-grave philosophy at Viacom, or at
least cradle-to-gray hair.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom grabs television viewers early with its popular
children's channel, Nickelodeon. When the hormones start raging,
it's on to MTV. When it's time to settle down and get a job, VH1
beckons. Now VH1 Classic is the next step.
</P>
<P>
   Since he arrived at VH1 in 1994, Sykes has given focus to a
music-based network that often lacked one. He has gradually built
VH1's credibility and power, to the point where January was the
most-watched month in the network's history. The dishy series about
rock stars' dirty laundry, ''Behind the Music,'' is an institution,
and the yearly divas concert is a rite of spring.
</P>
<P>
   Yet programming at Viacom network is like shooting at a moving
target, and Sykes knows he had better be prepared to move, too.
</P>
<P>
   MTV has remade itself over the past few years into ground zero
of the teen pop phenomenon, driving the sales of 'N Sync,
Backstreet Boys, Britney Spears and Christina Aguilera. VH1 faces a
similar transformation.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you are 30 years old, you were 20 when you first heard
Nirvana,'' he said. ''You were 15 when you first heard Run DMC.
It's only logical that we will adopt those viewers to our format.
The culture at MTV Networks is about staying true to your
demographic and letting the audience move through.''
</P>
<P>
   Artists like Jewel, D'Angelo, Sheryl Crow and Macy Gray are the
new VH1 mainstays. The veterans -- Mellencamp, Steely Dan, Don
Henley -- won't be forgotten, but they're most likely to be seen
reliving their glories on a program like ''Storytellers.''
</P>
<P>
   It also means being ready to accept the generation that grew up
musically on rap as it approaches age 30, even if it makes for a
dividing line with older viewers who have never embraced the style.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to play it,'' Sykes said. ''We'd be crazy not to.
Otherwise, we're going to fade away with our viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of VH1's new series are variations on themes already
explored on MTV. While MTV has ''Fanatic,'' which follows
star-struck music devotees as they encounter their heroes, VH1 will
debut ''Fan Club'' this month. The new series focuses on the people
who obsess over certain musicians.
</P>
<P>
   VHI has also recently begun a live music news show, ''The Daily
One,'' that recalls MTV's ''Total Request Live.''
</P>
<P>
   While ''TRL'' with Carson Daly has been the key to MTV's
transformation, it has the advantage of a built-in audience ready
to sit in front of the television when it gets home from school.
VH1 has no such luxury. The network is experimenting with the show
at 2 p.m. ET, but Sykes said it is likely to eventually land on the
early evening schedule.
</P>
<P>
   He wants ''The Daily One'' to be ''like the friend you used to
have who you gossiped about music with, that you no longer have
because you're an accountant and you sit next to someone who can't
stand music.''
</P>
<P>
   VH1 has other new series, hoping that at least one will catch on
like ''Behind the Music.'' In March, it began the documentary
series ''Rockstory,'' with ''ER'' actor Anthony Edwards as host,
that looks at particular moments with an impact on society. ''Sound
Affects,'' premiering in June, talks to people whose lives have
been changed by a song.
</P>
<P>
   The network is also branching out into original movies. One
picture looks back on the lives of music's prefab four, the
Monkees. Another, ''Out of Sync,'' is a comedy about a luckless
music producer who inadvertently discovers a housewife with an
extraordinary voice.
</P>
<P>
   Movies are the natural evolutionary step for a network that,
like MTV, began its life by chiefly showing music videos. Now
executives prefer longer-form programming so viewers are more apt
to stay tuned longer and watch the advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's this preconceived notion that a music channel has to
play videos all day because that's what MTV did 20 years ago,''
Sykes said. ''It's a totally different audience now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
