<DOCNO> APW20000502.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Leader's Condition a Mystery  </HEADLINE>
By GINNY PARKER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- When Japan's prime minister suddenly collapsed
after a stroke last month, reporters and camera crews rushed to the
downtown Tokyo hospital where he was taken, setting up camp and
awaiting word on his condition.
</P>
<P>
   Word never came.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a month after Keizo Obuchi's stroke set off a political
succession crisis, information about his condition remains scant.
Doctors have yet to give a news conference. Politicians have
offered details only grudgingly, and then often have conflicted
with each other. And though Obuchi remains in his hospital room in
a coma, virtually all the reporters are gone.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, such is often the case. Public disclosure is still a
novel and frequently ignored concept here. Doctors regularly refuse
to show patients their charts; juvenile court records are closed
even to the victims.
</P>
<P>
   But there are signs that the blackout over Obuchi has caused
some re-examination.
</P>
<P>
   National newspapers have tried to piece together the foggy chain
of events that followed Obuchi's collapse while criticizing the
apparent leadership vacuum that resulted.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition party leaders, meanwhile, are shouting cover-up. They
say the murkiness calls into question the right of Obuchi's
successor, former Liberal Democratic Party secretary-general
Yoshiro Mori, to govern. They have demanded that Obuchi's doctors
appear before Parliament for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no transparency at all in this process. It was one
lie after another,'' said Osamu Matsumoto, an official with the
opposition Democratic Party of Japan. ''If you've got leaders
standing on lies, who knows when the citizens will be tricked.''
</P>
<P>
   The events following Obuchi's collapse have been mired in
secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   He was hospitalized early April 2, but the government failed to
announce it for 22 hours, and 12 more hours passed before the
nation learned he was in a coma. Officials at the prime minister's
office even told reporters Obuchi was at home when he was actually
in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Cabinet Secretary Mikio Aoki, meanwhile, took over as
acting prime minister. A few leading party members then met behind
closed doors to select a successor, Mori, who was later voted in by
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Holes have since arisen in the official story. Aoki, for
instance, said the ailing Obuchi ordered him to take over. Other
senior Liberal Democratic Party officials told versions that
contradicted this, then retracted them later.
</P>
<P>
   Details about the health of politicians and candidates are
typically kept under wraps in Japan. The hospital where Obuchi is
staying will not comment on his condition. On Tuesday, officials
there refused to meet with a reporter and would only speak briefly
via a telephone in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Cabinet Secretary Aoki -- the one government official
speaking publicly on Obuchi's condition -- repeatedly says he cannot
answer specific questions because he is not a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The official silence comes in a nation where freedom of
information is still a new concept. Until lawmakers last year
passed a bill to increase public access to government information,
details about decision-making in Japanese government ministries
were not made public.
</P>
<P>
   Even as information begins to flow a bit more freely, officials
in many sectors and all levels of society often show little
compunction about withholding details from citizens. The problems
even extend to law enforcement: Earlier this year, a state police
chief and other officials admitted to covering up another officer's
drug use to protect the ''dignity'' of the police department.
</P>
<P>
   ''The officials should at least be up front about things that
directly affect us,'' said vocational school student Kazue
Ichinose, 19. ''They're not even doing that. It's just going to
cause more problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1338 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000502.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Flood Victims Leave Camps  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) -- With the rainy season over and river
levels receding, hundreds of thousands of Mozambicans displaced by
floods are leaving aid camps to return to demolished villages.
</P>
<P>
   About 2 million of Mozambique's 19 million people lost their
homes in the floods that began in February, and many of those
pouring from the camps carried plastic sheeting and tents.
</P>
<P>
   A mass exodus has nearly emptied the country's largest
displacement camp, which once held 60,000 people. Only 2,500
remained Tuesday at Chaqualane, about 125 miles northeast of
Maputo, the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Flood victims have left other refugee camps in central and
southern Mozambique, although many return periodically to get food.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 600,000 people will need to be fed until the end of
September, said Inyene Udoyen, a spokesman for the World Food
Program.
</P>
<P>
   Roads have been restored to many areas, making it possible for
the food program to truck in food, but the funding is drying up for
helicopters that reach remote areas.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. agency has 14 aircraft, but many will be phased out by
May 12, Udoyen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''At present we are reaching pretty much everyone,'' he said.
''We hope to keep one helicopter flying from Maputo and one from
Beira, and maybe one C-130 cargo plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding Mozambique's infrastructure will take years and an
estimated $450 million, which aid groups hope to raise at an
international donors conference beginning Wednesday in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Though water supplies have been re-established and basic
infrastructure rebuilt in some flood-stricken towns, much work
needs to be done in rural areas, UNICEF's Ian Macleod said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think some quite remarkable progress has been made there but
there is certainly a long way to go,'' he said. ''About 60 schools
have reopened in the last 10 or 11 days, which is an important step
back to normality.''
</P>
<P>
   The floods damaged more than 600 primary schools and 620 miles
of roads, downed 250 miles of power lines and swept away the crops
and cattle of farmers in the southeast African nation, one of the
world's poorest.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people scrambled up trees and onto rooftops
to escape the floodwaters, and await helicopter rescue, but the
flooding killed 700 Mozambicans.
</P>
<P>
   Most flood victims were subsistence farmers who lived in reed
and mud huts. While aid agencies distributed tons of seed and
agricultural implements, very little funding was made available for
building materials, Macleod said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
