<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 44; Nasdaq Dips 32  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were lower in quiet trading today as AT&AMP;T
fell after delivering a cautious profit outlook.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 44.67 at 10,767.11.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also fell. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 6.46 at 1,461.79, and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 32.97 at 3,925.11.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T fell 6 15/16 to 41 13/16 after lowering its earnings
forecasts for fiscal year 2000, saying the competitive
long-distance market is cutting into consumer phone revenue. For
the first quarter, AT&AMP;T posted operating profit of $1.73 billion,
or 53 cents per share. That matched the estimates of analysts
surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Also, shares of AT&AMP;T's new Wireless Group fell 1 13/16 to 32
11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were mixed after three days of solid gains.
Microsoft gave up some of its Monday advance and was down 2 7/16 at
71.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's decline came after Mary Meeker, an influential
technology stock analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said she
believes Microsoft's stock is fairly valued in the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   Meeker said in a research note she believes the proposal to
break the company in two to satisfy antitrust concerns is an
excessive punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ''Remember, we aren't at all opposed to disciplining Microsoft,
but we think a break up is simply too harsh,'' the note said.
</P>
<P>
   Several other prominent technology stocks rose. Broadcom was up
9{ to 183} and Qualcomm was up 5 15/16 at 115 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   The broader market was fairly quiet, hemmed in by a lack of news
on the inflation fronts. The Federal Reserve holds its next
policy-making meeting on May 16, and many investors are expecting
the Fed to raise interest rates by a quarter-percentage point.
Recent signs of booming economic growth have stimulated some
concerns that the Fed could raise rates by as much as a
half-percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates are generally bad for stocks, so fears of
a sharper-than-expected increase are likely to hang over the market
until the Fed's next meeting, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some people have gone to the sidelines to wait for the
employment data due out Friday,'' said Arthur Hogan, chief market
analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ''There's no sense of doom, but
investors are definitely waiting for more data to gauge the
strength of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 652.01 million
shares, ahead of Monday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.66 to 518.27.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
