<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka May Be Seeking India Help  </HEADLINE>
By DILSHIKA JAYAMAHA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- Sri Lanka's president has asked India
for help in evacuating some 40,000 troops trapped by Tamil Tiger
rebels advancing on their former capital, a television station
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sri Lanka's first appeal has been to India,'' a news report on
Telshan Network said.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian Embassy spokesman in Colombo declined comment on the
TV report, except to say it was ''speculative.'' But an official
close to the embassy, speaking on condition of anonymity, confirmed
the Sri Lankan government had requested India's aid.
</P>
<P>
   The TV report was broadcast after President Chandrika
Kumaratunga met with opposition leaders to discuss how to prevent
Jaffna, once the center of Tamil culture, from being retaken by the
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The Tamil uprising began in Jaffna in 1983. From 1990-95, the
Tamils ran a virtually independent state in the Jaffna peninsula on
the northern tip of the island. Sri Lankan troops drove the rebels
out of the city of 500,000 people in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The National Sangha Council -- a group of Buddhist monks -- also
has agreed that the Indian military should intervene to prevent the
fall of Jaffna to the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam.
</P>
<P>
   The monks had protested when Indian troops were sent to the
island nation in 1987 to disarm the rebels. But over the weekend
the monks, who are extremely influential in a country where 76
percent of the population is Buddhist, met an Indian envoy and
appealed for Indian military help.
</P>
<P>
   Tamil Tiger rebels, who overran the key Pallai military base
over the weekend, unleashed an intense artillery barrage on the
navy camp Tuesday in a bid to control the sea supply route,
military officials and rebel sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Ministry said its soldiers were holding onto the
camp 15 miles south of Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the International Committee of the Red Cross said the
rebels had handed over the bodies of 42 soldiers killed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The military said 14 officers and soldiers were killed and 222
others were wounded Sunday. The rebel's clandestine Voice of Tigers
Radio said Tuesday that 10 of their combatants died.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists have been barred from the war front and telephone
links to the area have been cut.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas are fighting for a separate homeland. They say
minority Tamils have been discriminated against by the Sinhalese
majority.
</P>
<P>
   India is home to 52 million Tamils, who have ties with Sri
Lanka's 3.2 million Tamils.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1440 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000502.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Examiner Publisher Recants Comment  </HEADLINE>
By BOB EGELKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The San Francisco Examiner's publisher
testified that he offered Mayor Willie Brown favorable treatment in
editorials if Brown would support Hearst Corp.'s purchase of the
San Francisco Chronicle. Hours later, the publisher said he
misspoke.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy White testified Monday that he told Brown at a lunch
meeting last August, several weeks after the $660 million purchase
of the Chronicle had been announced, that the mayor could expect
''more favorable treatment'' in Examiner editorials if he supported
the sale.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail afterward to the head of Hearst's newspaper
division and read in court, White said: ''I asked Willie how I was
going to justify to my superiors in New York wanting to support him
and cooperate with him when he was seeming to go out of his way to
make our lives difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   White later recanted his U.S. District Court testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was tired and confused by the question,'' White said in a
statement distributed by Hearst Corp. ''The implication of my
answer that the pages of The Examiner can be influenced, under any
circumstances, is absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst also denied that any special treatment had been offered.
''It is not now -- nor has it ever been -- a policy of the San
Francisco Examiner to trade favorable editorial coverage for any
gains, including political influence,'' Hearst said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's trial lawyer, Garry Halling, said the lawsuit was
designed ''to make headlines.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What you see in here will be entertaining, often misleading
and untrue. But it will also be largely irrelevant to the antitrust
issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic mayor had no comment on the testimony, his office
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown initially was outspoken against Hearst's plans for the
papers, urging the White House and Justice Department to block the
Chronicle sale until Hearst found a buyer for the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   In the months after his Aug. 30 lunch meeting with White, Brown
worked behind the scenes to support the Examiner sale to the Fang
family, owners of a free local newspaper, even negotiating for a
bigger Hearst subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst eventually agreed to give the Fangs $66 million to take
the paper off its hands.
</P>
<P>
   White was the first witness in a trial on a lawsuit challenging
Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle. The suit was filed by Clint
Reilly, a real estate investor, losing candidate for mayor and
unsuccessful bidder for the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's lawsuit contends Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle was
rigged and that its transfer of the Examiner to a local publisher
is a sham, designed to give Hearst a local newspaper monopoly after
more than a century of competition.
</P>
<P>
   All three publishers -- Hearst, the Chronicle Publishing Co., and
Ted Fang, the prospective publisher of the Examiner -- say their
transactions will promote competition, not destroy it.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department found no antitrust violations in the sale
and approved the dissolution of the joint operating agreement under
which the Chronicle and Examiner have been published since 1965.
The agreement, which combines business operations but keeps
editorial staffs separate, was scheduled to run through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   However, U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker stunned the
publishers by issuing a restraining order against the Chronicle
sale March 30, a day before it was to be completed.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's testimony, White also said he repeatedly warned the
rival Chronicle last year that it faced all-out competition after
the JOA ended in 2005, even though he knew the Examiner was doomed
on its own.
</P>
<P>
   It was part of a ''blowfish theory'' -- inflating oneself to look
fierce -- that the Examiner's owners devised to bluff the larger
Chronicle into returning to negotiations over the two newspapers'
future, White testified.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle is the nation's 14th-largest newspaper with a
circulation more than four times the Examiner's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1453 </TRAILER>
