<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Upbeat After Irish Talks  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BARR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- British officials detected ''a bit more hope'' for
solving Northern Ireland's political deadlock following a day of
negotiations Tuesday, but couldn't immediately agree with Irish
colleagues on whether to follow up with more talks this week.
</P>
<P>
   No indication was given as to who, if anyone, had given ground
on the intractable issue of paramilitary disarmament, but Britain's
senior official in Northern Ireland, Peter Mandelson, told
reporters he was ''somewhat encouraged.'' He said all parties had
shown ''a willingness to resolve this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair's office announced he and his
Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, would meet again with Northern
Ireland's parties on Thursday. But two hours later, Ahern told
reporters he was ''not too sure'' whether that would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be more discussions tomorrow on the telephone
between the prime minister and myself and the officials will
probably meet again and we have kept Thursday free for
discussions,'' Ahern said. Blair's office confirmed the two sides
were still discussing the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Blair and Ahern met separately with the Ulster Unionists, the
province's main pro-British Protestant party, and the two main
Catholic parties -- Sinn Fein, the party associated with the Irish
Republican Army, and the Social Democratic and Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists' demand for the IRA to disarm and the
outlawed group's refusal to do so led to the suspension of Northern
Ireland's new power-sharing government in February. The new
government was the keystone of the peace agreement concluded on
Good Friday two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams and his delegation were the
first group to arrive at Blair's Downing Street offices Tuesday
morning -- and the last to leave Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got some answers to some issues,'' Adams said. ''We have a
lot more to do and we will continue and our hope is we will come to
a conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson said that ''the people of Northern Ireland, whose
future depends on these talks and a successful outcome, deserve a
bit more hope. That's what we're giving them today.''
</P>
<P>
   A more downbeat assessment came from David Trimble, leader of
the Ulster Unionists, who insisted the onus was on Sinn Fein and
the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really boils down the question: Are they actually prepared
to do anything?'' Trimble said. ''And they should tell us what they
are prepared to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
