<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 79; Nasdaq Falls 104  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly lower today as AT&AMP;T fell
after delivering a cautious profit outlook and investors took
profits from a recent rally in technology shares.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was down 79.34 at 10,732.44.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also fell. The Nasdaq composite index
was down 104.68 at 3,853.40, its first decline in four sessions.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 17.63 at 1,450.62.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T fell 7 1/16 to 41 11/16 after lowering its earnings
forecasts for fiscal year 2000, saying the competitive
long-distance market is cutting into consumer phone revenue. For
the first quarter, AT&AMP;T posted operating profit of $1.73 billion,
or 53 cents per share. That matched the estimates of analysts
surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Also, shares of AT&AMP;T's new Wireless Group fell 2 to 32 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were mixed after three days of solid gains as
investors took some profits. Microsoft gave up some of its Monday
advance and was down 3 1/4 at 70 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's decline came after Mary Meeker, an influential
technology stock analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said she
believes Microsoft's stock is fairly valued in the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   Meeker said in a research note she believes the proposal to
break the company in two to satisfy antitrust concerns is an
excessive punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ''Remember, we aren't at all opposed to disciplining Microsoft,
but we think a break up is simply too harsh,'' Meeker wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Several other prominent technology stocks rose. Broadcom was up
9 1/8 to 183 3/8 and Qualcomm was up 4 1/2 at 114 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   The broader market was fairly quiet, hemmed in by a lack of news
on inflation. The Federal Reserve holds its next policymaking
meeting on May 16, and many investors are expecting the Fed to
raise interest rates by a quarter-percentage point. Recent signs of
booming economic growth have stimulated some concerns that the Fed
could raise rates by as much as a half-percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates are generally bad for stocks, so fears of
a sharper-than-expected increase are likely to hang over the market
until the Fed's next meeting, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some people have gone to the sidelines to wait for the
employment data due out Friday,'' said Arthur Hogan, chief market
analyst at Jefferies &AMP; Co. ''There's no sense of doom, but
investors are definitely waiting for more data to gauge the
strength of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Economic surveys released today showed little evidence of a
slowdown to more sustainable levels. The Commerce Department said
new-home sales rose in March to their second-highest level on
record, indicating that Americans are unfazed by rising mortgage
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Conference Board said its Index of Leading Economic
Indicators, which is designed to predict economic activity three to
six months ahead, rose 0.1 percent in March, indicating continued
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 781.27 million
shares, ahead of Monday's quiet pace. On the Nasdaq, decliners led
by an 8-to-5 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.51 to 512.42.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
