<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Begins Dismantling Outposts  </HEADLINE>
Eds: This story was submitted to the Israeli military censor who
ordered a deletion.
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRYAT SHEMONA, Israel (AP) -- Army trucks loaded with fences,
mobile homes and parts for water tanks rolled south through this
border town Tuesday as Israel began dismantling outposts in south
Lebanon ahead of its July troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah guerrillas in southern Lebanon shelled an Israeli
military base that straddles the border and had already been
partially evacuated. Soldiers and firefighters rushed to put out
fires at the Livneh outpost after the mortar shells hit an oil tank
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Several civilian and army vehicles were also damaged at the
post, 38 miles west of Kiryat Shemona, the main town in the north,
the army spokesman's office said. Some shells landed in Israeli
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah said the attack was in response to Israeli shelling of
the Lebanese village of Baraachit earlier in the day. Israeli
warplanes struck back after a guerrilla attack, firing missiles
into a valley three miles northeast of the outpost. There were no
reports of casualties from any of the exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   As Israel began pulling back from some outposts in the occupied
zone, residents of northern Israel protested attempts to build a
new border fence that would leave their homes on the front line,
fearing infiltrations, bombings and shelling from Lebanese
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is packing up after 18 years of occupation in south
Lebanon and promises to be out by July 7, despite its failure to
work out security arrangements with Syria, the main power broker in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Syria and Lebanon have warned that they will not restrain
anti-Israeli guerrillas after the Israeli pullout if a
comprehensive peace agreement is not worked out beforehand.
Guerrillas have not stated clearly if they will continue
anti-Israeli attacks. Israel invaded Lebanon in 1982, then created
the security zone three years later along the frontier to prevent
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In the first stages of the withdrawal, an outpost located just
dozens of yards north of Israeli communities was evacuated Monday.
Only a few soldiers and some communications equipment remain at the
site, Israeli army officials said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Some 85 soldiers were also evacuated Monday from the Taibeh
infantry position in the central sector of the zone and equipment
has been removed from the Shreika position in the east, a Lebanese
military official said. It was not immediately known if soldiers
were moved to other bases in Lebanon or to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Livneh outpost, soldiers and temporary structures
have also been removed from the bases Srefa, inside Lebanon, and
Olesh, on the border, Israeli army officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The army spokesman confirmed forces were getting ready to
withdraw. ''There is activity all the time and this is part of the
preparation for the withdrawal,'' the spokesman's office said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in northern Israel said Tuesday that they will prevent
the army from evacuating some key bases inside the occupied zone
near their communities.
</P>
<P>
   ''We intend to fight for the border even if it means we have to
block the bulldozers with our bodies to prevent the soldiers from
evacuating,'' said Eitan Davidi, a resident of the community of
Margaliot.
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen residents protested when army sappers and tractors
came to demarcate the new border at the communal farm of Misgav Am.
The army delayed the work -- dismantling mines and building a new
border fence -- until Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   A few houses in Misgav Am encroach on Lebanese soil and will be
dismantled if Israel withdraws to a 1923 international border, as
it has indicated it will do.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the Israeli army said it would resume
participation in an international monitoring committee that reviews
an agreement between Israel and Lebanese guerrillas to avoid
targeting civilians. Israeli officials walked out of the last
committee meeting in February after an Israeli soldier was killed
in what Israel said was a violation of the agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
