<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NY voters don't like Gore or media in Elian Gonzalez case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- New York voters don't much like the way Vice
President Al Gore or the news media handled the Elian Gonzalez
case, a statewide poll reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   By a 44 percent to 24 percent margin, voters surveyed by the
Quinnipiac College Polling Institute said they disapproved of the
way Gore handled the case.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, the presumptive Democratic presidential
nominee, had called for Congress to grant the Cuban boy permanent
resident status and said the case should be handled by Family
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Clinton administration and Attorney General Janet
Reno have sought to have the case kept in federal court. She
ordered the boy's forced removal by armed officers from the home of
his Miami relatives on April 22. Elian has since been staying with
his father in the Washington area as the court case proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-five percent of New York voters said Elian should go
back to Cuba with his father. Sixteen percent said he should stay
in this country with his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-nine percent of voters said ''appropriate'' force was used
in removing the boy from the Miami home where he had been living
while 36 percent said excessive force was employed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their disapproval of Gore's handling of the Elian
Gonzalez case, the vice president still leads Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, 52 percent to 36 percent, among New York voters asked about
the presidential race. That is statistically unchanged from an
April poll from the Hamden, Conn.-based institute that had Democrat
Gore leading Republican Bush, 53 percent to 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The voters were even harsher in their feelings about the news
media's coverage of the Elian Gonzalez case. Seventy-two percent
said they disapproved while 22 percent approved.
</P>
<P>
   Voters approved of Reno's handling of the case, 54 percent to 38
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tough stuff seems to work,'' said Maurice Carroll, director of
the polling institute. ''Janet Reno is a winner for seizing
Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll of 952 registered voters was conducted April
24-30 and has a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage
points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
