<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday, May 2, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Warships Wait Off Vieques
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- With a showdown looming over the U.S. Navy's
prime Atlantic training ground, protesters who have blocked bombing for over a
year said today that federal agents would have to arrest them to clear the range
but promised they wouldn't fight back. Scores of Puerto Ricans kept a vigil at
the main gate to the restricted Navy compound on Vieques Island, jeering at
soldiers in passing Humvees. The range has been occupied by protesters since a
civilian security guard was killed by stray bombs in April 1999, releasing
pent-up frustrations throughout Puerto Rico, a U.S. territory of 4 million
people.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
ABC Returning to Time Warner
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Warner agreed today to return ABC to its cable
systems, at least temporarily bringing "Good Morning America" and "Who Wants to
be a Millionaire" back to the 3.5 million customers who had the channel blacked
out because of a corporate dispute. The cable company agreed, in effect, to an
extension to keep negotiating with the Walt Disney Co., ABC's corporate parent,
until July 15. Time Warner said that it expected ABC programming to be restored
on some of its systems by this afternoon.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Holocaust Remembrance Day Observed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli and Palestinian peace negotiators stood
side-by-side in tribute to the 6 million victims of the Holocaust today as
sirens wailed across Israel, bringing the country to a standstill for two
minutes to reflect on the horrors of the Nazi genocide. In towns and villages,
at work and at play, people stopped in their tracks when sirens went off this
morning for Holocaust Remembrance Day. In the Israeli Red Sea resort of Eilat,
negotiators interrupted peace treaty talks and stood in silence. The chief
Israeli negotiator, Oded Eran, said he appreciated the gesture of his
Palestinian colleagues, saying it was a sign of good will.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Conclusions in College Bonfire Collapse
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) -- Inadequate wiring of logs and weak oversight
of the project were factors to blame for the deadly bonfire collapse at Texas
A&AMP;M University last fall, an investigation commission announced today. The
panel, disclosing the findings of its probe into the collapse that killed 12
people last November, blamed school officials and students involved in the
construction of the bonfire for contributing to the disaster. But the panel said
drinking and student horseplay did not play a significant role in the accident.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Confederate Flag Debaters Face Gap
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- The dispute over the Confederate flag flying over the
Statehouse has exposed a generation gap in the ranks of South Carolina's civil
rights leaders. Some veterans of the struggles of the 1960s support a deal under
which the flag would be moved to a less conspicuous spot on the Statehouse
grounds. But a younger generation of blacks wants the flag removed altogether
and says the older leaders are too willing to compromise. The state Senate
agreed April 13 to lower the flag as long as it is raised again above a monument
to Confederate war dead on the Statehouse grounds. The House could vote as early
as next week.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sri Lanka May Be Seeking India Help
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- Sri Lanka's president has asked India for help in
evacuating some 40,000 troops trapped by Tamil Tiger rebels advancing on their
former capital, a television station reported today. The Indian Embassy
spokesman in Colombo declined comment on the TV report, except to say it was
"speculative." But an official close to the embassy, speaking on condition of
anonymity, confirmed the Sri Lankan government had requested India's aid.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Down 65; Nasdaq Slips 138
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly lower today as AT&AMP;T fell after
delivering a cautious profit outlook and investors took profits from a recent
rally in technology shares. Just before 4 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were
down 65.46 at 10,746.32. On the NYSE, decliners led advancers 1,664-1,314. The
Nasdaq was down 138.82 at 3,819.26.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bonds' Home Run Splashes Down in Bay
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Barry Bonds' drive soared and sailed and didn't come
down until it was in the drink -- nine games into the inaugural season at
Pacific Bell Park, there was another first: a home run that splashed down in San
Francisco Bay. "It was pretty cool to see it on TV," teammate J.T. Snow said.
"It seemed like the ball was in the air for five minutes. I got to see the boats
go after the ball." Bonds' sixth-inning, three-run shot off New York's Rich
Rodriguez, part of San Francisco's 10-3 win over the Mets last night, took a
418-foot flight over the right field wall, clearing the pierside walkway and
plopping into McCovey Cove.
</P>
