<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Armenian President Dismisses Govt.  </HEADLINE>
By AVET DEMOURIAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   YEREVAN, Armenia (AP) -- President Robert Kocharian fired
Armenia's prime minister and his government Tuesday and tightened
police security around government buildings.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement read on national television, Kocharian said he
dismissed Prime Minister Aram Sarkisian -- whose predecessor died in
a parliament shootout -- for allowing the former Soviet republic's
economy to deteriorate and ignoring discord in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently fearing unrest, Kocharian stepped up police presence
around government buildings and the headquarters of the Unity
Party, which has a majority in parliament and has shown increasing
dissatisfaction with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ''Political games of some (Cabinet) ministers became a way of
life, while economic problems snowballed,'' Kocharian said. ''Such
developments threaten to bring about the disintegration of the
army, ... a halt of investments and a drop in the country's
authority on the international scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between Kocharian and the government have mounted since
Sarkisian took office in November and named a few controversial
figures to Cabinet posts.
</P>
<P>
   According to Armenia's constitution, with the firing of the
prime minister, the government was also automatically dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Kocharian did not immediately name a new premier. He did replace
Defense Minister Vagarshak Arutyunian with Deputy Defense Minister
Mikhail Arutyunian, who is reportedly more loyal to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Sarkisian's predecessor and brother, Vazgen Sarkisian, was
killed when gunmen burst into parliament Oct. 27. The gunmen took
legislators hostage, saying they were trying to save the country
from corruption. Sarkisian, the parliament speaker and six others
were killed in a shootout before the gunmen surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   After assuming office, Aram Sarkisian pledged to improve the
country's lagging economy and boost exports. He has met with top
U.S. and Russian officials about investment and trade.
</P>
<P>
   Kocharian, a nationalist and technocrat, has had three
governments since he won presidential elections in 1998 in this
mountainous country of 3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Anger with Kocharian has been building, and some legislators
have called for his impeachment, accusing him of barring a
prosecutor from hearings on the parliament massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Communist lawmaker Khoren Sarkisian criticized Kocharian's
dismissal of the government, and the legislator said he would
collect signatures to launch impeachment proceedings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1558 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
