<HEADLINE> Chechen Militants Raid Russian Posts  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SLEPTSOVSKAYA, Russia (AP) -- Chechen militants attacked eight
Russian posts Tuesday, narrowly missing a top Russian official,
while Russian jets and helicopters pounded rebel positions in
southern Chechnya, the military said.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Koshman, the Russian government's chief envoy for
Chechnya, left a military command post about 10 minutes before the
post came under fire from rebels with grenade launchers, military
spokesmen said. No casualties were reported at the post in the
mountain town of Shatoi.
</P>
<P>
   The post was one of eight Russian checkpoints or police stations
shot at by rebel gunmen Tuesday, the Interior Ministry press center
in Chechnya said, according to the ITAR-Tass news agency. The
central military commandant's office in Grozny was hit overnight,
killing one Russian soldier, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered rebel attacks have continued for weeks despite
Russia's claim to control most of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Koshman said Russia would mine all approaches to
electric power plants in Chechnya to prevent plundering of metals.
</P>
<P>
   Metal thefts from electric plants and oil refineries have cost
Chechnya's Moscow-backed administrators tens of thousands of
dollars, Koshman told reporters. Maj. Gen. Vasily Prizemlin, the
military commandant in Grozny, said Russian forces had shot 20
people trying to smuggle out metals from plants around the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring electricity and basic services to Chechnya is a huge,
expensive challenge for the Russians. The republic's infrastructure
was devastated by Chechnya's 1994-6 separatist war and had not been
rebuilt by the time Moscow launched its latest offensive last
September.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Russian Su-25 attack jets and Su-24 bombers flew
combat missions striking at targets in the Argun gorge, a key rebel
refuge, and near the border with Georgia, the military command said
Tuesday. Russia claims that arms and fighters slip across the
mountainous border from Georgia to join the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is trying to trap rebels in the republic's nearby
southern mountains and finish them off. The rebels, although
outnumbered and outgunned, have resisted fiercely.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees continued to flee areas under Russian air and artillery
bombardment. One, Aslambek Ibragimov, tried to go home to Grozny
but returned to a refugee camp in neighboring Ingushetia because,
he said, he was forced to bribe Russian soldiers at every
checkpoint on the road home.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was stopped by a riot police officer who demanded a fine
because I had an expired pollution inspection sticker,'' Ibragimov
said Tuesday. ''I asked him where could I get my car inspected in a
destroyed city. 'It's not my problem,' was his answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1602 </TRAILER>
