<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Vs. Euro; Down Vs. Yen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro fell against the dollar on Tuesday,
approaching the all-time low that it hit last week amid concerns
that European authorities will not take aggressive steps to boost
the troubled currency.
</P>
<P>
   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at 90.73 cents,
down from 91.72 cents late Monday. During intraday trading on
Tuesday, it fell as low as 90.35 cents, just above the record low
of 90.30 cents reached on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also was quoted at 108.48 Japanese yen, down from
108.79 yen late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has been under selling pressure for the last week, and
analysts said they did not foresee an immediate rebound for the
single currency of 11 European nations that was launched in January
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts blame the euro's troubles on the strength of the
U.S. economy, which has attracted money from Europe that investors
might otherwise have put into European stocks. This outflow of
funds has caused the dollar to strengthen and has undermined the
euro.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts that European authorities would rally around a strategy
to stimulate growth and make Europe a more attractive place to
invest have added to the currency's woes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The overall general mood is not favoring the euro right now,''
said Kevin Lawrie, foreign exchange manager for Mellon Bank in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar was slightly weaker against the yen in light trading
Tuesday, a day after rallying to a two-month high against the
Japanese currency. Analysts said they expect trading to remain slow
for rest of the week, with Japanese markets closed Wednesday to
Friday for the Golden Week holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also was quoted at 1.7184 Swiss francs, up from
1.7056, and 1.4850 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4787. The British
pound rose to $1.5596 from $1.5535.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.1559 German
marks, up from 2.1326; 7.2306 French francs, up from 7.1525; and
2,134.34 Italian lire, up from 2,111.29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
