<HEADLINE> Aid Convoy Ambushed in Angola  </HEADLINE>
By CASIMIRO SIONA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUANDA, Angola (AP) -- Some 300 gunmen attacked a U.S.-chartered
aid convoy as it traveled through a rural area, killing a driver
and injuring two others, a U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
   The ambush took place Sunday in the coastal province of Benguela
along a road that links Lobito to Cubal, 250 miles south of the
capital, Luanda, according to a U.N. official who asked not to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers of the first three trucks were caught in the ambush
when the attackers, who wore UNITA rebel uniforms, opened fire from
both sides of the road, the official said by phone.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were all Angolans.
</P>
<P>
   The last truck managed to escape and return to the provincial
capital, also named Benguela.
</P>
<P>
   The trucks, chartered by U.S. aid group Catholic Relief
Services, were carrying 48 tons of food provided by the U.N. World
Food Program for displaced people in Cubal.
</P>
<P>
   Angola's civil war, which resumed in December 1998, has
drastically limited access by international aid groups to only a
few provinces in the southwestern African nation.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling outside government-held areas is dangerous. UNITA
often stages hit-and-run attacks, while armed bandits roam the
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   The government and UNITA, a Portuguese acronym for the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, began fighting after
Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
