<HEADLINE> Pastrana Aid Offers To Resign  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- President Andres Pastrana's chief of
staff offered to resign Tuesday, accused by opposition lawmakers of
profiting from his post by awarding government contracts to
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Hernandez's offer was the latest twist in a political
battle between Pastrana's government and the opposition Liberal
party over corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez denied wrongdoing, noting that the business in
question -- owned by his wife's family -- has been selling uniforms
to Colombia's police for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   A presidential spokesman said Pastrana had not yet accepted
Hernandez's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   On March 30, Pastrana announced he would hold a referendum to
dissolve Congress and hold elections for a new legislature after
the discovery of fictitious contracts worth $2.7 million by the
House of Representatives. Last week, $1.5 more million in
questionable contracts were discovered in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal lawmakers, who hold a majority in both houses, contend
that the executive branch is more corrupt and have called for
replacing the executive in the proposed referendum.
</P>
</TEXT>
