<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gannett chairman to step down as CEO; replacement named  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gannett chairman and chief executive officer
John Curley will step down as CEO on June 1. He will be replaced by
current vice chairman and president Douglas McCorkindale.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was announced at a Gannett shareholders meeting on
Tuesday at the company's Arlington, Va., headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Curley, 61, will retain the title of chairman through early next
year, according to a Gannett spokeswoman. McCorkindale will assume
the title of chairman at that time.
</P>
<P>
   ''Doug McCorkindale and I have worked together for almost 30
years,'' Curley said. ''I am extremely confident Gannett will
continue to prosper under his leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Curley, a former reporter and editor at three New Jersey
newspapers now owned by Gannett and a former reporter in New Jersey
for The Associated Press, joined Gannett in 1969. He has been CEO
since 1986, and chairman since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Curley started his journalism career at the AP, working nights
and weekends at the news cooperative in New York before obtaining a
master's degree at Columbia University in 1963. He worked for the
AP in New Jersey after graduation from 1963 to 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Curley worked as a reporter for the Asbury Park Press of Neptune
and an editor for the Perth Amboy Evening News, now the Home News
Tribune of East Brunswick, from 1967 to 1969.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1969, he joined Gannett as suburban editor of the
Rochester, N.Y., Times-Union and returned to New Jersey as editor
of The Courier-News in Bridgewater in June 1970. He was publisher
and president from August 1971 to February 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Curley ran Gannett News Service in Washington from 1974 to 1980
and then was publisher of the News-Journal in Wilmington, Del.,
before returning to Washington in 1982 to become the first editor
of USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, he became president of the Gannett newspaper division
and a member of the Gannett board of directors. A year later, he
became president and chief operating officer of the company, and in
1986 he became chief executive officer of Gannett, continuing as
president.
</P>
<P>
   When then chairman Allen H. Neuharth retired in April 1989,
Curley took his place. He remained president until September 1997,
when McCorkindale got the job.
</P>
<P>
   Curley, a 1960 graduate of Dickinson College, served as a
lieutenant in the U.S. Army before getting his master's degree from
Columbia University in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   McCorkindale, 60, has been with Gannett since 1971. In 1977, he
became a senior vice president for finance and law, and a member of
Gannett's board of directors. Two years later, he became Gannett's
chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, McCorkindale also became executive vice president and
president of the company's diversified media division. A year
later, he was named vice chairman of the board, continuing as CFO.
In 1997, he became Gannett's president. He is a graduate of
Columbia University and its law school.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett Co. Inc. publishes 74 daily newspapers in the United
States, including USA Today and seven daily newspapers in New
Jersey. The company also owns a variety of other publications,
including USA Weekend, a weekly newspaper magazine. Additionally,
Gannett operates 22 television stations and has a number of
Internet sites, including USAToday.com.
</P>
<P>
   Newsquest plc, a subsidiary of Gannett, is one of the largest
regional newspaper publishers in England. Its holdings include 11
daily newspapers and other publications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-02-00 1633 </TRAILER>
