<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Council Giving Cash To Film  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The British Film Council unveiled plans Tuesday to
pump $35 million into the country's movie business, saying it no
longer can be a ''cottage industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The council, launched April 1 as a successor to several public
film bodies, outlined plans to build on Britain's film-making links
with Europe and the United States to produce popular releases while
also nurturing new talent and less commercial projects.
</P>
<P>
   It has a budget of $240 million over three years. Some $16
million of the money -- a combination of government and lottery
funds -- will be channeled into funding mainstream films that have a
''real chance of finding bigger audiences,'' said Alan Parker, the
council's chairman and the director of ''Evita'' and ''Angela's
Ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The idea here is to move away from the cottage industry that
we all currently work in,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the money will go projects such as funds for
screenwriters and for low-budget and experimental films and a plan
to give children access to low-cost digital filmmaking equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also calls for stronger links with European producers
and an expansion of the British film office in Los Angeles in a bid
to attract more Hollywood funding.
</P>
<P>
   Since the advent of arts funding from the National Lottery in
1994, more than $160 million has been pumped into British films and
the number of movies produced in the country has skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   But the quality of the results has come in for criticism, and
few of the films have made a profit. Parker told The Sunday Times
that Britain made ''too many movies'' with sometimes ''shabby''
scripts.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are too many people with a T-shirt saying 'I want to
direct,''' he told the newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1641 </TRAILER>
