<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Expected To Get Debt Relief  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY DUNPHY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Uganda is expected to become the first poor
country to qualify for millions of dollars in debt relief under a
newly enhanced program administered by the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   However, the East African nation must first clear a World Bank
hurdle before obtaining final approval to receive $50 million a
year in debt relief over the next 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's board of directors met Tuesday to decide whether
Uganda can benefit from the high-profile debt initiative. The IMF
board signed on to the deal Monday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and leaders of other rich nations have been
promoting the debt relief program for 40 of the world's poorest
nations since their annual economic summit last June. But critics,
including Pope John Paul II and aid agencies, say the program is
slow and doesn't provide enough relief.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda was supposed to reach what lenders call the ''completion
point'' last month during the spring meetings of the two
Washington-based international financial institutions. But some IMF
nations raised strong objections to Uganda's decision to spend $36
million on a jet aircraft for President Yoweri Museveni.
</P>
<P>
   Ugandan officials said the decision to buy the secondhand jet
had been agreed on by the country's parliament and was a
justifiable expense. There was no suggestion that any money freed
up under the Highly Indebted Poor Countries debt initiative would
be involved in the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The East African nation has always been regarded as a model
country in the HIPC debt relief process. It used $37 million saved
in a previous program to increase school enrollment. Uganda now is
expected to receive $50 million under what the IMF and World Bank
call the enhanced HIPC program.
</P>
<P>
   The executive boards of both organizations, whose approval is
required for debt relief, deferred their decisions on Uganda last
month, at a time when thousands of demonstrators were gathering in
Washington. Among their demands, the protesters wanted the IMF and
World Bank to stop treating poor countries harshly and ease or
totally cancel their debt burdens.
</P>
<P>
   IMF approval of debt relief for Uganda came Monday as Stanley
Fischer was winding up his 11-week reign as the IMF's managing
director.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's Horst Koehler, former president of the European Bank
for Reconstruction and Development, assumed the top job Tuesday
after a bitter succession race in which Fischer was one of the
leading candidates to run the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard economist Jeffrey Sachs, a persistent critic of the IMF,
said Koehler must end the ''excruciatingly slow debt relief
process.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope he will provide the leadership to get this job done
now,'' Sachs said. ''He should recognize the current process is not
working and call for faster action.''
</P>
<P>
   The IMF and World Bank have promised ''deeper, faster, broader''
debt relief for 40 of the world's poorest nations. So far only five
have qualified since the program began in 1996. The IMF and World
Bank said at the meetings last month they hope to boost that number
to 20 by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: IMF: http://www.imf.org
</P>
<P>
   World Bank: http://www.worldbank.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
