   Tower Air Shuts Passenger Service
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tower Air, which filed for bankruptcy protection
earlier this year, discontinued its scheduled passenger service,
stranding at least 300 passengers at John F. Kennedy International
Airport. ''We are still operating charters and military flights but
not passenger flights,'' Pam Buoninconcri, director of corporate
relations for Tower, said today. ''We are not out of business. We
are still operating.'' Asked whether passenger flights would resume
at some point, Buoninconcri said, ''I can't predict the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberds Prepares for Liquidation
</P>
<P>
   WEST CARROLLTON, Ohio (AP) -- Furniture and appliance retailer
Roberds Inc. closed all 14 of its stores and a distribution center.
Operating under U.S. Bankruptcy Court protection since January, the
company said today that it would conduct an inventory to prepare
for liquidation. It said it expected to have a
going-out-of-business sale within three months. Roberds,
established in 1971, currently employs more than 1,300 workers. It
had six stores in the Dayton area and eight in the Atlanta market.
