<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Aims To Save Radio Stations  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Public interest groups kicked off a media
campaign Tuesday to defend a government plan authorizing hundreds
of low-power FM radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Full-page ads in The Washington Post and The New York Times
urged consumers to mail cut-out coupons to the White House and
Senate and House lawmakers. The ads accuse the broadcasting lobby
of trying ''to keep broadcasting in the hands of a few
corporations. Which means that all radio, once the most diverse and
local of mediums, sounds the same everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The Media Access Project, a public interest law firm in
Washington and the Public Media Center, a nonprofit advocacy agency
in San Francisco, jointly funded the ads, which also are appearing
in papers on Capitol Hill and about a dozen regional dailies across
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are hoping for a substantial response,'' said Andrew Jay
Schwartzman president of the Media Access Project.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission this year ordered the
creation of hundreds of low power mini-radio stations to give local
community groups, churches and schools more access to the airwaves.
Last week, it announced the first window for accepting applications
for the stations.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan is facing opposition from the National Association
of Broadcasters and some lawmakers, who say low-power stations
would add unacceptable interference on already overcrowded radio
bands. Earlier this month, the House passed legislation scaling
back the government's plan. Legislation to reverse the commission's
action is moving in the Senate as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is purely and simply about preserving interference-free
radio for the listening public. That's why public broadcasters,
religious broadcasters, radio manufacturers, and radio reading
services for the blind have joined NAB in questioning the FCC's''
low-power plan, said NAB spokesman Dennis Wharton.
</P>
<P>
   National Public Radio had urged the FCC to take more time to
study the interference matter. NPR says that public radio stations
are particularly vulnerable to potential interference because of
its music programming -- jazz and classical -- which can range from
soft to loud passages and because public radio stations are more
tightly packed together.
</P>
<P>
   ''The haste with which the FCC is acting does not service the
public interest,'' said NPR president Kevin Klose.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Media Access Project http://www.mediaaccess.org
</P>
<P>
   National Association of Broadcasters: http://www.nab.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
