<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Farmworkers Invade Buildings  </HEADLINE>
By PETER MUELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Thousands of landless farmworkers
invaded government buildings in cities across the country on
Tuesday in a new wave of protests aimed at speeding up land reform.
</P>
<P>
   Although many occupations were peaceful, police in some cities
used tear gas and rubber bullets to break up demonstrations and
arrested hundreds of protesters. Protesters reported dozens of
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The worst violence was in the southern state of Parana, where
riot troopers blocked a caravan of 34 buses carrying farmworkers to
the state capital of Curitiba.
</P>
<P>
   Local television showed police firing guns and tear gas at
protesters, who responded by throwing stones and sticks. More than
200 farmworkers were arrested and dozens were hurt, according to
the Landless Rural Workers Movement, known here as MST.
</P>
<P>
   In Rio, some 300 MST members invaded the headquarters of
Brazil's National Economic Development. They pledged to stay until
they are granted an audience with bank President Francisco Gros and
until the MST's national leadership is received by Brazilian
President Fernando Henrique Cardoso.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, some 600 MST supporters briefly occupied the
Finance Ministry offices in Sao Paulo but were expelled by police.
Farmworkers also occupied the headquarters of the government-run
Agrarian Reform Institute in Brasilia, the capital, and broke into
the offices of Brazil's Internal Revenue Service in the midwestern
city of Cuiaba.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Pedro Malan said the government will not
negotiate until protesters leave the occupied buildings.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Brazil's Labor Day holiday, other landless groups
invaded idle farmland in dozens of areas in Brazil's poor
northeast.
</P>
<P>
   The root of the conflict is Brazil's unequal land distribution.
The richest 20 percent of the people own 90 percent of the land,
while many of the poor have none.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our demands are the same as always,'' MST spokesman Nilton
Viana said by telephone from Sao Paulo. ''Land reform is stalled.
We have 74,000 families camped in tents by roadsides around the
country, waiting for a piece of land.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso, who took office in 1995, says he has distributed more
land than all previous governments combined, but MST leaders say
it's not enough. ''Any government would have done more, because the
others did nothing,'' Viana said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1816 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000502.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Approves Hmong Citizen Bill  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House approved legislation Tuesday that
would make it easier for America's former Laotian allies during the
Vietnam War to become U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill waives the English-language requirement for Hmong and
Laotians who were recruited by the CIA in Laos for covert military
actions. Proponents say the Hmong, an ethnic group in Laos, have
found it difficult to learn English because their language did not
have a written form until recently.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Bruce Vento, who announced earlier this year that he had
lung cancer and would not seek a 13th term, said in an interview
after the vote that the bill he has been pushing for a decade was
very important to him.
</P>
<P>
	   ''Most of us like to conclude things that are concludable,''
said Vento, a Democrat from Minnesota, which is home to 60,000
Hmong. ''I'm pleased that the House responded today on an
overwhelming basis.''
</P>
<P>
	   The bill passed the House bill on a voice vote with no
objections.
</P>
<P>
	   Identical legislation is pending in the Senate, where it was
sponsored by Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn. Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., is among its co-sponsors.
</P>
<P>
	   ''Learning to read in English has been the greatest obstacle for
the Lao-Hmong because written characters in the Hmong language have
only been introduced in recent years,'' Vento said on the House
floor.
</P>
<P>
	   ''In addition, their long participation and service to U.S.
forces in the Southeast Asian military conflict significantly
disrupted any chance most Lao-Hmong patriots may have had to learn
a written language.''
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the House Judiciary Committee chairman,
said the United States owed a debt to the Hmong.
</P>
<P>
	   ''Those Hmong veterans who survived the war faced severe
persecution for fighting with the U.S.,'' said Hyde, who helped
shepherd the bill to the House floor.
</P>
<P>
	   He recalled that Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura pushed for the
bill during a meeting in Washington earlier this year. The two
large men engaged in a playful arm wrestle for the cameras.
</P>
<P>
	   ''And I want to say that the fact that he let me win has nothing
to do with my support for this bill,'' Hyde quipped.
</P>
<P>
	   Philip Smith, Washington director of the Lao Veterans of
America, which had pushed for the bill, called Vento an
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
	   ''When we heard that he had cancer, we were despondent as an
organization,'' Smith said. ''This was something we could not win
without his leadership.''
</P>
<P>
	   But the group was emboldened when Vento, from his hospital bed,
had his staff call Smith to tell him he would continue to press for
the bill.
</P>
<P>
	   ''He's really our hero,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
	   According to Smith, there are roughly 70,000 Hmong and Lao
veterans in the United States, and about half are not citizens.
Most are permanent residents but are not eligible to vote or hold a
passport.
</P>
<P>
	   --------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 371
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
