<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House passes downtown development deal; governor signs bill intolaw  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Adriaen's Landing is law.
</P>
<P>
   Governor John G. Rowland on Tuesday signed legislation to spend
$455 million of state money on Hartford's $771 million riverfront
development project, touting it as a catalyst for redevelopment
across the state.
</P>
<P>
   The plan includes a 700-room hotel, a convention center,
entertainment and retail space and nearly 400 housing units. Also
planned is a $90 million stadium in East Hartford for the
University of Connecticut. The development is expected to create
about 3,400 construction jobs and more than 1,100 permanent jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone will share in this dream,'' Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill passed the House 117-34 Tuesday afternoon
following more than five hours of debate which included concerns
about attracting conventions to the city and securing corporate
sponsors. The Senate had passed the measure 30-6 at 3:37 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The project had been scheduled for a vote Friday, but a deal
collapsed when the AFL-CIO demanded language that guaranteeing the
right to organize workers at the planned hotel.
</P>
<P>
   After negotiations Monday, officials from the Hotel &AMP; Restaurant
Employees and Bartenders Union of the AFL-CIO dropped their binding
arbitration demands and settled for wording that will allow workers
to organize without interference from their bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Workers would earn a ''standard wage'' -- the average pay of
similar jobs in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our cause has been right,'' AFL-CIO President John W. Olsen
said in a written statement Tuesday. ''We forced the dialogue to
shift from creating poverty-level jobs just to appease a developer
to creating family-supporting jobs that will make Hartford a
stronger community.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders said they were pleased with the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has been a long, tedious, painful-- at times-- process, but
with good results,'' said Senate President Pro Tempore Kevin
Sullivan, D-West Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Mike Peters said he was pleased with the ''new type of
leadership'' that overcame differences to work for a common goal.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a love-in, I guess,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the project say it will benefit the state as a
whole by encouraging redevelopment throughout Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must look at Hartford as part of the overall agenda,'' said
Rep. Lenny T. Winkler, R-Groton. ''It creates a critical mass for
projects down the road. The truth is, we've never had a project
passed in this state that's been so thoroughly thought out and
analyzed.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan has changed drastically since first proposed two years
ago when it expected to revolve around a football stadium for the
New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots backed out of the deal last year, and their stadium
was replaced on the drawing board by a domed stadium for UConn's
football team.
</P>
<P>
   Plans changed again when United Technologies Corp. donated its
75-acre Rentschler Field in East Hartford for the UConn stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James A. Amann, D-Milford, criticized lawmakers for
''rushing'' the plan, saying the state should not move ahead with a
convention center before booking conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this particular time, I believe this project is flawed in
this area,'' said Amann. ''It's what I call Adriaen's crash
landing. It doesn't make sense. It's a felony in
irresponsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The $771 million project, which will be tax exempt for 15 years,
would be funded by $355 million in bonds and $100 million in
surplus funding authorized last year. Rep. Andrea L. Stillman,
D-Waterford, co-chairwoman of the bonding subcommittee, and Rowland
said $210 million in private financing has been secured.
</P>
<P>
   The Waterford Group, which has developed the Mohegan Sun casino
in Montville and operates other Connecticut hotels, is one of the
project's major private sponsors. Operators Len and Marc Wolman
have agreed to spend $20 million to build the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ''We really need to move forward on each of the elements-- the
land acquisition needs to be accomplished, the cleanup needs to be
done and simultaneously the joint reach of the components along
with all the details, documentation associated with it, of the
financial commitments ... need to be but into place,'' said Len
Wolman.
</P>
<P>
   Construction should begin next summer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''From my perspective, the risk is too great,'' said Robert A.
Landino, D-Westbrook. ''I oppose the bill, but I hope that I am
wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
