<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore: Move Vieques Training Soon  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Navy live-fire training should be moved from the
Puerto Rican island of Vieques as soon as possible, Vice President
Al Gore said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the expected Democratic presidential nominee,
expressed support for an agreement between President Clinton, the
Pentagon and Puerto Rican authorities to conduct limited training
pending the outcome of a yet-unscheduled referendum by the island's
9,400 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Gore declined, however, to say what should be done about
protesters who have been blocking the training ever since a bombing
accident killed a civilian worker last year.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have said a raid by U.S. marshals and FBI
agents to remove the protesters could happen this week.
</P>
<P>
   Other elements of the agreement include turning over some of the
two-thirds of federal land on Vieques to Puerto Ricans and a $40
million assistance package.
</P>
<P>
   Once the agreement is met, Gore said, ''then we should move to
the referendum and let the people decide and not the protesters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
