<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reporter hears man confess to arranging murder of rabbi's wife  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- She was a reporter. He was a private
investigator. They met Friday to discuss a sensational criminal
case -- the 1994 killing of a prominent Cherry Hill rabbi's wife.
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor joined them at a South Jersey diner, and by the end
of their meeting the man had confessed that he helped arrange the
killing -- at the rabbi's request.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was sitting across the table from a man who said he had
something inside and he could no longer keep it a secret,''
Philadelphia Inquirer reporter Nancy Phillips said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips reported Jenoff's confessions in Tuesday's editions, a
day after Jenoff and an alleged accomplice were arrested and
charged in the killing of Carol Neulander, 52.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff is being held on $200,000 bail. Bail for the man he
allegedly hired, Paul Michael Daniels, is $400,000. Prosecutors say
both men confessed, saying they went to Mrs. Neulander's home on
the night of Nov. 1, 1994, with the intention to kill her.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday, Rabbi Fred Neulander had been the only person
charged in the beating death of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, 57, once the head of the largest synagogue in the
southern New Jersey community of Cherry Hill, was long suspected in
the killing, but was not charged until September 1998. He resigned
his position three months after his wife's death after reports
surfaced about two extramarital affairs with members of his
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff, who had gone to Neulander for counseling after losing
his marriage and his home, maintains Neulander offered him $30,000
to kill a person he claimed was an enemy of Israel. According to
the story he offered reporter Phillips, Neulander told Jenoff he
could get him a job with Mossad, the Israeli secret service, if he
pulled off the murder without being caught.
</P>
<P>
   According to the account published in Tuesday's editions of the
Inquirer, Phillips and Jenoff met for an interview on Friday and
drove in Jenoff's minivan toward Philadelphia, but then he changed
his mind and drove into Camden, pulling up outside a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff then asked Phillips to call Camden County Prosecutor Lee
Solomon to see if he would agree to meet for coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon met Jenoff and Phillips at an Audubon diner. County
homicide investigator Martin Devlin accompanied Solomon. For three
hours, Jenoff sat across from Solomon and Devlin and, with Phillips
at the table, talked about his role in the murder of Carol
Neulander.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff ordered coffee and a fruit cup. As he talked, he smoked
cigarettes and drank several glasses of water. At times, he broke
down, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not a bad person,'' he said at one point. ''I just did a
bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff told Solomon that he hoped he could win leniency in
exchange for his cooperation. Solomon made no promises, but told
Jenoff his office would investigate and attempt to corroborate the
story.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was surreal,'' Phillips said Tuesday before Jenoff's first
court appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff's lawyer, Francis Hartman, said his client was haunted by
what happened and felt a compelling need to confess.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was something that was eating at him. The trial is coming
up and the thought occurred to him that the rabbi might be
acquitted and that might be a terrible thing,'' Hartman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Neulander's attorneys, who have argued that Mrs. Neulander
was killed by an intruder during a robbery, charged that Jenoff is
a troubled character with questionable credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ''In his belittled and befuddled mind, he's become a part of a
major story,'' said defense lawyer Dennis Wixted.
</P>
<P>
   Wixted also said the presence of the reporter at the Friday
meeting would be a complicating factor. Phillips' role makes her a
witness and her notes subject to a subpoena, Wixted said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's already under way, but I can't comment any further,''
Wixted said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Solomon thanked the media in general for
help, but refused to comment specifically on any role Phillips had
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone call made Tuesday afternoon to Phillips at the
Inquirer's South Jersey office in Cherry Hill was forwarded to John
V.R. Bull, assistant to the editor at the Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Bull declined comment on the timing of the story or Phillips'
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anything we have to say we will say in the paper, like we did
today,'' Bull said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
