<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tower Air Shuts Passenger Service  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN MATTHEWS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tower Air, the no-frills airline that filed for
bankruptcy protection earlier this year, has halted all passenger
service, leaving ticketholders scrambling to find space on other
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are still operating charters and military flights but not
passenger flights,'' Pam Buoninconcri, director of corporate
relations for Tower, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger flights were discontinued Monday night. The airline
had been flying to Los Angeles; Miami; San Juan, Puerto Rico; Santo
Domingo, Dominican Republic and Tel Aviv, Israel. Flights to San
Francisco; Fort Lauderdale, Fla.; Athens, Greece and Paris were
dropped as problems mounted in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Some 300 Tel Aviv-bound passengers learned of the news when they
arrived at John F. Kennedy International Airport for their 11:30
p.m. Monday flight.
</P>
<P>
   Buoninconcri did not know how many other flights had been
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Morrison, a spokesman for the Port Authority of New York
and New Jersey, said Port Authority staffers at Kennedy were
helping the stranded passengers book flights on other airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Tower Air Inc. filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in
February in the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   The same month, the airline, based at Kennedy Airport, said it
intended to cut 300 jobs, or 19 percent of its work force, and
reduce the size of its fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Tower was known for low fares -- less than $400 round trip from
New York to Los Angeles, for example -- and spotty service. Delays
were routine, and Tower's fleet of aging Boeing 747s required
frequent maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.towerair.com
</P>
</TEXT>
