<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Defends Vieques Bomb Training  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon renewed it insistence Tuesday
that it has no alternative but to use the inhabited island of
Vieques for live-fire training. Critics said a federal showdown
with protesters is imminent because the Navy didn't look hard
enough for another target range.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today there's only one Vieques,'' said Rear Adm. Craig
Quigley, Pentagon spokesman, as federal authorities threatened to
forcibly remove protesters on the Puerto Rican island to clear the
way for an agreement allowing limited training.
</P>
<P>
   ''They haven't been able to use Vieques for more than a year,
and yet the Navy managed to conduct the training it needed,'' said
Manuel Mirabal, head of the National Puerto Rican Coalition, which
opposes military use of the island.
</P>
<P>
   Marbal said that since the United States is at peace and is not
threatened, it doesn't need the island as badly as the Navy says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Navy insists the requirements for the kind of
training it has staged on the Puerto Rican island since World War
II simply are not met anywhere else in the Atlantic. The island is
part of Puerto Rico, a U.S. territory, and its 9,400 residents are
American citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Deep water, enough uninhabited land and free airspace are all
essential ingredients that make Vieques the best place in the
entire Atlantic, the Navy says, to conduct live bombing, shelling,
submarine maneuvers, amphibious assaults and ship-to-ship warfare
drills all at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy, which controls two-thirds of the 51-square-mile
island, argues that it has been safely bombarding its test range
for nearly six decades -- halted only last year with the death of a
civilian worker in a bombing accident.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters have prevented implementation of an agreement
involving President Clinton, the Defense Department and Puerto
Rican authorities allowing scaled-back training on the island
pending a referendum by residents to decide future use. The
agreement also calls for turning back of some federal land to
Puerto Rico and a $40 million assistance package for the island.
</P>
<P>
   Quigley acknowledged that if Vieques residents vote down the
training, the Navy would be forced to develop an alternative,
although at ''considerable expense.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, critics continue to accuse the Navy of failing to
seriously consider alternate sites for live-fire training.
</P>
<P>
   Mirabal said the Pentagon showed the same resistance in the
1970s before it abandoned a weapons range on another Puerto Rican
island, Culebra, and another range similar to Vieques on the
Hawaiian island of Kahoolawe.
</P>
<P>
   He said Puerto Ricans are ill-equipped to argue with the U.S.
military about its assessment of needs, ''a business they are
solely in and keep secret.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said a year without Vieques ''does not seem to have
reduced their ability of defending the U.S. and carrying out their
obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has found alternatives to some of the training it does
on Vieques, diverting four series of naval maneuvers since the
temporary hold on use of Vieques last year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, it announced that the aircraft carrier USS George
Washington and its battle group would train off Virginia and North
Carolina rather than Puerto Rico
</P>
<P>
   The Washington and the USS Dwight D. Eisenhower battle groups
have both been diverted to the East Coast twice. Earlier this year,
three ships with the Eisenhower were sent to Cape Wrath, Scotland,
for practice shelling under an agreement with Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Lee Hamilton, member of the now-defunct Pentagon
task force that recommended the Navy phase out its use of Vieques,
said Tuesday he believes the military seriously tried to find an
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy examined ''in very great detail'' at least 18 possible
sites, he said. While opponents kept insisting there were bound to
be alternatives, they offered none, Hamilton said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Pentagon-appointed commission itself did not have
the resources to examine alternatives on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, he said, the military can make adjustments to
training, making Vieques unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not suggesting it would be easy, but I do think it can be
done,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
