<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Clouds continued to darken the Northeast on Tuesday,
while clear
skies were the norm over the central part of the country. Clouds
and some rain fell in the Northwest.
<TEXT>
<P>
   High pressure remained in control of the weather from the
northerain and central Plains, east into the Great Lakes and Ohio
Valley. Generally clear to partly cloudy skies were found over the
entire region.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front stretching from Virginia, west into Kentucky
continued to slowly sag southward. Clouds were found in association
with this front over most of the Mid-Atlantic states, southerain
Appalachians and Tennessee Valley.
</P>
<P>
   An upper-level disturbance over northwesterain Texas continued to
cause showers and thunderstorms over Texas, Louisiana and Arkansas.
Flash flood watches were in effect for most of southerain Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A frontal boundary system moving across the northerain Rockies
brought clouds to Idaho, Montana, westerain Wyoming and Utah.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure over the Southwest continued to provide fair and
dry weather from southerain Califorainia, east into New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures across the Lower 48 ranged from a low of 25 in
Taox, N.M., to an early-afterainoon high of 88 in Thermal, Calif.
WIth the wind chill, it felt like 16 in Taos, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service:
http://iwin.nws.noaa.gov/iwin/graphicsversion/bigmain.html
</P>
<P>
   Intellicast: http://www.intellicast.com/LocalWeather
</P>
<P>
   Weather Channel: http://www.weather.com
</P>
