<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Web Site Scoops Up Stars &AMP; Stripes  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY BAIR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- An Internet company has acquired Stars &AMP;
Stripes veterans' newspaper, which has been published for all but
12 years since the Civil War, and will begin posting its stories on
a new Web site.
</P>
<P>
   IServed.com said Tuesday it bought the newspaper for an
undisclosed price and described the Stars &AMP; Stripes name as an
''amazing brand.'' The newspaper's stories will appear at
www.stripes.com and in a special mailed edition this week that
announces the change.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's deal does not include the government-owned European
and Pacific editions of the Stars &AMP; Stripes, which are circulated
at military bases. Those papers, which operate both on
subscriptions and government subsidies, previously agreed not to be
circulated in the United States as part of a deal that gives them
free rights to the Stars &AMP; Stripes name.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Haugerud, the owner of the U.S. edition, said he never
made money in the nine years he owned the paper, which mails 10,000
copies across the country every two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have gotten a lot of psychic reward out of running the damn
thing,'' Haugerud said from the paper's office in Thurmont, Md. ''I
never tried to make money. The way we ran it, it was never going to
make money.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper has an editorial staff of only four people and
pays its free-lancers $50 per story, much lower than most national
publications.
</P>
<P>
   The paper publishes columns written by members of the U.S. House
and Senate and recently has run several articles and editorials
about military personnel refusing orders to take anthrax shots.
</P>
<P>
   IServed.com already publishes information about military
contracts, veterans and other matters on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars &AMP; Stripes was started for Union troops during the
Civil War in 1861. Soldiers from an Illinois unit under the command
of Gen. Ulysses S. Grant overtook the offices of the Bloomfield
Daily Herald of Missouri and used its equipment to publish a
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The paper stopped for 12 years after the war before it was
reborn as the National Tribune under the management of some of the
editors of the first Stars &AMP; Stripes. Its staff covered military
malaria outbreaks during the Spanish-American War, and the paper
was renamed the Stars &AMP; Stripes in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Haugerud, a real-estate developer, will join the board of
directors at the new owner. Rich Tauberman, a spokesman for the new
owners, said the mail edition will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will focus on developing innovative sponsorships and
commerce relationships that match the desire of marketers to reach
veterans with the needs of our members for relevant information and
services,'' said Jack Colletti, the new chief executive officer at
Stars &AMP; Stripes.
</P>
<P>
   The new corporate name will be Stars &AMP; Stripes Omnimedia Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.stripes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1842 </TRAILER>
