<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Detained in McDonald's Bombing  </HEADLINE>
By PIERRE-ANTOINE SOUCHARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Five suspected Breton separatists were detained for
questioning by French police Tuesday in connection with last
month's fatal bombing of a McDonald's restaurant in Brittany,
police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the five included Gael Roblin, spokesman for
Emgann, a 200-member separatist group which is believed to be the
political arm of the Breton Revolutionary Army, known by its French
initials ARB. Two men and two women, whose identities were not
revealed, were also in police custody.
</P>
<P>
   The ARB, which seeks autonomy for the western region of
Brittany, is considered the prime suspect in the bombing, but it
has denied responsibility. Emgann, which means ''combat'' in the
Breton language, had previously condemned the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-terrorist authorities believe there may be links between
the Emgann and the ARB. But Emgann has denied links with the older
group, which has claimed responsibility for a number of nonfatal
bombings this year.
</P>
<P>
   The April 19 blast tore through the drive-through windows of a
McDonald's fast-food restaurant located near Dinan, a town of
22,000 people 250 miles west of Paris. A 27-year-old employee,
Laurence Turbec, was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Small groups of Breton separatists have long sought autonomy for
the coastal region, which has maintained a strong cultural identity
reflecting the Bretons' Celtic origins.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have opened a judicial inquiry into the McDonald's
blast and into a bombing attempt in the nearby city of Rennes on
the same day. Police defused the Rennes bomb, which was placed in
front of a downtown post office.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe the two incidents were linked. Explosives
found at both scenes are thought to be part of a large stock of
dynamite stolen in September from a company in the Breton town of
Plevin.
</P>
<P>
   After the theft, police recovered more than half the dynamite
and arrested eight Breton and five Basque separatists. Then, in
March, the ARB claimed responsibility for an attack that made use
of some of the explosives that weren't recovered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1843 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000502.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to complete state swing; Giuliani picks upstate campaignexpert  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- As Hillary Rodham Clinton prepared for a
two-day foray that will end with her having visited all of New
York's 62 counties, Senate rival Rudolph Giuliani tapped a veteran
Republican operative Tuesday to bolster his upstate campaign
effort.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City mayor, who learned last week that he has
prostate cancer, has been criticized by some fellow Republicans for
not spending enough time in traditionally more conservative upstate
New York while the first lady has been crisscrossing what is
expected to be a major electoral battleground this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''He knows this state like the back of his hand,'' said Bruce
Teitelbaum, the mayor's campaign manager, as he announced that
state GOP executive director Brendan Quinn will become director of
statewide field operations for the Giuliani campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gov. George Pataki continued to duck questions about
whether he would take up the GOP Senate banner if the mayor drops
out of the race. ''I believe he will continue to run,'' Pataki
said. Beyond that, the governor said, ''I'm not going to
speculate.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls have shown Pataki is the top choice among
Republican voters to take on Clinton if Giuliani drops out of the
race. The mayor said he will make his decision before the end of
May about that.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign aides were showing no signs of slowing down.
Joining Quinn at state GOP headquarters in Albany, Teitelbaum said
the announcement was the first in a series this week aimed at
letting people know the campaign was moving ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things on tap is a possible meeting later this week
between Giuliani and state Conservative Party Chairman Michael
Long. The two have been at odds over the mayor's refusal to come
out for a ban on what critics call ''late-term abortion'' and his
strong ties to the Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, with Long's encouragement, former U.S. Rep. Joseph
DioGuardi announced he would seek the nominations of the
Conservative, Right to Life and Independence parties. A DioGuardi
candidacy could drain conservative votes away from the mayor, a
liability in a close race. Polls show the race is close.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Long said that ''at this stage of the game'' he did
not see Giuliani being the Conservative Party's candidate and
believed the nomination would go to DioGuardi. But Long cautioned
that could change before the party's June 3 state convention.
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani said he would court the Conservative Party,
Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said the first lady would
ask the Liberal Party for its support despite the fact that party
boss Raymond Harding is one of Giuliani's top political advisers.
Both Giuliani and Clinton are scheduled to meet with the Liberal
Party's policy committee Saturday in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Some leaders of the Independence Party, the New York arm of the
national Reform Party, were grumbling Tuesday about state
Democratic Chairwoman Judith Hope's reference to it as ''an
anti-Semitic party'' during a Monday night television appearance.
On Saturday, at an Independence Party forum in Buffalo, Clinton had
complained that one of the party's top leaders, Lenora Fulani, had
made anti-Semitic remarks in the past. Fulani, who was in the
audience, called the attack ''slanderous.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope spokesman Peter Kaufman said Tuesday that it was clear from
the entire interview that Hope was complaining about Fulani and the
Reform Party's possible presidential nominee, Pat Buchanan, not the
entire Independence Party.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to
count the votes they receive on third-party ballot lines, a factor
in close races. In New York, no Republican has won statewide office
since 1974 without the Conservative Party line. Conversely, no
Democrat has been elected U.S. senator or governor without the
Liberal Party line since the party's founding in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to everything else, both campaigns were completing
work on new television ads that could begin airing as early as this
week. While Giuliani has already been airing TV ads, the Clinton
campaign has yet to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady planned to visit Washington, Franklin, Hamilton
and Clinton counties in northern New York on Wednesday and
Thursday, a trip that will mean she has visited all 62 of the
state's counties since she began campaigning 10 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hope noted that was not accomplished by Democratic Sen. Charles
Schumer until late last year, a full year after he defeated
Republican incumbent Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary Clinton is in the process of redefining New York state
politics, throwing traditional formulas out the window with her
relentless attention to counties that heretofore have been
ignored,'' the state Democratic Party leader said. ''Clearly,
upstate New York will be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hope said the first lady's visit to all 62 counties was
not aimed at helping her overcome charges that she is a
carpetbagger, the Giuliani camp pressed that point.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Clinton can travel to as many counties, as many times as
she wants,'' Teitelbaum said. ''It will not change the fact that
she's never lived in New York, never worked in New York and she has
absolutely no connection to New York. There's only one real New
Yorker in this race, Rudy Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton moved to the suburbs north of New York City in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
