<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge to decide whether to approve multibillion-dollar settlement  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL RUBINKAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Opponents of a proposed $3.75 billion
national settlement of health claims against the diet drug
combination fen-phen called the deal inadequate Tuesday and intend
to ask a federal judge to throw it out.
</P>
<P>
   ''The plan is illegal and unfair,'' said Edward F. Blizzard, an
attorney for a splinter plaintiffs' group that objects to the
settlement. ''The amounts being offered to settle these claims are
inadequate to compensate people for their injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Louis C. Bechtle, who gave preliminary
approval to the deal last November, began hearing testimony Tuesday
into its fairness. The hearing is expected to last two weeks.
American Home Products, the drug's maker, and plaintiffs attorneys
favor approval.
</P>
<P>
   More than 9,000 lawsuits have been filed against Madison,
N.J.-based American Home, maker of fenfluramine, the ''fen'' in the
fen-phen combination. The company sold the drug under the brand
name of Pondimin and also made Redux, a chemical cousin.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs were withdrawn in September 1997 after a Mayo Clinic
study linked the fen-phen combination to potentially fatal heart
valve damage.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, reached lasted October, pays fen-phen users a
maximum of $1.5 million. Most, however, would get far less,
depending on their level of injury and how long they took the
drugs. It also includes money for future medical monitoring for
those who are still healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Blizzard predicted the deal will be tossed out either by Bechtel
or on appeal. He argued the class is too large and involves too
many interests, from people who have suffered no ill effects from
the drug to those who have been seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Melbourne Mills Jr., an attorney in Lexington, Ky., who
represents 2,400 fen-phen users, said about 340 have dropped out of
the national settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think the benefits for the most serious conditions are
adequate compared to what juries have awarded across the country,''
said Mills, who attended the court session.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody's trapped,'' countered Arnold Levin, a plaintiff
attorney who helped negotiate the deal. ''If they don't like it,
they can go out and try their own cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Of 6 million people who took fen-phen before it was pulled from
the market, just 45,000 of them elected to refuse the settlement.
Those who opted out retain the right to sue for punitive damages.
Those who remained in the class action may still reject the
settlement, but are forbidden from collecting punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see any room to object when you can walk away from the
deal,'' said Kip Petroff, a Dallas lawyer who won a $23.3 million
award in a fen-phen case last year.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's testimony, plaintiffs' attorney Michael Fishbein
described last year's settlement talks as extremely adversarial.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 75 or so negotiating sessions ''were what amounted
to screaming battles,'' Fishbein said. ''I cannot think of a more
adversarial negotiation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
