<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Drops E-mail Claim  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN SOLOMON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House on Tuesday dropped a potential
executive privilege claim and turned over to Congress several
handwritten notes from lawyers that were being sought by
investigators in the controversy over missing e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential counsel Beth Nolan made the concession in a letter
to Rep. Dan Burton, chairman of the House Government Reform
Committee, on the eve of a new round of hearings by the panel into
the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are making these seven documents available today to your
committee,'' Nolan wrote. ''We are not waiving the right to assert
executive privilege or attorney-client privilege with respect to
future requests.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue were handwritten notes by White House lawyers involving
discussions they had with computer experts about the missing e-mail
problem since the controversy first erupted earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The White House initially declined to turn over the memos,
saying they included the ''mental impressions'' of presidential
lawyers and may be protected by the president's right to keep
confidential the advice he receives.
</P>
<P>
   The White House did not formally invoke the executive privilege,
instead listing the documents and saying they were subject to such
a claim. Burton, R-Ind., criticized the maneuver as ''legal
mumbo-jumbo.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressional committee as well as federal prosecutors are
investigating why the White House, after discovering a glitch in
1998 that kept e-mails from being properly archived, did not
immediately retrieve the missing messages to determine if they
should have been turned over to investigators under subpoenas
issued in investigations from Whitewater and impeachment to
political fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials blame a ''disconnect'' between their
technicians, who diagnosed the e-mail problem, and their lawyers,
who apparently did not understand until this year that the glitch
might affect pending subpoena requests.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan's letter Tuesday also made a second concession to the
House committee. The presidential lawyer turned over, without
requiring a new subpoena, a disk of e-mails from the Monica
Lewinsky investigation that White House officials used to test the
extent of the e-mail glitch back in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have said they retrieved a sample of
Lewinsky-related e-mails after the glitch was discovered and
determined they were duplicates of documents already turned over to
prosecutors. As a result, officials did not tell investigators
about the e-mail problem, review additional documents for
compliance with subpoenas or try to recover the rest of thousands
of missing e-mails until earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel Robert Ray, the Justice Department and
Congress are all investigating whether the delay was part of an
effort to obstruct the investigations that have dogged the Clinton
White House. Presidential aides have denied such wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Executive privilege, which became famous a quarter-century ago
during the battle for Richard Nixon's audio tapes in the Watergate
scandal, refers to the right of a president to keep confidential
the advice he receives from aides on official matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1908 </TRAILER>
