<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Approves Spending Bill  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House subcommittee quickly approved the
first spending bill of the coming fiscal year on Tuesday, but the
panel's easy passage belied budget fights between President Clinton
and Congress that lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   By voice vote, the House Appropriations Committee subcommittee
that oversees military construction approved an $8.6 billion
measure for fiscal 2001, which begins Oct. 1. The full committee
plans to consider the bill next week.
</P>
<P>
   There are 13 annual spending bills that keep federal agencies
functioning, and the military construction measure is traditionally
one of the least controversial. White House budget chief Jack Lew
signaled Tuesday that Clinton will demand more money for many of
the measures than Republicans seem ready to spend.
</P>
<P>
   Unless they do, ''the president simply cannot and will not sign
them,'' Lew said at a speech at the Urban Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Lew said Clinton wants about $20 billion more for schools, land
conservation and other domestic programs than Republicans seem
ready to provide, which is about $293 billion. The overall federal
budget is about $1.8 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is fundamental that the administration wants to spend more
and we want to hold the line. So they are going to characterize
anything we do as unreasonable cuts in that regard,'' House
Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said later.
</P>
<P>
   The military construction measure finances facilities such as
bases and housing. It would provide nearly $300 million more than
this year's total, and $600 million more than Clinton requested.
</P>
<P>
   Included is $83 million of the $104 million Clinton requested to
build radar facilities in Alaska as part of a possible anti-missile
defense system the administration is considering. The subcommittee
said it might provide the additional money later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1913 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000502.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High court overturns death sentence  </HEADLINE>
By STRAT DOUTHAT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The state Supreme Court on Tuesday
overturned the death sentence given to Terry Johnson, who killed a
state trooper in 1991, and ordered him imprisoned for life without
parole.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and his brother were convicted of killing Trooper
Russell Bagshaw early in the morning of June 5, 1991. Johnson fired
nearly 20 hollow-point bullets at Bagshaw's cruiser after the
trooper's routine patrol interrupted the burglary of a North
Windham sporting goods store.
</P>
<P>
   Terry and Duane Johnson were convicted of capital felony in
separate trials. Terry Johnson received a death sentence; Duane
Johnson was sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But the high court ruled that jurors erred when they found that
Terry Johnson had killed Bagshaw in an especially cruel or heinous
manner. That finding was based on the conclusion that Bagshaw had
been terrorized when he was ambushed.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled 4-3 that the shooting itself was not
enough to meet the standard for the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''The vile nature of the crime committed by the defendant in
this case cannot be overstated,'' the high court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   But the court said the jury could not have found that Johnson,
who was 21 when he killed Bagshaw, caused the trooper pain above
and beyond what caused his death.
</P>
<P>
   Bagshaw's widow, who has remarried, has moved and could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Windham County Chief State's Attorney Mark Solak said he was
disappointed with the ruling but glad that the high court found no
errors that would have meant retrying the case.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he regrets, as a citizen, that the death penalty
law will not apply in cases where police officers are gunned down
from a distance. He said he planned to ask the Legislature to make
it a death penalty crime to kill a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should not have to ask juries to count the breaths of life
in a mortally wounded police officer,'' Solak said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland, who supports the death penalty, said the
ruling does not alter his stance on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still trust the system,'' he said. ''The judicial side will
make its determinations. ... We abide by its decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Gold, an assistant state public defender, said the court
''has drawn some sort of line that says every killing is not
necessarily cruel and heinous.''
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled unanimously against a number of other challenges
to Johnson's conviction and the trial judge's refusal to allow him
to withdraw a guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   But the court was divided 4-3 on reversing the death sentence,
with Chief Justice Francis McDonald and justices Barry Schaller and
Paul Foti dissenting.
</P>
<P>
   In arguments on the appeal in October, Johnson's attorney
Richard Emanuel argued that Johnson wanted to kill, not torture,
the trooper.
</P>
<P>
   ''The capital offense is over -- 17 shots, less than 10
seconds,'' Emanuel said. ''There was no intent by the defendant to
prolong the victim's suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant State's Attorney Marjorie Dauster argued that Johnson
watched and waited as Bagshaw pulled up to the sporting goods store
and then unleashed a fusillade on the trooper.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was gratuitous violence in the number of bullets that were
fired,'' Dauster said.
</P>
<P>
   But the court said that while Bagshaw's last words -- ''Oh, my
God'' -- and final act of turning on the cruiser's lights ''evoke
great sympathy,'' they do not demonstrate that Bagshaw suffered
extreme psychological pain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-02-00 1920 </TRAILER>
