<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't May Probe Air Tix Pricing  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two Senate Democrats asked the Transportation
Department Tuesday to investigate ''unfairness'' in airline ticket
pricing, saying it takes too long to build an antitrust case
against predatory pricing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Enforcement actions under the department's statutory authority
are likely to be far quicker and simpler than the often protracted,
lengthy and complex antitrust enforcement litigation,'' Sens.
Herbert Kohl, D-Wis., and Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., said in a letter to
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was released at a hearing of the Senate Judiciary
subcommittee on antitrust, business rights and competition Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department has never used the unfairness
standard before, although it is in its power to do so, spokesman
Bill Mosley said. He refused to respond directly to the letter,
saying the department had not officially received it yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department last year accused Dallas-based American
Airlines of undercutting fares to drive out tiny Vanguard Airlines.
American raised its fares once Vanguard withdrew, the lawsuit said.
The lawsuit was the first predatory-practices case brought since
airlines were deregulated in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Having the Transportation Department go for ''unfairness''
instead would help speed up things because there wouldn't be any
concern about meeting the technical requirements of antitrust law,
Leahy and Kohl said in their letter.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will give them a chance to get moving quickly, instead of
initiating an antitrust case which could take years,'' Kohl said
after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, start-up airline Sun Country Airlines, a
small carrier based in suburban Minneapolis which began scheduling
low-fare flights last summer to markets served by Northwest
Airlines, complained of bullying by Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Country's president, Bill La Macchia, testified that
Northwest excluded a big Minneapolis area travel agency from its
discount ticket promotions after the agency had sold more Sun
Country tickets than any other agency in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest also banned the courtesy practice of selling airline
parts to Sun Country, and discontinued arrangements in which Sun
Country paid Northwest to use its facilities for crew training, La
Macchia said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe it is Northwest's intent to drive us from the
market and achieve an even greater level of monopolization,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest has denied any uncompetitive, predatory or illegal
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Senate Judiciary subcommittee on antitrust, business
rights and competition:
http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)judiciary/antibusn.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1929 </TRAILER>
