<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trial begins for man charged in witness slaying  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- The trial of the first of two brothers
charged in the killing of an 8-year-old witness opened Tuesday with
chilling testimony from the man who found the boy's body.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Williams' voice cracked as he described what he found
when he went to check on his co-worker, Karen Clarke, when she did
not report for work on the morning of Jan. 8, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he sounded his car horn, then called Clarke's name
several times before entering the Bridgeport duplex she shared with
her son, 8-year-old Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr.
</P>
<P>
   After entering through the open front door, Williams said he
walked by grocery bags and a woman's purse on the floor as he made
his way toward the rear of the house. When Clarke still did not
answer his calls, he went to check upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I started walking up the stairwell and I (saw) B.J. laying on
the ground, on the floor ... at the top of the stairwell,''
Williams said. He said there was blood coming from the boy's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he was about to check the boy's pulse when he was
startled by the sound of television static. He said he ran down the
stairs, outside to his car and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   When the paramedics arrived, he showed them where the boy was.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the paramedics shook his head 'no' to the police
officer'' after checking the boy's pulse, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler, 28, is charged with masterminding the murders of
B.J. and his mother to stop the boy from testifying against him in
the 1998 murder of Clarke's boyfriend, Rudolph Snead Jr. The boy
had witnessed an earlier driveby shooting in which Peeler allegedly
attempted to kill Snead.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler's brother, Adrian, charged with being the actual gunman,
is scheduled to stand trial once Russell's trial is completed. Both
brothers face the possibility of the death penalty if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was Clarke's manager at U-Haul, grimaced slightly
and looked away when he was asked to look at three photographs of
the crime scene. The jury was shown two of the photos -- one showed
a view of the boy's body at the top of the stairs, while the other
showed grocery bags by the front door.
</P>
<P>
   Later, autopsy photographs of Clarke were passed among the
jurors, but Judge G. Sarsfield Ford did not allow prosecutors to
pass out autopsy photos of B.J.
</P>
<P>
   The judge noted that the jurors had already seen the photos as
they were held up by Bridgeport State's Attorney Jonathan Benedict
and that they would be able to see them again during deliberations.
The enlarged autopsy photos, which showed closeups of the boy's
gunshot wounds, contrasted sharply with a photo the jurors saw
earlier in the day: a smiling little boy wearing a blue denim shirt
and a red tie.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Kanfer, the medical examiner who performed the autopsies,
said B.J. was shot four times -- in the right arm, in the left arm,
in the back and in the head. Kanfer said Clarke had three gunshot
wounds -- two in the chest and one in the right arm -- which may have
been caused by either two or three bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe the mother and son were killed the night of Jan.
7, 1999, as they returned home from grocery shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler's defense attorneys objected to prosecutors being allowed
to ask Kanfer about the mere possibility that Clarke may have been
shot twice instead of three times. Attorney William Koch noted that
the state's star witness, Josephine Lee, told police Adrian Peeler
used a revolver, which fires a maximum of six shots. If Clarke was
shot three times and B.J. four times, the total of seven shots
would contradict Lee's statements.
</P>
<P>
   Kanfer testified that Clarke's wounds were consistent with
either two or three shots.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is expected to last about four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors plan to call up to 80 witnesses, including Lee, who
lived across the street from Clarke and her son.
</P>
<P>
   Lee originally told police that she heard the two brothers
planning the killings, then acted as a lookout for Adrian Peeler
and watched as he killed the mother and son.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee appeared to recant what she told police in a letter she
wrote to her lawyer in December.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything that I have told them (police) is lies,'' she
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she wrote three separate letters to Bridgeport
police officers in which she apologized for her role in the
killings and said she was grateful that the Peelers didn't kill
her.
</P>
<P>
   Lee pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit murder and agreed to
testify against the brothers in exchange for a maximum sentence of
seven years. She is expected to testify against Russell Peeler next
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-02-00 1929 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000502.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov.s Join Biotech Food Promotion  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER, AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Governors concerned that opposition to
genetically engineered food could hurt farmers and biotech
companies in their states announced plans Tuesday to use their
political muscle to promote the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 governors hope to reassure the public that ''this isn't
just the big, bad chemical companies trying to engineer something
to jam down your throats,'' said North Dakota Gov. Ed Schafer.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer, a Republican, is co-chairing the Governors
Biotechnology Partnership with Iowa Gov. Tom Vilsack, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The governors have yet to finalize a strategy, but they are
patterning the effort after a governors' ethanol coalition that
promotes the corn-based gasoline additive, in part through
sponsoring studies of the product.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Schafer and Vilsack, the governors forming the
biotech coalition include Democrats Mel Carnahan of Missouri and
Tom Carper of Delaware, whose states are home to two of the leading
companies in the industry, Monsanto and DuPont.
</P>
<P>
   The other governors are Republicans Dirk Kempthorne of Idaho,
John Engler of Michigan, Mike Johanns of Nebraska, Kenny Guinn of
Nevada, Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin and George Ryan of Illinois,
and Democrats Frank O'Bannon of Indiana, Jim Hunt of North Carolina
and Gary Locke of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer said the governors hope to coordinate their message with
the biotechnology companies, who last month launched a $50 million
advertising campaign to counter criticism of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Crops have been engineered to stay fresher longer or else to
resist pests and herbicides. The National Academy of Sciences
concluded recently that the biotech food now on the market is safe,
but critics say there isn't enough proof, and some U.S. food
processing companies and fast-food companies have been turning away
from the crops.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration is expected to announce steps
soon, possibly as early Wednesday, that are meant to assure the
public that the food is safe. The steps will include formalizing a
process for biotech companies to consult with FDA and establishing
guidelines for companies that want to label food as free of biotech
ingredients, food industry officials say.
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials did not return phone calls Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think they (the governors) are doing their farmers or
their consumers any benefit by promoting a technology that hasn't
proven to be safe,'' said Charles Margulis, a spokesman for
Greenpeace, an environmental group that has led the opposition to
biotech food. ''I don't think it's going to make much difference to
our side.''
</P>
<P>
   Vilsack, speaking Tuesday at the National Press Club, invoked
the name of Henry Wallace, a liberal icon who was a pioneer in corn
research and later a tireless promoter of New Deal policies while
serving as agriculture secretary and vice president under Franklin
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic engineering is fundamentally no different than the
conventional plant breeding done by Wallace, Vilsack said. Genetic
engineering involves transferring traits from one organism to
another by splicing genes, while conventional breeding methods
include cross pollinating plants and inducing genetic mutations.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not new science,'' Vilsack said. ''It's simply quicker
science.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rissler, a biotech expert with the Union of Concerned
Scientists, said genetic engineering is ''a very powerful
technology, far more powerful than traditional breeding, just as
nuclear energy is far more powerful than fossil fuels.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: USDA biotech site:
http://www.aphis.usda.gov/biotechnology
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1940 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000502.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
