<HEADLINE> UN, NATO To Regulate Serbs' Return  </HEADLINE>
By ALISON MUTLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRACANICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Kosovo's top U.N. and NATO
officials joined moderate Serbs Tuesday in a committee meant to
regulate the return of Serbs who fled ethnic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Kouchner, Kosovo's U. N. administrator, declined to
specify when Serbs would begin to return to their homes in Kosovo
in large numbers, suggesting that depended on security in the
Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
   About 10,000 ethnic Albanians died during the 18-month crackdown
by forces loyal to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and that
has led to revenge killings, which have hampered reconciliation
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 100,000 Serbs fled Kosovo fearing reprisals by
ethnic Albanians after NATO and the U.N. moved in to run the
province in June. While many ethnic Albanians remain opposed,
moderate Serbs insist the returns must start soon, to show that
international organizations running the province are serious about
their commitment to ethnic coexistence in the province
</P>
<P>
   ''You want to rush for political reasons,'' said Kouchner after
signing the agreement. ''(For) the maximum of safety we don't want
to take too much risk.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Rev. Sava Janjic, a spokesman for a moderate group
of Serbs, said he believed the returns could begin as early in
June. He said a group of 50 people would return either to the
heavily damaged village of Osojane, in northwest Kosovo or Slivovo,
a deserted village 10 miles east of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government earlier this year proposed a scheme to
return 700 Serbs to the village of Osojane, and Oliver Ivanovic,
the leader of a radical Serb faction, wants to return as many as
1,500 Serbs in one group. Kouchner said all returns would be
coordinated through the joint committee established Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs mainly live in enclaves and often are escorted by NATO-led
peacekeepers when they venture out of their residences and towns.
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner said an open letter will be sent to Ivanovic, Serb
leader in the ethnically divided city of Kosovksa Mitrovica,
inviting him to participate in the agreement. Ivanovic so far has
refused to join any U. N.-led organization.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo's main ethnic Albanian leaders also have agreed to
support the return of other non-Albanians, such as Gypsies, also
known as Roma. About 30,000 are believed to have fled. Roma have
been accused by ethnic Albanians of collaborating with Serb
military forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1946 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000502.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hostage's School Urges Speedy Return  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOETTINGEN, Germany (AP) -- Students and teachers at the school
where one of the hostages being held in the Philippines works said
Tuesday they are watching with hope for a peaceful resolution of
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Those who work with geography teacher Werner Wallert, 57, said
he is dedicated to his students. He is among the 21 hostages being
held by Muslim rebels along with his wife, Renate, 56, and their
26-year-old son, Marc.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately we can do so little here, but we hope for the
best for the family,'' said Ulrike Koller, head of the 700-student
Theodor Heuss High School.
</P>
<P>
   The school has also been following the crisis on its Web site,
posting updates on the situation.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Monday by journalists who accompanied a doctor
allowed to visit the hostages on the southern Philippine island of
Jolo, Wallert stressed the dire nature of their situation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are risking our lives here and if the Philippine government
should try to march in and find a military solution, there will be
bloodshed, nothing else. ... It must be a political solution, it
must be a peaceful solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Renate Wallert is one of two captives who requires
hospitalization, according to the doctor who visited the hostages.
She suffers from cardiopulmonary disease and high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer said he has been in
contact with his counterpart in the Philippines, telling ARD
television that he has stressed Germany doesn't want any actions
taken which would endanger the hostages' safety.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer told the Cologne Express newspaper in a report to be
published Wednesday that there has been no direct contact with the
hostages from the German government.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hostage-takers are difficult to predict. We must take them
seriously,'' he said, calling for patience in the crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 1952 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000502.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deal Could Reunite Mom, Accused Boy  </HEADLINE>
By JIM IRWIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. (AP) -- The mother of the 6-year-old boy accused of
fatally shooting another first-grader in class will admit she
neglected her children under a deal that could restore her custody
rights, a prosecutor said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement between lawyers for the state, Tamarla Owens, and
her children is to be presented to Probate Judge Thomas L. Gadola
on Wednesday. The ultimate goal is to reunite the mother, the young
boy accused of killing 6-year-old Kayla Rolland, and the boy's two
siblings, Genesee County Prosecutor Art Busch said.
</P>
<P>
   A trial had been scheduled for Wednesday on Owens' bid to regain
custody of her children. The agreement means no trial will be held,
but Owens will agree to allow Probate Court to take jurisdiction
over the children, said her lawyer, Mark Clement.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the children will continue living with an
aunt and attend school. Owens also will undergo a psychological
evaluation, and will have parenting classes and other counseling as
needed, Busch said.
</P>
<P>
   Busch would not say how soon Owens and her children could resume
living together.
</P>
<P>
   Busch said he isn't alleging that Owens had any responsibility
for Kayla's Feb. 29 shooting death. Police say the boy shot and
killed Kayla at Buell Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   Owens and her husband, Dedric Owens, who is in jail on an
unrelated probation violation, were charged with child neglect
after the school shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Busch said the boys lived in ''shameful conditions'' at Owens'
brother's house, which police have said was used for drug dealing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
