<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two men charged in murder-for-hire of rabbi's wife  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- Nearly six years after her beating death, a
private investigator and an unemployed man have come forward to say
they were hired by a rabbi to kill his wife, prosecutors said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both men told investigators they showed up at Carol Neulander's
suburban Cherry Hill home with a lead pipe, intent on killing her,
Camden County Assistant Prosecutor James P. Lynch said in court.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Fred J. Neulander was scheduled to stand trial for the
murder on June 19. Up until Monday, Neulander had been the only
person accused in the Nov. 1, 1994, beating death of his
52-year-old wife. And he was not charged until September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander's lawyers have steadfastly maintained that the rabbi
did not kill his wife, despite accusations of infidelity. Instead
they say she was killed by an intruder in a possible robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Private investigator Leonard Jenoff's claim that he was hired by
Neulander to arrange the killing is an attempt on his part to seek
notoriety, the defense says.
</P>
<P>
   ''In his belittled and befuddled mind, he's become a part of a
major story,'' said Dennis Wixted, a defense lawyer for the rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff, 54, admitted to authorities that he accepted money to
kill the woman and confessed because guilt ''was eating, eating,
eating away at him,'' said Francis Hartman, Jenoff's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Now being held on $200,000 cash bail, Jenoff could face the
death penalty, Hartman said. Hartman is working with prosecutors on
a deal for his client, who is cooperating with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''The trial is coming up and the thought occurred to him that
the rabbi might be acquitted and that might be a terrible thing,''
Hartman said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Lynch told a judge that Paul Michael Daniels was
''clearly the primary actor in striking the blows.'' Mrs. Neulander
died after being repeatedly beaten, according to the medical
examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Wixted said Jenoff has told investigators nothing that has not
appeared already in media accounts in the years following the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's not one detail that he has provided that can be
corroborated,'' Wixted said, adding there is ''no weapon, no
fingerprints, no evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Jeffrey Zucker, another of Neulander's defense
team, Jenoff even went so far as to offer pictures of the alleged
killer that had been provided by a psychic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really believe he's deliberately trying to be part of this
case from day one,'' Zucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Zucker and Wixted said they did not hire Jenoff, a longtime
private investigator from Collingswood, or use him in any way as
part of their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Murder for hire is a factor that prosecutors can use to seek the
death penalty for all three defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Lee Solomon refused to comment on any of the details
offered in confessions made by Jenoff and Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon also would not say how the arrests of Daniels and Jenoff
will affect the charges against Neulander. His office ''will review
and re-evaluate'' the entire case and decide whether to seek the
death penalty, Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a decision I'll have to make further down the road,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff and Daniels were arrested Monday night and charged in the
slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Neulander has said he found his wife's body when he
returned from Congregation M'Kor Shalom synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander was indicted in January 1999. He remains free on
$400,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff and Daniels were being held in the Camden County Jail.
Daniels is being held on $400,000 cash bail.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have said Neulander had his wife of 29 years killed
so that he could continue his extramarital affair with Philadelphia
radio personality Elaine Soncini.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander reportedly thought divorce would jeopardize his
position as senior rabbi at the synagogue, which he founded with
his wife in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Soncini admitted having a two-year affair with Neulander that
ended shortly after his wife's killing. She has not been charged
with any wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
