<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Fire Service firefighters want more funds for trucks, safetygear  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Two months ago, firefighters with the New
Jersey Forest Fire Service raced to the scene of a 60-acre blaze
climbing a rocky forest slope along the Kittatinny Ridge in Walpack
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   There they were met by federal rangers who stopped them short.
The fire was on federal land, and most of the 40 state firefighters
lacked the safety gear required by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   So Tuesday some of these firefighters ventured to the Statehouse
here to make it plain that their equipment is outdated, their staff
is stretched too thin and many of those who do report to blazes
lack the safety gear that federal authorities have been mandating
since a 1994 disaster in Colorado claimed 14 lives.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey firefighters eventually did go in to knock down
the Walpack blaze, but only after driving 15 miles out of their way
to the headquarters of the Delaware Water Gap National Recreation
Area, where rangers handed out ''Nomex'' fire retardant coveralls,
shrouds, helmets and flame shelters designed to give these
so-called Hot Shots a chance to survive if a wall of flame shifts
and overtakes them.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Page, a spokesman for Department of Environmental
Protection Commissioner Robert Shinn, said Shinn was unaware of
these complaints before Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The commissioner has agreed to review what they have to say
and consider whether we have to shift money around to meet other
equipment needs,'' Page said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed budget provides $4 million for the fire service,
which has 88 full-timers and a roster of 1,050 seasonal part-timers
standing by to be called to fight fires around the clock. The
budget includes $1.9 million for equipment, including nine new
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Environmental Protection spokeswoman Sharon
Southard said the funding, staffing and fire calls have been stable
for several years.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Aughenbaugh, president of the New Jersey Deputy Fire
Chiefs Association, said a one-time grant of an additional $3.6
million is needed for new equipment to outfit all firefighters with
safety gear, to replace old trucks and to repair grounded
helicopters and equip them with smoke vision equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ''The situation is serious. We do not want to lose a firefighter
in the state of New Jersey,'' Aughenbaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the added $3.6 million could be used to replace 24 fire
trucks and 10 bulldozers, and to hire 19 more full-timers as
firefighters and fire wardens. He said the current Department of
Environmental Protection budget proposal would add 16 state park
rangers but only one firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the firefighters at the protest asked not to be
identified. One supervisor told of how most of the part-timers
working on his ''line'' wear only dungarees and flannel shirts,
which became worrisome last year at a Pinelands fire when a meadow
suddenly went up in a sheet of flame ''as if it was soaked in
gasoline.''
</P>
<P>
   ''These people had to run full blast back for the truck, and if
it had not been there (or if it had broken down), someone would
have gotten burned because none of them were wearing the right
gear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Assembly members spoke to the small group promising
to press ahead with legislation to provide the special funding.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now there is a deaf ear in this administration to the
needs of these firefighters,'' said Assemblyman Neil Cohen,
D-Union. ''If we don't act now in anticipation of another drought
season, we could be in serious danger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
