<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second report uncovers additional school cheating  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Six months after uncovering widespread cheating
on standardized tests, a city education watchdog charged Tuesday
that nine teachers at eight schools improperly assisted students
during testing.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, a fifth-grader was reduced to tears when a
teacher allegedly berated the boy for refusing to write down an
answer provided by the instructor, according to the report by
Special Commissioner of Investigation Edward Stancik.
</P>
<P>
   Equally shocking, the teacher's written explanation of what
happened was rife with misspellings and errors in grammar.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was in room 245 helping supervised,'' he wrote. ''I took the
examen to two or three students because they were talking without
control.'' One of the students later told the school principal ''I
said (told) her the answers of the test,'' the teacher wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Stancik, summing up his latest probe in a 20-page letter to
schools Chancellor Harold Levy, said additional reports of cheating
surfaced following his initial investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once again we found proctors who gave answers to students,
alerted them to wrong responses and changed student choices after
the exam was turned in,'' Stancik wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a teacher used the actual questions from the state
English Language Assessment to drill her students in preparation
for the exam. In another, one teacher provided the class with the
correct answers to the first 11 questions.
</P>
<P>
   Schools Chancellor Harold Levy responded to the allegations in a
statement issued Tuesday. ''I support Special Commissioner
Stancik's efforts to rid the public schools of teacher-assisted
cheating and have taken three actions in response to his report.''
</P>
<P>
   First, Levy has asked his general counsel to review the report
and determine its legitimacy. If it proves true, the chancellor
plans to take disciplinary action. Next, he is directing a
monitoring effort for Thursday's citywide math tests.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Levy has asked Stancik ''to assist future monitoring
activities by dispatching his investigators to schools in
coordination with the Board during the administration of
high-stakes tests.''
</P>
<P>
   United Federation of Teachers President Randi Weingarten said
that if Stancik's allegations were true, ''there should be serious
consequences.'' But the UFT has an independent investigator
reviewing the report to see if the charges are accurate.
</P>
<P>
   In his December report, Stancik found that teachers and
administrators at 32 New York City schools helped students cheat on
standardized tests by providing them with questions in advance and
even marking test forms for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-02-00 2015 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000502.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fen-Phen Settlement Hearings Begin  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL RUBINKAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Opponents of a proposed $3.75 billion
national settlement of health claims against the diet drug
combination fen-phen called the deal inadequate Tuesday as a judge
began hearing testimony on the fairness of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Louis C. Bechtle, who gave preliminary
approval to the deal in November, is expected to decide at the end
of the two-week hearing whether the settlement will stand.
</P>
<P>
   Edward F. Blizzard, an attorney for a group of fen-phen users
who object to the settlement, wants the judge to throw it out.
</P>
<P>
   ''The plan is illegal and unfair,'' Blizzard said Tuesday. ''The
amounts being offered to settle these claims are inadequate to
compensate people for their injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug's maker, American Home Products, and plaintiffs'
attorneys who worked out the settlement last October favor its
approval.
</P>
<P>
   More than 9,000 lawsuits have been filed against Madison,
N.J.-based American Home, maker of fenfluramine, the ''fen'' in the
fen-phen combination. The company sold the drug under the brand
name of Pondimin and also made Redux, a chemical cousin.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs were withdrawn in September 1997 after a Mayo Clinic
study linked the fen-phen combination to potentially fatal heart
valve damage. The second drug in the combination, phentermine, was
not linked to the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, the fen-phen users would get a maximum of
$1.5 million, though most would get far less, depending on their
level of injury and how long they took the drugs. The settlement
also includes money for their future medical monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   ''The settlement is the result of a dedicated effort between
plaintiffs' attorneys and American Home Products to create a
comprehensive and equitable plan,'' said Louis L. Hoynes Jr.,
American Home's senior vice president and general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Of 6 million people who took fen-phen before it was pulled from
the market, 45,000 refused the settlement and retain the right to
sue for punitive damages. Those who remained in the class action
may still reject the settlement and sue for compensatory damages
but are forbidden from collecting punitive damages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 2020 </TRAILER>
