<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine launches attack on Florio over taxes, recession  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- U.S. Senate candidate Jon Corzine has
pulled the trigger on one of the biggest weapons in his arsenal, an
attack on opponent Jim Florio over his tax increases as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said Tuesday they are surprised to see this
punch thrown this hard or this early in the battle for the
Democratic primary nomination.
</P>
<P>
   It suggests that the Corzine campaign may be feeling some
weakness or frustration in their effort to familiarize voters with
their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is probably testimony to the fact that Florio is holding a
lead, and that it is not decaying as fast as Corzine and his people
would be comfortable with,'' said political analyst Jim McQueeny.
</P>
<P>
   Polls gave Florio an edge of up to 2-to-1 among registered
Democrats but they are more than a month out of date, a period
during which Corzine has poured millions into television.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Florio increased income tax rates, raised the sales
tax and expanded the taxable categories to raise a combined $2.8
billion in revenue. The move came in response to a sharp dip in
state revenues that foretold a brief but painful economic
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Public outrage resulted in a disastrous 1991 election season for
Democrats, who lost majority control of the Senate and Assembly. By
1993, Florio himself had rebounded in public approval but not quite
enough, losing re-election to Gov. Christie Whitman on her promise
to cut some of those taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Corzine 30-second ad hits Florio for the taxes, 280,000 lost
jobs, 200,000 people without health insurance, spiraling auto
insurance rates, then climaxes with the question: ''Do we want to
go back to that?''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial then flips to Corzine's friendly face and offers:
''Welcome to the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Rider University political analyst David Rebovich said he
thought the negative ad was being used surprisingly early in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''He came out negative early because he apparently had to. The
feel-good ads apparently weren't doing it,'' Rebovich said. ''They
haven't given him the name recognition that he had hoped, and he
has not moved voters away from Florio.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Pomper of Rutgers University disagreed. He did not think
the negative attack was too early. What it was, Pomper said, was
too harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Corzine has framed that debate, that issue, that
consideration, correctly. But I also think it may be that it is too
rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Could it backfire? ''Oh definitely, especially if it is on too
long,'' Pomper said.
</P>
<P>
   McQueeny said he thought it was fair. ''It does take on the
record, not just the guy,'' he said. ''It is not personal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florio campaign, which has not spent money on TV commercials
and has no plan to do so soon, insists the hardball tactic will not
affect their strategy or timing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our game plan remains the same. We are pleased with our
position right now,'' said spokesman Jim Lanard. ''What Mr. Corzine
has done is to show a desperate act of a desperate campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio aide Walter Fields, who has spearheaded some of Florio's
most negative attacks on the campaign trail, said their offensive
tactic has forced Corzine's campaign to reply.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly we believe we have caused them to rethink their
campaign. I think there was a sense in the Corzine campaign that by
simply dumping money into this campaign they could overwhelm Jim
Florio's candidacy, and it has not worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine spokesman Steve Goldstein acknowledged that they were
responding in some sense to Florio's initiative, but not for the
reasons Fields cites.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein said they rolled out the attack ad now because Florio
has been spending more and more time discussing and defending his
1990 taxes, perhaps to defuse the bomb before Corzine could drop
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was Jim Florio himself, not Jon Corzine or the Corzine
campaign, who injected the issue of Florio's tax increase into this
campaign,'' Goldstein said. ''Our campaign is not doing anything
differently now than it had planned. If there was a slight
acceleration, it was because of Gov. Florio's intentions to discuss
the tax cut and to defend it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It had us here scratching our heads,'' Goldstein added.
''There is no remorse. He is not sorry at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-02-00 2029 </TRAILER>
