<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: More NYC School Cheating  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Six months after uncovering widespread cheating
on standardized tests, a city education watchdog charged Tuesday
that nine teachers at eight schools improperly assisted students
during testing.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, a fifth-grader was reduced to tears when a
teacher allegedly berated the boy for refusing to write down an
answer provided by the instructor, according to the report by
Special Commissioner of Investigation Edward Stancik.
</P>
<P>
   Stancik, summing up his latest probe in a 20-page letter to
schools Chancellor Harold Levy, said additional reports of cheating
surfaced following his initial investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Stancik called for either firing or severely disciplining most
of the teachers involved.
</P>
<P>
   Levy said Tuesday he has asked his general counsel to review the
report and determine its legitimacy. If it proves true, the
chancellor plans to take disciplinary action. Next, he is directing
a monitoring effort for Thursday's citywide math tests.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Levy has asked Stancik ''to assist future monitoring
activities by dispatching his investigators to schools in
coordination with the Board during the administration of
high-stakes tests.''
</P>
<P>
   United Federation of Teachers President Randi Weingarten said
that if Stancik's allegations were true, ''there should be serious
consequences.'' The union has an independent investigator reviewing
the report to see if the charges are accurate.
</P>
<P>
   In his December report, Stancik found that teachers and
administrators at 32 New York City schools helped students cheat on
standardized tests by providing them with questions in advance and
even marking test forms for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 2029 </TRAILER>
