<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Easley Leads NC's Crowded Gov. Race  </HEADLINE>
By DENNIS PATTERSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- State Attorney General Mike Easley led
Democratic candidates in early returns Tuesday and former Charlotte
Mayor Richard Vinroot led the Republicans in bids to succeed
retiring Gov. Jim Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   With 4 percent of precincts reporting, Easley had 8,240 votes,
or 57 percent, to Lt. Gov. Dennis Wicker's 5,535 votes, or 38
percent. Vinroot had 4,899 votes, or 48 percent, to state Rep. Leo
Daughtry's 3,478 votes, or 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Indiana, with 14 percent of precincts reporting, GOP Rep.
David McIntosh led with 35,428 votes, or 71 percent, in his effort
to win the nomination to challenge first-term Democratic Gov. Frank
O'Bannon. John Price, a lawyer who toured the state in a red school
bus, had 14,549 votes, or 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional races in both states drew heavy competition.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout, however, was expected to be low in both states since
the Republican and Democratic nominees for president are all but
final. George W. Bush and Al Gore already have won the necessary
number of delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore easily won their nominations in Indiana and North
Carolina. Voters in Washington, D.C., also made their presidential
choices Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, North Carolina's governor from 1975 to 1983 and re-elected
to two more terms starting in 1993, is barred by state law from
seeking another term. The Democrat is one of the state's best-known
politicians, with approval ratings exceeding 70 percent. He did not
endorse any of the 13 candidates.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Wicker and Easley argued over how best to
strengthen education programs with money from a not-yet-approved
state lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans fought over who was more conservative. Vinroot and
Daughtry criticized each other's conservative record on spending
and abortion, while debating whether to use attack ads. Former
state Rep. Chuck Neely avoided most of that fight, and trailed with
15 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Easley, a 50-year-old former state prosecutor who ran
unsuccessfully for Senate in 1990, led by as much as 20 points in
independent polls, but a poll last week showed his margin slipping
below 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Vinroot ran unsuccessfully for the GOP nomination for
governor. Daughtry was former majority leader of the state House.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a runoff, the winning candidate in each party must get
more than 40 percent of the vote. In all, there were seven
Democrats, four Republicans and two Libertarians running.
</P>
<P>
   In congressional races, three Republicans and a Libertarian
sought to challenge Rep. Mel Watt, a Democrat whose district's
lines are being challenged in federal court. Critics allege it was
drawn with an unconstitutional emphasis on race.
</P>
<P>
   In Indiana, conservative three-term Rep. McIntosh's decision to
run for governor set off a scramble to represent his east-central
Indiana district, which includes Muncie. Among the 11 candidates in
early results, former radio talk show host Mike Pence held a narrow
lead over Republican state Rep. Jeff Linder.
</P>
<P>
   McIntosh and Price were seeking the GOP nomination to challenge
O'Bannon, who has no opposition for the Democratic nomination.
Price promised to visit all 92 counties in his red bus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 2044 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
