<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Hepatitis A Exposure Feared  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- More than 700 children may have been
exposed to hepatitis A when they ate strawberry-topped waffles for
breakfast in a Head Start program.
</P>
<P>
   The children, ages 3 to 5, were to be immunized against the
disease Wednesday, said Francie Wise, director of communicable
disease control in Contra Costa County, east of San Francisco. The
139 adults who ate the strawberries will also be immunized.
</P>
<P>
   Sysco Corp. distributed the frozen fruit, which was served April
21. One week later, the company said the strawberries may have been
contaminated with the virus. A phone call to Houston-based Sysco
was not returned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It takes 15 to 50 days for symptoms to appear, and none of the
students has complained of illness, Wise said.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis A affects the liver. Wise said it is relatively mild
in children but can cause nausea, vomiting, diarrhea and jaundice
in adults. The virus is often transmitted by someone who does not
wash his or her hands after using the restroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
