<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Trade Backers Optimistic  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Backers of granting China permanent trade
benefits expressed new optimism Tuesday that they will prevail in a
tough showdown three weeks from now. President Clinton asserted
that the trade bill's rejection would be ''very, very unwise and
precarious.''
</P>
<P>
   To press his case, Clinton met with about 20 Democrats and
Republicans Tuesday evening at the White House to try to persuade
them to vote for permanent normal trade relations with China. He
brought along Martin Lee, leader of Hong Kong's Democratic Party,
to help him argue in favor of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Lee said that he had been warmly received but that he
didn't know if he'd secured any more yes votes for the measure. Lee
wants the United States to grant normal trade status with China,
but wants America and other members of the global trade forum to
pressure China for reform.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there's no deal, then what?'' he asked reporters. ''Would
human rights improve in China, or would China, in fact, be more
suppressive, seeing that the United States is no longer engaged?''
</P>
<P>
   This was Clinton's seventh meeting with undecided lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are optimistic. We are making our case,'' P.J. Crowley, a
spokesman for the National Security Council, told reporters. ''This
is still going to be a struggle. It's still going to be a tight
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, supporters picked up a key swing vote, that of Rep.
Steny Hoyer, D-Md., the first member of the House Democratic
leadership to back the pact. Hoyer had previously been uncommitted.
</P>
<P>
   And top House Republican leaders suggested they would consider
supporting a Democratic-sponsored proposal to set up a watchdog
commission to monitor human rights in China -- if it helps win
overall passage of the China trade deal.
</P>
<P>
   With the House back from a two-week spring recess, supporters
claimed that momentum was with them -- or at least that Democratic
defections had slowed despite heavy lobbying by labor unions and
the disapproval of House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration clearly had little success with its plan
to fly dozens of undecided House members to China during that
recess to persuade them to support the bill.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, only two undecided members -- Reps. Gregory Meeks,
D-N.Y., and Ruben Hinojosa, D-Texas -- took the trip, and both
returned still undecided. They were accompanied by two members who
already supported the measure: Reps. Norman Dicks, D-Wash., and
Greg Walden, R-Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wish more had gone on the trip,'' Meeks said. ''I thought
the trip was very beneficial. It gave me much more insight into
China and the Chinese people.'' But he said he needs more time to
decide.
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota Gov. Ed Schafer, a Republican also on the trip,
said he tried to persuade the two undecideds to vote for the trade
bill, but that ''they kept getting phone calls from the unions....
And the unions were saying, 'We gotta talk, don't make (decisions),
and when you get back, we want our time with you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif., the Clinton administration's point
man on the legislation, predicted an overall victory when the House
takes up the bill the week of May 22, expecting the support of 70
to 80 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   If Republican leaders can produce an expected 150-160 GOP votes,
then the legislation -- which needs 218 votes in the 435-member
House -- will pass, Matsui said. ''It's still going to be a tough
battle. But I feel very good about where we are right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to win,'' asserted U.S. Trade Representative
Charlene Barshefsky during a question session after a speech to the
Council of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Rep. Lois Capps, D-Calif., another previously
undecided member, announced her support for the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   And House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, told that
reporters Republicans were doing their part. ''We have picked up a
couple of good votes on our side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Armey and Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House
Ways and Means Committee, indicated they might support a proposal
by Rep. Sander Levin of Michigan, the committee's senior Democrat,
designed to make the bill more palatable to those concerned about
human rights and labor rights.
</P>
<P>
   Levin would set up a watchdog commission to monitor human rights
in China and could recommend economic sanctions. The Clinton
administration has signaled it could accept such a measure if it is
the cost of winning overall support for the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, where the legislation has wide bipartisan support,
is expected to take up the measure after the House vote, probably
in June.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would grant China permanent normal trade relations,
putting it on the same footing as nearly every other country with
which the United States trades. Currently, China's trade status
must be reviewed annually.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also ease China's entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton presented one of his strongest cases yet for the
legislation on Tuesday, during a speech before a conference of the
Independent Insurance Agents of America.
</P>
<P>
   ''From a national security point of view, it would in my view be
a very, very unwise and precarious move to say that the United
States doesn't care whether they're part of the world community or
not,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said there was still time to defeat the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be a very close vote,'' said Fred Clarke, a
spokesman for House Democratic Whip David Bonior, D-Mich., a
leading opponent of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
