<HEADLINE> Court Hears Confederate Flag Flap  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- The squabble over the lieutenant
governor's decision to prevent a protest over the Confederate
battle emblem on the state flag moved to the state Supreme Court
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the high court blocked a judge's ruling that found
Lt. Gov. Amy Tuck had violated the constitution. Justices will
review written arguments filed Tuesday and rule later.
</P>
<P>
   Tuck was sued over the weekend by seven black senators after she
refused to let them have bills read aloud before votes, a common
legislative practice of protest.
</P>
<P>
   At least one black legislator wanted to have 110 budget bills
read to bring attention to the failure of a proposal to remove the
Confederate Battle flag from the state banner.
</P>
<P>
   Tuck said the bill reading could have kept lawmakers from ending
the four-month session on time at the end of the week.
</P>
</TEXT>
