<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arist Ousts Founder Clive Davis  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Music executive Clive Davis, who helped launch
the careers of pop stars like Billy Joel and Bruce Springsteen, has
lost a power struggle over his future at Arista Records, the
company he founded 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   BMG Entertainment, a division of German media conglomerate
Bertelsmann, announced Tuesday that Antonio ''L.A.'' Reid will take
Davis' spot as head of Arista on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''Antonio brings to Arista an inspired track record as a
businessman, Grammy award-winning producer and deeply committed
record man,'' said Strauss Zelnick, chief executive of BMG
Entertainment, which owns Arista.
</P>
<P>
   The move ends a six-month feud between Davis, 66, and his
corporate bosses. Bertelsmann traditionally enforces a retirement
age of 60 on its top executives.
</P>
<P>
   ''Though I regret the imposition of the Bertelsmann retirement
age policy, it's time now to turn to a new and vital chapter in
this fast changing world of music,'' Davis said in a statement. A
publicist, Howard Rubenstein, said Davis is weighing offers from
BMG and others to create a new company.
</P>
<P>
   BMG had been grooming Reid, an executive with LaFace Records and
an accomplished record producer with partner Babyface, as a
potential successor and sent him to Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   At Arista, Davis presided over a pop empire that includes
Whitney Houston, Sarah McLachlan, Sean ''Puffy'' Combs, Aretha
Franklin, Monica and Deborah Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' career began at CBS Records in the 1960s, signing artists
like Janis Joplin, Billy Joel and Springsteen. He was fired in 1973
when the label accused him of mismanaging funds, but he quickly
founded Arista, which has been a haven for artists mostly in the
pop and rhythm 'n' blues fields. Arista was sold to Bertelsmann in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many music executives who concern themselves strictly
with business, Davis often took an active role in molding artists
by producing albums and picking the songs they record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
