<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Ontario Celebrates Death of Budget Deficit
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Explosive economic growth has enabled the Ontario
government to balance its books, cut taxes, boost health-care
spending and even pony up a billion-dollar ''dividend'' on last
year's taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative government celebrated the death of the deficit
Tuesday with a $1.4-billion increase in health funding and more of
the tax cuts that first propelled the party to power in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The budget, balanced fully in Ontario for the first time in 30
years, also featured more money for schools and universities, a
battery of new anti-crime squads and $1 billion for the province's
aging network of highways.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to last year's mighty economic surge, the Tories will
also start reducing the $114-billion debt faster than planned,
spending at least $1 billion on debt each year, said Finance
Minister Ernie Eves.
</P>
<P>
   And Ontarians also get a ''dividend'' check of up to $200 for
last year's taxes, at a cost to the government of about $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ---
British Airways: Ottawa Should Rein in Air Canada
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Air Canada's ''near monopoly'' over Canadian skies
will drive up fares domestically and internationally if Ottawa
doesn't step in to ensure other carriers can compete, British
Airways warned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   New federal legislation must ensure that Air Canada doesn't
drive out competition, which is vital to protecting consumer choice
and keeping air fares affordable, British Airways representatives
told the Commons transport committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Legislation to ensure that Air Canada's near monopoly does not
extract a heavy price to consumers is essential,'' said lawyer
Robert Russell, who represents three international airlines:
British Airways, Air France and Cathay Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Tom Long: Quebecers Like His Small-Government Message
</P>
<P>
   SHAWINIGAN, Quebec (AP) -- Canadian Alliance leadership hopeful
Tom Long stood by the Saint-Maurice River in Jean Chretien's riding
Tuesday and said federal support for an ornamental fountain
typifies the prime minister's arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   Long berated the federal Liberals for giving $200,000 in
job-creation money toward the $500,000 fountain, which is to be
built in the middle of the river.
</P>
<P>
   He said it demonstrates Chretien's ''arrogant disregard'' for
how taxpayers' money is spent.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is as powerful a symbol as I can think of, of the
difference Canadians are going to see between a Canadian Alliance
government under my leadership and what they've had under Jean
Chretien and his Liberals,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   In Ottawa, however, Chretien defended the federal contribution
to the fountain, saying it accounts for only a small portion of the
funding for the tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Newspapers, Radio, TV To Face Ownership review
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- A government review of media ownership rules will
include radio and television, not just newspapers, says Heritage
Minister Sheila Copps.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials have been reviewing concentration of media
ownership in Canada for several months and are looking at aligning
newspaper and broadcast ownership regulations, Copps said.
</P>
<P>
   Copps was expanding on comments Monday that the government is
reviewing newspaper ownership, including rules that have the effect
of restricting foreign holdings to 25 per cent of a newspaper
company.
</P>
<P>
   The review was begun long before newspaper baron Conrad Black's
Hollinger group put 350 small and mid-sized newspapers in Canada
and the United States up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson Corp., owner of the Globe and Mail and five other
dailies including the Winnipeg Free Press, said in February that it
plans to sell all its newspapers except the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   ---
BC Premier's Son To Plead Not Guilty to Assault Charges
</P>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Ontario (AP) -- A son of British Columbia Premier Ujjal
Dosanjh will plead not guilty to charges he assaulted a police
officer and caused a disturbance after a violent scuffle with
police outside a downtown bar, his lawyer said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He will plead not guilty for sure,'' said Patrick Ducharme,
lawyer for 24-year-old Asseem Dosanjh.
</P>
<P>
   Dosanjh was charged earlier Tuesday following his arrest over
the weekend. He had been celebrating his law-school graduation from
the University of Windsor when the melee broke out.
</P>
<P>
   He was released on $500 bail and will appear in court again on
May 26.
</P>
<P>
   According to a police news release, punches were exchanged,
pepper spray was used by police and clothing was torn in the
Saturday morning skirmish.
</P>
