<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Probed in Lumumba Slaying  </HEADLINE>
By RAF CASERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Belgium's parliament opened an
investigation Tuesday into possible government involvement in the
1961 killing of Congo's first premier, Patrice Lumumba, whose death
shocked the world during the turbulent months following Congolese
independence from Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   The parliamentary inquiry follows publication of the book ''The
Murder of Lumumba,'' which claims Belgium was responsible for the
logistics behind the capture and execution of the fierce opponent
of Congo's old colonial masters.
</P>
<P>
   Lumumba was revered by many, in Africa and the West, as an
enlightened anti-colonial crusader. But in the Cold War politics of
the time, he was also depicted as a pro-communist agitator.
</P>
<P>
   Previous theories on his killing have centered on U.S.
involvement, or political rivalries within Congo.
</P>
<P>
   ''A self-respecting nation should not fear the past and must
have the courage to investigate possible errors,'' said Liberal
Party legislator Geert Versnick, who on Tuesday was elected
chairman of a committee to investigate whether Belgium played a
role in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the bloody turmoil that followed independence, Lumumba was
abducted by Congolese rivals, taken to the breakaway province of
Katanga and killed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole murder was orchestrated from Brussels, with
cooperation from Congolese,'' Ludo De Witte, the writer of ''The
Murder of Lumumba'' told the newspaper De Standaard recently.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most widely-quoted elements suggesting possible
government involvement is a cable from then-African Affairs
Minister Harold d'Aspremont Lynden stating that ''the most
important objective for Congo, Katanga and, of course, Belgium, is
the final elimination of Lumumba.''
</P>
<P>
   With the establishment of the parliamentary committee,
historians will now be able to consult archives which had
previously been closed to them.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, which is expected to last one year, comes at
a time when Belgium is trying to refocus its policies toward
central Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian Foreign Minister Louis Michel recently met with
Congolese President Laurent Kabila during a tour of the region, and
Belgian Prime Minister Guy Verhofstadt went to Rwanda last month
and apologized the lack of international action to prevent the 1994
ethnic slaughter in that former Belgian colony.
</P>
<P>
   If the parliament committee confirms the book's claims of
Belgian military involvement, Belgium is expected to issue an
official apology for Lumumba's killing. Kabila has already said he
would forgive the culprits if they ask forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium held sway over Congo for some 80 years with a
ruthlessness that became proverbial and was highlighted in Joseph
Conrad's book ''Heart of Darkness,'' a fictional story that touches
on colonial exploitation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 2129 </TRAILER>
