<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, May 2, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rebels Say Two Hostages Die in Clash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TALIPAO, Philippines (AP) -- Rebels said two foreign hostages died in a clash
early Wednesday between military troops and Muslim guerrillas holding 21 people
in the southern Philippines. But military officials said they had no knowledge
of any fatalities among the hostages kidnapped from a Malasian resort.
Meanwhile, the same rebel group holding another group of 27 Filipino hostages in
neighboring Basilan province offered Wednesday to release all their captives if
the military halts its pursuit.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Puerto Rico Protesters Hold Their Ground
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Protesters on Vieques island that serves as the
U.S. Navy's prime Atlantic training area are holding their ground in protest
over bombing of the island. The protesters who have blocked bombing on Vieques
island for over a year say that federal agents would have to arrest them to
clear the range but promised they wouldn't fight back. With three U.S. warships
offshore, the occupiers readied for what they called ''the invasion,'' a
possible effort to remove them.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ky. Launching Anti-Smoking Campaign
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) -- Kentucky, the No. 1 state in smoking and No. 2 in
tobacco growing, is launching its first statewide kick-the-habit campaign, with
a modest goal to start with. The state's top public health official would like
Kentucky to fall to No. 2 in its smoking rate. ''If we can make it to No. 2, we
can probably make it to No. 5 or No. 8,'' Dr. Rice Leach, public health
commissioner, said today. ''If we can do that, we're on our way to getting
somewhere in the middle of the pack.''
</P>
