Fortier's Lawyer Criticizes Judge
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- A judge who resentenced Michael Fortier to 12 years in prison
in the Oklahoma bombing case was acting vindictively because the first sentence
he handed down was thrown out, according to Fortier's lawyer. In a brief filed
today with the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, lawyer Michael G. McGuire of
Tulsa, Okla., argued that U.S. District Judge Thomas Van Bebber of Kansas City
showed ''a deliberate effort to achieve a punitive level'' by sentencing Fortier
to 12 years for a second time. Fortier appealed the initial sentence and the
appeals court in Denver sent the case back to Van Bebber, saying he mistakenly
used guidelines for first-degree murder rather than manslaughter.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Teachers Urge School Repair Funds
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than 20 million schoolchildren nationwide attend
schools that are falling apart or ill-equipped for classroom computers, the
nation's largest teachers union says in a report calling on states to pony up
their budget surpluses. Right now, states need $322 billion for school
construction -- roughly 10 times what they currently spend and nearly three
times what the federal government has estimated they need, the National
Education Association said in a report to be released tomorrow.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AT&AMP;T Stock Down Over Profit Warning
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T's stock slid 14 percent today as the company issued its
first profit warning under chief executive C. Michael Armstrong, fueling worries
about whether his radical remake of the nation's largest long-distance company
will succeed. AT&AMP;T fell $7.12{ per share to $41.87{. The disappointing forecast,
which came as AT&AMP;T posted first-quarter results that met most expectations,
dampened the enthusiasm created by last week's initial public offering of $10.6
billion worth of stock in the company's wireless business.
</P>
