<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reds 7, Phillies 0  </HEADLINE>
By ROB MAADDI, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Denny Neagle allowed one hit in six innings,
and Sean Casey hit a two-run homer as the Cincinnati Reds beat the
Philadelphia Phillies 7-0 Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle (3-0) allowed a leadoff double to Doug Glanville and
didn't give up another hit. He struck out five and walked four
while extending his scoreless innings streak to 18.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia has lost four straight and 14 of 17.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle allowed two hits in seven innings in a 12-1 victory over
the New York Mets in his last start on April 26. Scott Sullivan
allowed one hit in the final three innings for his second save.
</P>
<P>
   Casey hit a two-run homer in the second and Pokey Reese had two
RBIs to lead the Reds to their third straight victory and fifth in
six games.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Ashby (1-3) struggled for the second straight outing,
allowing six runs -- five earned -- in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies got just one runner to third base. Neagle retired
nine straight and 11 of 12 at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. went 0-for-4 in his first game in Philadelphia.
Griffey got a little flavor of the Philly fans with two outs in the
fifth when a fan ran out to center-field, well ahead of the
security officers. The man shook Griffey's hand and did a dance
before falling to his knees and surrendering.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds took a 1-0 lead in the second when Reese lined a single
off the left-field wall to score Gookie Dawkins. Casey followed
with a two-run homer to right-center to make it 3-0. It was the
first homer of the season for Casey, who hit 25 last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds put the game away with three runs in the sixth. Eddie
Taubensee, Aaron Boone and Dawkins hit successive singles to make
it 4-0. A sacrifice fly by Reese made it 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   Dawkins then scored from second as Casey reached first on a
throwing error by Mickey Morandini, giving the Reds a 6-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Phillies, who entered the game with a major
league-leading .990 fielding percentage, committed three of their
12 errors Tuesday. ... Reese, who won the NL Gold Glove last
season, committed his fourth error at second base. ... Injured
closer Mike Jackson, out with a strained right shoulder, threw
Tuesday for the first time since April 18. He reported some pain in
his shoulder, but said he was encouraged by the outing. ''The true
test will come when I throw off the mound,'' Jackson said. ...
Injured reliever Jeff Brantley pitched one inning at Triple-A
Scranton Wilkes-Barre. He allowed two runs and one hit. Brantley is
scheduled to pitch again Wednesday. ... Ashby had a career ERA of
2.98 in March and April before posting a 5.17 ERA this April.
</P>
</TEXT>
