<HEADLINE> Greek, Turk Officials Meet Albright  </HEADLINE>
By DAFNA LINZER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Three weeks before the United Nations convenes
another round of talks on the future of Cyprus talks, the Greek and
Turkish foreign ministers met Tuesday with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to discuss the divided Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
   Albright met separately and jointly with George Papandreou of
Greece and Ismail Cem of Turkey at the Waldorf Astoria hotel after
attending a daylong seminar on the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials provided no details of the talks,
saying only that the three discussed the Cyprus dispute and
regional issues relating to the Balkans and economic reform in both
Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Cyprus has been divided into a Turkish north and Greek south
since a Turkish invasion in 1974, which came in the wake of an
Athens-backed coup by supporters of union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
   A breakaway Turkish Cypriot state declared in 1983 in the north
is only recognized by Turkey, which maintains 35,000 troops there.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has mediated two rounds of indirect talks
between Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash and is hosting a third round at U.N.
headquarters beginning May 23.
</P>
<P>
   The talks have deadlocked so far over Denktash's insistence on
the recognition of the breakaway state in the north as a
precondition for substantive face to face negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Papandreou, Cem, Albright and Javier Solana, the European
Union's foreign policy chief, opened the day by addressing a forum
on the Balkans at the East West Institute, a European-American
nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   In her remarks to the forum, Albright took a swipe at Congress'
slashing of funds for American foreign policy, saying U.S. payments
for the enormous U.N. mission running Kosovo were being withheld.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is irresponsible,'' Albright told the forum. ''The 21st
century is no time to retreat. Congress should appropriate the
funds the president has requested.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
