<HEADLINE> Deliberations Halted in Edwards Case  </HEADLINE>
V0847-----
u a *1110AP-Edwards-Trial     05-02 0311
*1110 AP-Edwards-Trial,0310   
Deliberations Halted in Edwards Case
AP Photos, 
By NATALIE GOTT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Deliberations in former Gov. Edwin
Edwards' federal racketeering trial were halted after six days
Tuesday while the judge interviewed each of the 12 jurors.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Frank Polozola would not say what his
inquiry involved but said attorneys were to report to court early
Wednesday morning to finish discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ''No decision has been made on the matter before the court,''
Polozola said in an open court hearing Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors did not deliberate all day, he said. Polozola said
the jurors would report to court an hour later than usual
Wednesday, at 9 a.m., and may begin deliberating then.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, his son, Stephen, State Sen. Greg Tarver and four
others are accused in a series of extortion schemes to manipulate
the licensing of Louisiana riverboat casinos from 1991 through
1997. If convicted on all counts, Edwards, 72, faces more than 300
years in prison. Deliberations began April 24.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday began with attorneys and defendants meeting privately
for about an hour in the judge's chambers. Polozola then called
everyone into court, where he revealed that he was going to conduct
an inquiry and that the jurors were not deliberating.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys, defendants and the judge remained locked up in
the courtroom for more than 10 hours before the judge unlocked the
door to tell reporters that the issue the court faced had to be
dealt with outside the presence of the public.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court has interviewed each juror and has just completed
the process -- all 12 jurors,'' Polozola said.
</P>
<P>
   During breaks from the marathon session with the judge,
attorneys refused to discuss what was taking place in the
courtroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
