<HEADLINE> RNC 'Census' Did Not Violate Rules  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Postal Service has ruled that a Republican
National Committee fund-raising mailing sent to members, which
included a GOP-specific census form, did not violate federal postal
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The six-page RNC mailing had been criticized by Democrats as
looking too much like a Census Bureau document. Last week, Rep.
Carolyn Maloney of New York, senior Democrat on the House
Government Committee's census panel, said the mailing trivialized
the Census Bureau's current efforts to count the population and
asked the Postal Service to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   The RNC mailing is ''not actionable,'' Postal Service inspector
Daniel Mihalko said Tuesday. It is not a ''government look-alike
mailing.''
</P>
<P>
   The mailing came in an enveloped emblazoned with the phrase
''REPUBLICAN CENSUS DOCUMENT ENCLOSED.'' The first page of the
cover letter is written on Republican National Committee
letterhead, and the bottom of the page has the phrase ''Not printed
at taxpayers' expense. Paid for by the RNC.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're elated that Congresswoman Maloney closely reads her mail
and now hope she ends her partisan sniping once and for all,'' said
RNC spokesman Mark Pfeifle.
</P>
<P>
   However, Maloney said, ''It may not be illegal but it certainly
is a cheap stunt that hurts the census.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
