<HEADLINE> Dems Hold NY County Legislature  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT WASHINGTON, N.Y. (AP) -- Democrats in the Long Island
suburbs held onto their control of the Nassau County legislature
Tuesday when a 29-year-old bankruptcy lawyer won a special election
to succeed his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have held a solid lock on the county since World War
I, but lost it last year after a series of fiscal problems and a
last-minute property tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   But the death of Barbara Johnson from breast cancer in March
gave Republicans another chance. The race in one of the nation's
richest counties was being watched as a possible harbinger for the
November presidential and Senate elections.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's son, Scott, won with 6,774 votes, or 58 percent of the
vote in the tiny legislative district mostly on the island's North
Shore. He beat Republican Linda H. Green, an assistant principal in
Queens and the former town clerk in North Hempstead, who drew 2,650
votes, or 23 percent. Green Party candidate Ben Zwirn, a former
North Hempstead town supervisor, drew 2,278 votes, or 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Helping in the campaign for the lone seat on the 19-member
Legislature were Republicans Rudy Giuliani and Sen. John McCain,
and Democratic Sen. Charles Schumer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
