<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, May 2, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Arkansas Woman Executed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VARNER, Ark. (AP) -- A former nurse who asked for the death penalty for
drugging and suffocating her two children was executed by injection today in
Arkansas' first execution of a woman in more than 150 years. Christina Marie
Riggs, 28, was the fifth woman executed in the United States since the Supreme
Court lifted a ban on capital punishment in 1976. She had maintained throughout
that she wanted to die and her last words reflected her grief. She had withdrawn
all appeals and chose not to seek clemency from Gov. Mike Huckabee.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Two Hostages Die in Clash, Rebels Say
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TALIPAO, Philippines (AP) -- Two foreign hostages died early Wednesday when
military troops and their Muslim rebel captors clashed in the Southern
Philippines. But military officials said they had no knowledge of any fatalities
among the hostages kidnapped from a Malasian resort. Meanwhile, the same rebel
group holding another group of 27 Filipino hostages in neighboring Basilan
province offered Wednesday to release all their captives if the military halts
its pursuit.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nuclear Pledge Called Inadequate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- A coalition of countries said today that a new pledge
by the key five nuclear powers to work to eliminate their nuclear arsenals falls
short of demands that they actually get rid of them. ''We stress that the total
elimination of nuclear weapons is an obligation and a priority and not an
ultimate goal,'' said a statement by Mexico, Ireland, South Africa, Egypt,
Sweden, New Zealand and Brazil. The statement was a response to a joint position
paper issued Monday in which the United States, Russia, China, France and
Britain pledged their ''unequivocal commitment to the ultimate goals of complete
elimination of nuclear disarmament.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Puerto Rico Protesters Hold Their Ground
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Protesters on Vieques island that serves as the
U.S. Navy's prime Atlantic training area are holding their ground in protest
over bombing of the island. The protesters who have blocked bombing on Vieques
island for over a year say that federal agents would have to arrest them to
clear the range but promised they wouldn't fight back. With three U.S. warships
offshore, the occupiers readied for what they called ''the invasion,'' a
possible effort to remove them.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Economic Indicators Reverse Decline
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The U.S. economy is set to grow well into the second half of
the year, according to two private reports released today, while the government
provided fresh evidence in a third report that rising interest rates have done
little to dissuade new-home buyers. Analysts said the figures pointed to further
interest rate increases by inflation fighters at the Federal Reserve. The Index
of Leading Economic Indicators, which is designed to predict economic activity
three to six months ahead, rose 0.1 percent in March.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
British Upbeat After Irish Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- British officials detected ''a bit more hope'' for solving
Northern Ireland's political deadlock following a day of negotiations Tuesday,
but couldn't immediately agree with Irish colleagues on whether to follow up
with more talks this week. No indication was given as to who, if anyone, had
given ground on the intractable issue of paramilitary disarmament, but Britain's
senior official in Northern Ireland, Peter Mandelson, told reporters he was
''somewhat encouraged.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Microsoft Defense Seeks Gov't Files
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft plans to ask for authority to seek government
records and subpoena witnesses to support its argument that breaking the company
in two would be going too far, a company spokesman said today. Jim Cullinan said
he expects a long discovery process to find out how the Justice Department came
up with its ''Draconian and overbearing'' proposal. The company is scheduled to
file its response to the agency's proposed remedy in the antitrust case with
U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson on May 10.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nasdaq Down 172; Dow Ends Down 80
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell broadly today after AT&AMP;T delivered a cautious
profit outlook and investors took profits from a three-day rally in technology
shares. Worries about rising interest rates hung over the market, keeping volume
low and buyers scarce. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 80.66 to close at
10,731.12. On the NYSE, decliners led advancers 1,696-1,293. The Nasdaq
composite index fell 172.63 to 3,785.45, its first decline in four sessions. In
Japan, financial markets were closed on Wednesday for Constitution Day, a
national holiday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Suns' Kidd Back in Starting Lineup
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Jason Kidd, out since March 22 with a broken left ankle,
returned to the starting lineup for the Phoenix Suns today night in Game 4 of
their playoff series against the San Antonio Spurs. ''The doctors say he's 100
percent and he's ready to go, so he's in there,'' coach Scott Skiles said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS
</SUBHEAD>
