<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 23:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Woman Gets Yad Vashem Medal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- A former school teacher who saved Jewish children
during World War II on Tuesday received the Medal of the Righteous
from Yad Vashem, Israel's Holocaust Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Edmond Durand, 89, was among three living French citizens
honored for their wartime heroism at a ceremony at the French
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Ambassador Eliahu Ben Elissar presented the medals to
Durand, Raymonde Fanouillaire and Marcelle Martin, who risked their
lives to save Jews from arrest and deportation to Nazi death camps.
Thirteen awards were presented posthumously.
</P>
<P>
   About 76,000 Jews, including 12,000 children, were deported from
France during World War II. Only about 2,500 survived.
</P>
<P>
   Fanouillaire sheltered 40 German Jewish boys at Chateau Quincy
outside Paris, where German soldiers were also billeted. Organizers
said Fanouillaire was in her seventies, but no exact age was given.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 76, provided food and clothing to two Jewish women,
Bella and Esther Kurzbatt, helping them survive in hiding at their
own home in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Durand was a young junior high school teacher in Castres,
southern France when the Nazis invaded the country. He was
approached by his principal, a member of the French Resistance, and
asked if he could find shelter for several Jewish children. He hid
them for more than eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Durand said he hoped his actions would set an example for young
people today.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I did wasn't anything special,'' he told Europe I radio.
''I did it as a human being. It was part of my Christian duty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 2305 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000502.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks 5, Brewers 1  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Steve Finley homered twice, and Todd
Stottlemyre allowed four hits in seven innings Tuesday night to
lead the Arizona Diamondbacks over the Milwaukee Brewers 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   Finley had another tremendous game at County Stadium, where he
is 10-for-18 (.556) with seven homers and 13 RBIs in his last four
games.
</P>
<P>
   Finley and Travis Lee hit consecutive homers in the fourth
inning, with Finley getting a two-run drive off Jimmy Haynes (3-2).
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre (5-1) took care of the rest, striking out five and
pitching out of a jam in the seventh. Finley also hit a solo homer
in the eighth off Ray King and tied San Francisco's Barry Bonds for
the NL home-run lead at 11. It was the 16th multihomer game of
Finley's career, his second this year.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee, shut out three times in its previous six games,
received a solo homer from Geoff Jenkins in the fourth but got only
one other runner as far as third base in the first six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The NL West-leading Diamondbacks won for the fifth time in seven
games, all on the road. Milwaukee has followed a 2-7 road trip by
losing four of its first five in a 10-game homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre is playing with a torn rotator cuff sustained early
last season. He pitched past the fifth inning for just the third
time this year, baffling the overswinging Brewers with offspeed
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee loaded the bases with one out in the seventh on a
single by Jenkins and two walks, but Stottlemyre got Henry Blanco
to ground into a double play. The chilly County Stadium crowd
didn't even bother to boo.
</P>
<P>
   Blanco was back in Milwaukee's lineup for the first time since
April 15 with a cut on his right hand that still isn't completely
healed. He still threw out Tony Womack trying to steal second in
the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes pitched well but again received no run support from the
Brewers. He allowed six hits and five walks in seven innings.
Notes: Brewers reliever Rocky Coppinger had successful ligament
replacement surgery on Tuesday in Birmingham, Ala. Coppinger
developed an inflammation in his right elbow during the first week
of March. He's finished for the season. ... The Diamondbacks'
back-to-back homers were their first since April 10. ... Mark
Loretta, who was scratched from the lineup on Tuesday night because
of a strained hamstring, is the NL's top defensive shortstop after
one month of play. He has a .991 fielding percentage, with just one
error in 109 chances. ... Jay Bell doubled home the Diamondbacks'
final run in the ninth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 2307 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000502.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs 11, Astros 1  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ARMOUR, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- New elbow, same old Kerry Wood. Or close enough,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching in a major league game for the first time in almost 19
months, Wood gave up just one run -- a homer -- and three hits in six
innings Tuesday night as the Chicago Cubs routed the Houston Astros
11-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros didn't come close to touching him until Daryle Ward'
homer to right in the sixth, putting just six others on base and
getting only one past second.
</P>
<P>
   And the elbow that was surgically repaired April 8, 1999, after
he blew it out in spring training? Just fine, thank you very much.
Wood even hit the third home run of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's going to be a lot of guys on pins and needles every
time he throws,'' Cubs manager Don Baylor said before the game.
''He's one of those rare commodities you do have, and everybody's
going to be watching because he had a major injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood wasn't the same, dominating power pitcher he was the last
time he faced the Astros at Wrigley Field, when he tied a major
league record with 20 strikeouts in just his fifth career start.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 NL Rookie of the Year returned to the mound just four
days shy of the two-year anniversary of that May 6, 1998 game.
</P>
<P>
   Wood struck out four, but only one in the first four innings.
Most of his outs were on fly balls to the outfield, and he got some
help from his teammates, including a jaw-dropping, diving, backhand
catch by Sammy Sosa in the second inning. He threw one wild pitch,
walked four and sent a couple Astros jumping out of the way of
wicked inside pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't matter. Except for Ward's homer, the Astros had as
much luck against him as they did in 1998, when Wood had a 0.53 ERA
against them.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I'm expecting today is, hopefully, maybe a little rust,''
Jeff Bagwell, who accounted for three of Wood's 20 strikeouts two
years ago, said before the game. ''Obviously, it's going to be very
hard for him to duplicate the 20-strikeout game. But if anybody can
do it, he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood showed he can hit the ball almost as well as he throws it,
too. He hit a two-run homer just over the left-field fence in his
first at-bat, the 11th home run allowed this year by Jose Lima
(1-5).
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs rocked Lima for four runs in the second inning, and
chased him in the fifth after five more. Lima, whose ERA swelled to
9.59, tipped his cap to the crowd as he left the field.
</P>
<P>
   While it takes most pitchers about 18 months to recover from
''Tommy John'' surgery, that hasn't tempered the expectations for
Wood. Fans can't see the scar on his right elbow, and most expect
him to come back just as scary-good as he was in 1998, when he drew
comparisons to Nolan Ryan and Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   The media contingent was as big as it was for the Cubs' home
opener. Cameras followed Wood everywhere he went before the game.
When he walked out of the dugout, there were cameras. When he took
batting practice, there were cameras. And when he stretched, there
were the cameras again.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the fans were even more excited. Wood got a
standing ovation as he left the dugout before the game, but he
didn't show any reaction or do anything to indicate this game was
special. He tip-toed over the third baseline as he walked to the
mound, but he does that before every inning.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd of 38,121 cheered every warmup pitch, and
there was a huge roar when Craig Biggio fouled off the first pitch
of the game for a strike. There was another big cheer when Ken
Caminiti swung and missed for the first swinging strike.
</P>
<P>
   Wood didn't get two strikes on anyone until Mitch Meluskey, the
second batter in the second inning. And he didn't get his first
strikeout until Lima came up in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Lima went down on a called strike, and the fans cheered and
waved the ''K'' signs they've had in storage the last 19 months.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Willie Green went 4-for-4, tying his career high. It was
the first four-hit game by a Cub this season. ... Tuesday's game
was the first night game of the season at Wrigley Field. ... Mel
Gibson was the guest conductor for the seventh-inning stretch. ...
Wood's last home run was in his last regular season appearance, on
Aug. 31, 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
