<HEADLINE> Pistons Deny Irvine Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Pistons denied a report
Tuesday that George Irvine will remain as coach next season.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN reported that Irvine, the Pistons' interim coach, would get
the job, but a team spokesman denied that.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is not the case as of right now,'' spokesman J.J. Carter
said. Team management and Irvine ''do plan to talk at some time in
the near future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN reported that the Pistons will likely sign Irvine to a two-
or three-year deal, possibly as early as this week.
</P>
<P>
   Irvine was an assistant coach under Alvin Gentry and became
interim head coach when Gentry was fired March 6.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Irvine said he had no interest in having the
interim removed from his title.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been there. I've done that. And I don't have any desire
to do it anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit topped the 100-point mark in 12 of 24 games under Irvine
and posted a 14-10 record. They were 28-30 under Gentry. The
Pistons were 7-5 on the road under Irvine, after having lost 11
straight on the road before his promotion.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Heat swept Detroit in their best-of-five first-round
playoff series. The Pistons played most of the second game and all
of the final game without All-Star forward Grant Hill after he
fractured his left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought George Irvine did a great job filling in and really
gave us a big lift down the stretch,'' reserve forward Jud Buechler
said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Irvine was an assistant with the Golden State Warriors for two
years and worked for 16 years in the Indiana Pacers' front office.
He played in the ABA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
