<HEADLINE> Tigers 7, Red Sox 6, 12 Innings  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD ULMAN, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Wendell Magee drove in the tying run in the
seventh inning then hit his third homer of the season in the 12th
to spoil a strong relief appearance by Tim Wakefield and give the
Detroit Tigers a 7-6 win over the Boston Red Sox on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers broke a six-game losing streak against the Red Sox
and won for only the third time in their last 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   Magee entered the game as a pinch hitter for Luis Polonia in the
seventh and hit an RBI groundout that scored Rob Fick, tying the
game 6-6. Wakefield (1-2) then replaced Rheal Cormier and allowed
only two hits and no runs in the next 4 2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   But with one out in the 12th, Magee homered over the left-field
wall. It was just his sixth hit of the season in 28 at bats.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Blair (1-0) pitched two scoreless innings and Todd Jones
recorded his fifth save, allowing one hit in the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Encarnacion's RBI single had given Detroit a 5-4 lead in
the sixth, Troy O'Leary's two-run homer, his fourth, put Boston
ahead 6-5 in the bottom of the inning before Magee tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rose had pitched six innings of three-hit ball in his last
start, a 10-0 shutout in Detroit on April 19. But on Tuesday, he
didn't get out of the second inning as the Tigers hit for the cycle
and batted around for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez began the four-run inning with his fourth homer,
Bobby Higginson tripled and Damion Easley doubled for a 2-0 lead. A
groundout moved Easley to third and he scored on Tony Clark's
single. Gregg Jefferies added an RBI single that made it 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox tied the game in the bottom of the inning against
Mark Johnson, making his first career start. They loaded the bases
with no outs on singles by Nomar Garciaparra and O'Leary and a walk
to Carl Everett. All three scored on Jason Varitek's single when
center fielder Encarnacion's throw to third base -- while third
baseman Jefferies was halfway between the base and home plate --
went into the Detroit dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek scored the tying run on Wilton Veras' sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Gonzalez' homer was the Tigers' 13th in a row with no one
on base. Of their 24 homers, 17 have been solo shots. ...
Encarnacion extended his hitting streak to a career-best 14 games,
going 2-for-7. ... John Wasdin, who relieved Rose with one out in
the second, left the game after Polonia led off the fourth with a
hard shot off Wasdin's leg. He suffered a bruise below his left
kneecap and was taken to a hospital for X-rays. ... Everett's
nine-game hitting streak ended. ... Detroit coach Juan Samuel will
have his appeal hearing Wednesday on his 15-game suspension for his
role in a brawl April 22 with the Chicago White Sox. Samuel said it
will be conducted by Paul Beeston, the highest ranking official in
the commissioner's office besides commissioner Bud Selig. . . .
Reliever Jim Poole is appealing his $500 fine for the brawl.
</P>
</TEXT>
