<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Okla. Health Commissioner Arrested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The interim commissioner of the state
Health Department was arrested Tuesday as part of a criminal
investigation into the department and its regulation of nursing
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Brent VanMeter, 46, was being held in the Oklahoma County jail.
He was arrested for allegedly violating a federal code that
pertains to theft or bribery concerning programs that receive
federal funds, the FBI said.
</P>
<P>
   Statements issued by Gov. Frank Keating and the attorney general
said search warrants were issued for offices at the state agency as
well as some businesses and homes.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left at VanMeter's home were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Drew Edmondson said the federal search warrants
support a joint state-federal investigation into ''possible
criminal activity which may have impacted the health care of
patients in several Oklahoma nursing homes.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the warrants sought records from some agency employees
and private citizens involved in the nursing home industry.
</P>
<P>
   VanMeter has been in the post while the commissioner is on
medical leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
