<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suns' Kidd Back in Starting Lineup  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Jason Kidd, out since March 22 with a broken left
ankle, returned to the starting lineup for the Phoenix Suns Tuesday
night in Game 4 of their playoff series against the San Antonio
Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The doctors say he's 100 percent and he's ready to go, so he's
in there,'' coach Scott Skiles said.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd looked different with his newly blond curls, but he played
the same. He finished with nine points and 10 assists in 31 minutes
as the Suns beat the Spurs 89-78 to win the best-of-five series
3-1. Kidd made his first three shots, the last one a 3-pointer to
give the Suns the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd has been working out for more than a week with no ill
effects, and if he can play, he should start, Skiles said. Kidd led
the NBA in assists at 10.1 per game, along with 14.3 points and 7.2
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's one of the best players in the league,'' Skiles said.
''There's no reason to not start. He's comfortable starting. He's
done it his whole career.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd returned before San Antonio's Tim Duncan could. Duncan
practiced on Monday, but said at Tuesday morning's shootaround that
he was too sore to play in a game. Duncan did not appear in the
playoffs because of a slight tear in the cartilage of his left
knee.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Skiles announced Kidd would start, Kidd was more
evasive, saying it would be a game-time decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yeah, I feel good,'' Kidd said. ''I think my body and my mind
is fresh and confident. The biggest thing is I don't want to do
anything to disturb the team. I want to help the team win. The guys
have been playing well without me, so we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Skiles said he no longer is amazed that players can come back so
quickly from such a serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''That stuff has come so far so fast,'' Skiles said. ''He's a
tough guy. He's been a quick healer before. He worked very hard in
rehab. It would have been very easy for him to just write the
season off. But he's had it in his head that he was going to make
it back, and we've survived long enough for him to be back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-02-00 2354 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
